/hyp-20260514-003-r1s2/formal/last_run-43013.log\\nPer-check logs in: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep3/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260514-003-r1s2/formal/riscv-formal/cores/bench-43013/checks/<check>/logfile.txt\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 1, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n","metadata":{"output":"{\"id\": \"baseline-bench-be29084\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T10:10:45.477521Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Guard ALU multipliers off critical path for non-M ops\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline ALU unconditionally computes three 64-bit products on every\\ncycle, even for simple ADD/SUB/AND/OR/XOR/SLT/SLTU/SLL/SRL/SRA/LUI\\noperations. On the Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-18C) these inferred multipliers\\nsit on the combinational critical path and limit Fmax. CoreMark is\\ndominated by integer ALU and memory ops, so the multiplier is almost\\nnever exercised, yet it still degrades timing for every other operation.\\nRemoving it from the critical path should raise Fmax with zero IPC risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline ALU unconditionally computes three 64-bit products on every\\ncycle, even for simple ADD/SUB/AND/OR/XOR/SLT/SLTU/SLL/SRL/SRA/LUI\\noperations. On the Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-18C) these inferred multipliers\\nsit on the combinational critical path and limit Fmax. CoreMark is\\ndominated by integer ALU and memory ops, so the multiplier is almost\\nnever exercised, yet it still degrades timing for every other operation.\\nRemoving it from the critical path should raise Fmax with zero IPC risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure alu.sv so the 64-bit multiply assignments (mul_ss, mul_uu,\\nmul_su) are only evaluated when the ALU operation is MUL, MULH, MULHU,\\nor MULHSU. For all other opcodes the products are tied to zero inside\\nthe always_comb block. This tells the synthesis tool that the multiplier\\nhardware is not needed on the fast-path case items (ADD, SUB, logic,\\nshifts, etc.), shortening the critical path and raising Fmax.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Guard the 64-bit multiply computations inside a conditional case block so they only execute for MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU ops. Default the product variables to zero so the main output case statement remains unchanged.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Guard the 64-bit multiply computations inside a conditional case block so they only execute for MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU ops. Default the product variables to zero so the main output case statement remains unchanged.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 315.22, \"delta_pct\": 11.46, \"vs_baseline\": 11.46, \"fmax_mhz\": 141.58, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10217, \"ff\": 1864, \"seeds\": [146.07, 134.99, 141.58], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T10:24:34.709300Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r1s0 (improvement, +11.46%): On inference FPGA targets, unconditionally computing wide multiply products inside the ALU keeps multiplier hardware on the combinational critical path for non-M opcodes; gating the multiply evaluation by opcode removes it from the fast path and raises Fmax with no IPC penalty.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Cold RV32M High-Half and Divide Unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline ALU unconditionally builds three independent 64-bit multiply\\nproducts (signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, signed*unsigned) and a\\ncombinational 32-bit divider on every cycle. This bloats area to ~9500 LUT4\\nand places heavy arithmetic on the EX-stage critical path for *all*\\ninstructions, even simple ADD or BRANCH. CoreMark's timed path is multiply-\\nheavy but only uses the low-half MUL result; it is effectively cold for\\nDIV/REM and high-half multiplies (MULH/MULHU/MULHSU). Prior work on similar\\nRV32IM baselines showed that moving cold division off the universal ALU path\\nwas one of the largest pure Fmax wins. Extending that idea to also remove the\\ntwo unused high-half multipliers should compound the area and timing benefit\\nwithout touching the benchmark's hot IPC path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline ALU unconditionally builds three independent 64-bit multiply\\nproducts (signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, signed*unsigned) and a\\ncombinational 32-bit divider on every cycle. This bloats area to ~9500 LUT4\\nand places heavy arithmetic on the EX-stage critical path for *all*\\ninstructions, even simple ADD or BRANCH. CoreMark's timed path is multiply-\\nheavy but only uses the low-half MUL result; it is effectively cold for\\nDIV/REM and high-half multiplies (MULH/MULHU/MULHSU). Prior work on similar\\nRV32IM baselines showed that moving cold division off the universal ALU path\\nwas one of the largest pure Fmax wins. Extending that idea to also remove the\\ntwo unused high-half multipliers should compound the area and timing benefit\\nwithout touching the benchmark's hot IPC path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure the EX stage into a fast single-cycle integer ALU plus a\\ndedicated cold Multiply-Divide Unit (MDU).\\n\\n- The ALU keeps ADD/SUB/logic/shift/compare/LUI and the existing single-\\n  cycle low-half MUL (mul_uu[31:0]). All other M-extension opcodes are\\n  removed from the ALU result mux.\\n- The new `rtl/mdu.sv` module handles the cold ops:\\n    * DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU using a 32-cycle iterative restoring divider.\\n    * MULH/MULHU/MULHSU using a 2-cycle pipelined 33x33 multiplier whose\\n      high-half result is captured in a registered output.\\n  The divider reuses the proven `div_unit.sv` state machine pattern from\\n  the reference v1 core, adapted for the bench baseline.\\n- `rtl/ex_stage.sv` detects a cold M-extension opcode and asserts a new\\n  `ex_long_busy` signal to the hazard unit, freezing the pipeline until the\\n  MDU signals `done`. On completion the MDU result is written into the\\n  EX/MEM register exactly like a normal ALU result.\\n- The ALTOPS branch in the MDU mirrors the formal substitutions already\\n  present in the baseline ALU, so `make formal` behavior is unchanged.\\n\\nCoreMark should see zero IPC penalty because its timed loop contains no\\nDIV/REM and no MULH variants, while the common RV32I and MUL instructions\\nnow run on a shorter critical path. LUT utilization should drop by\\n~1500-2500, relieving routing congestion and raising median Fmax.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and MULH/MULHU/MULHSU cases from the\\nmain result mux. Keep only the hot RV32I ops plus ALU_MUL (low half\\nof mul_uu). Add a cold-op indicator bit or reuse op[4] so EX stage\\ncan detect when the MDU is needed.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mdu.sv\", \"description\": \"New module: registered 2-cycle high-half multiplier for MULH/MULHU/\\nMULHSU plus a 32-cycle iterative divider for DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU.\\nIncludes start/busy/done handshake, ALTOPS substitutions under\\n`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS`, and exact RV32M corner-case handling.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate MDU, route operands to it, detect cold M-op via opcode\\nencoding, assert `ex_long_busy` while MDU is active, and select MDU\\nresult into EX/MEM when done.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept `ex_long_busy` alongside existing `dmem_ready` / `imem_ready`\\nstall sources. Treat MDU busy like a dmem stall: freeze IF/ID/EX\\nand bubble EX/MEM until the unit completes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new `ex_long_busy` signal from ex_stage into hazard_unit.\\nNo top-level IO changes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and MULH/MULHU/MULHSU cases from the\\nmain result mux. Keep only the hot RV32I ops plus ALU_MUL (low half\\nof mul_uu). Add a cold-op indicator bit or reuse op[4] so EX stage\\ncan detect when the MDU is needed.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mdu.sv\", \"description\": \"New module: registered 2-cycle high-half multiplier for MULH/MULHU/\\nMULHSU plus a 32-cycle iterative divider for DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU.\\nIncludes start/busy/done handshake, ALTOPS substitutions under\\n`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS`, and exact RV32M corner-case handling.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate MDU, route operands to it, detect cold M-op via opcode\\nencoding, assert `ex_long_busy` while MDU is active, and select MDU\\nresult into EX/MEM when done.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept `ex_long_busy` alongside existing `dmem_ready` / `imem_ready`\\nstall sources. Treat MDU busy like a dmem stall: freeze IF/ID/EX\\nand bubble EX/MEM until the unit completes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new `ex_long_busy` signal from ex_stage into hazard_unit.\\nNo top-level IO changes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T10:45:00.160423Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 1}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"32-entry 2-bit dynamic branch predictor in IF stage\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline always fetches pc+4 and only redirects after a branch resolves in EX,\\ncosting a 2-cycle bubble for every taken branch. CoreMark is loop-heavy; even a\\nsimple dynamic predictor eliminates most of these bubbles, directly improving IPC.\\nA 32-entry PHT adds only 64 flops and a small combinational read port, well within\\nthe ~400 LUT4 headroom on the Tang Nano 20K.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline always fetches pc+4 and only redirects after a branch resolves in EX,\\ncosting a 2-cycle bubble for every taken branch. CoreMark is loop-heavy; even a\\nsimple dynamic predictor eliminates most of these bubbles, directly improving IPC.\\nA 32-entry PHT adds only 64 flops and a small combinational read port, well within\\nthe ~400 LUT4 headroom on the Tang Nano 20K.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry 2-bit saturating counter branch predictor (PHT) indexed by PC[6:2].\\nIn the IF stage, detect conditional branches (opcode 1100011) and JAL (opcode 1101111);\\nextract the immediate via a small imm_gen instance and compute target = pc + imm.\\nQuery the PHT for branches; always predict JAL as taken. A new predict_taken bit is\\nadded to the IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles. In EX, redirect is asserted only on\\nmispredict (predicted != actual outcome), with the redirect target selecting the\\ncorrect path (branch target or pc+4). The PHT is updated when a branch resolves in EX.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predict_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline structs.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/branch_predictor.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-entry 2-bit saturating counter PHT module with async read and synchronous update.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add branch/JAL detection, imm_gen instance, target adder, and predictor integration to compute next_pc. Output predict_taken in IF/ID bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Pass predict_taken from IF/ID into the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change redirect logic to compare predicted vs actual outcome. Add predictor update output ports (update_en, update_pc, update_taken).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate branch_predictor, wire update signals from EX stage to predictor, and pass predict_taken through the pipeline.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predict_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline structs.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/branch_predictor.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-entry 2-bit saturating counter PHT module with async read and synchronous update.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add branch/JAL detection, imm_gen instance, target adder, and predictor integration to compute next_pc. Output predict_taken in IF/ID bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Pass predict_taken from IF/ID into the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change redirect logic to compare predicted vs actual outcome. Add predictor update output ports (update_en, update_pc, update_taken).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate branch_predictor, wire update signals from EX stage to predictor, a