{"type":"text","timestamp":1778758518286,"sessionID":"ses_1d9c3c473ffehCqw6PNuqEWnLH","part":{"id":"prt_e2644f41f001b278D4vEUxPgqn","messageID":"msg_e2644d84a001uh7TtBrtV11Zn9","sessionID":"ses_1d9c3c473ffehCqw6PNuqEWnLH","type":"text","text":"Done. I've written the hypothesis to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-001-r3s0.yaml`\n\n**Summary:** The hypothesis proposes **MEM-stage load forwarding** — exposing the combinational `load_data` from `mem_stage` and feeding it into the existing EX-stage forwarding path (via a top-level mux on `fwd_ex_mem`). Because `forward_unit` already selects `fwd_ex_mem` for any matching `rd` in the MEM stage, the dependent instruction in EX will receive the actual loaded value instead of the memory address, eliminating the need for the classic 1-cycle load-use stall. The `hazard_unit` is simplified to remove `load_use_hazard` entirely. This targets pure IPC improvement with minimal RTL churn and a contained timing-risk profile.","time":{"start":1778758513695,"end":1778758518285}}}
