{"type":"text","timestamp":1778772897797,"sessionID":"ses_1d8e760d8ffeIfbrvUr7QZfJPU","part":{"id":"prt_e27205ecb001YAY0S2gntLcVMG","messageID":"msg_e27204f9c001QrH3UPG3jetkAJ","sessionID":"ses_1d8e760d8ffeIfbrvUr7QZfJPU","type":"text","text":"Done. I wrote the hypothesis file at:\n\n**`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-001-r8s0.yaml`**\n\n### Hypothesis summary\n\n- **Title:** Split ALU into fast and M-extension paths with final 2:1 mux\n- **Category:** `micro_opt`\n- **Expected impact:** +3% fitness, medium confidence\n\n### Why this might work\n\nA prior successful hypothesis (+11.46%) proved that **gating multiplier evaluation** inside `alu.sv` removes multiplier hardware from the critical path of non-M ops. However, the ALU still selects its result through a single **19-entry `case` statement**. Even though the multipliers are gated, synthesis tools may still keep the large multiplier/divider outputs as inputs to the same output mux tree, adding load/delay to the fast path (ADD/SUB/LOGIC/SHIFT/SLT/LUI).\n\nBy explicitly splitting the ALU into:\n1. A **fast path** (11 base-integer ops → `fast_out`)\n2. A **guarded M-extension path** (MUL/DIV/REM → `m_out`)\n3. A final **2:1 mux** (`out = (op >= ALU_MUL) ? m_out : fast_out`)\n\n…the fast path sees a much smaller combinational cloud. This should shave a small amount off the critical path and raise Fmax with **zero IPC impact**.\n\n### What will change\n\n- **Only `rtl/alu.sv`** — restructure the single `always_comb` block into two parallel blocks plus a final ternary assignment. No other RTL files are touched.","time":{"start":1778772893387,"end":1778772897796}}}
