{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778780191472,"sessionID":"ses_1d875521dffeRFwpChqm8uVGYC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"rg 'hyp-20260514-002-r1s1' cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl -B 2 -A 80 | head -100","description":"Find hyp-20260514-002-r1s1 full record"},"output":"...output truncated...\n\nFull output saved to: /Users/bonetto/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_e278fbae90012WBjfO8ewFfMj1\n\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"8-entry PC-indexed BTB with isolated mispredict redirect\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline pays a 2-cycle flush penalty for every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause it always fetches PC+4.  Dynamic profiling shows CoreMark executes\\n~360k taken control-flow instructions out of ~2.9M total, so removing these\\nbubbles could cut ~720k cycles (~16% IPC gain).  Prior BTB attempts either\\nproduced zero delta (update path disconnected) or broke rvfi_pc_fwd because\\nthe implementation agent altered EX/MEM.pc_next to depend on prediction.\\nA tiny 8-entry BTB indexed directly by the PC register avoids the slow\\nimem_data-decode path that killed an earlier static predictor's Fmax, and\\nkeeping the BTB inline in if_stage makes it impossible to forget to\\ninstantiate a separate module.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline pays a 2-cycle flush penalty for every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause it always fetches PC+4.  Dynamic profiling shows CoreMark executes\\n~360k taken control-flow instructions out of ~2.9M total, so removing these\\nbubbles could cut ~720k cycles (~16% IPC gain).  Prior BTB attempts either\\nproduced zero delta (update path disconnected) or broke rvfi_pc_fwd because\\nthe implementation agent altered EX/MEM.pc_next to depend on prediction.\\nA tiny 8-entry BTB indexed directly by the PC register avoids the slow\\nimem_data-decode path that killed an earlier static predictor's Fmax, and\\nkeeping the BTB inline in if_stage makes it impossible to forget to\\ninstantiate a separate module.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an 8-entry direct-mapped branch-target buffer inline in if_stage.sv,\\nindexed by pc[4:2] with a 27-bit tag (pc[31:5]).  Combinational read produces\\nbtb_hit and btb_target.  Only BRANCH (opcode 1100011) and JAL (opcode\\n1101111) are eligible for prediction; JALR is excluded.  The IF next-pc mux\\nbecomes:\\n  next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target :\\n            (btb_hit && is_branch_or_jal) ? btb_target : pc + 4;\\nThis EXPLICITLY PRESERVES the existing redirect path; prediction is an\\noverlay, not a replacement.\\n\\nPass a single predict_taken bit through if_id_t / id_ex_t.  In ex_stage.sv\\nchange redirect to mispredict-only with SEPARATE branch and jump terms so\\nthat JAL (always taken) is never falsely compared against branch_taken:\\n  branch_mispredict = ctrl.is_branch && (branch_taken != predict_taken);\\n  jump_mispredict   = ctrl.is_jump   && !predict_taken;\\n  redirect          = (branch_mispredict || jump_mispredict) && !misalign_fault;\\nThe EX/MEM pc_next field MUST continue to be computed from actual branch/\\njump resolution exactly as in the baseline, independent of predict_taken.\\nOnly the redirect signal changes.\\n\\nThe BTB is updated in the cycle a branch resolves taken or a JAL executes,\\nstoring redirect_target at pc[4:2].  ex_stage.sv exposes combinational\\nbtb_update / btb_update_idx / btb_update_tag / btb_update_target outputs;\\ncore.sv wires them back to if_stage.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a single `logic predict_taken` field to `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t`\\npipeline bundles so the prediction travels with the instruction.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"1. Add 8-entry BTB arrays: `btb_valid[0:7]`, `btb_tag[0:7][26:0]`,\\n   `btb_data[0:7][31:0]`.\\n2. Combinational read indexed by `pc[4:2]`; hit when valid and tag\\n   matches `pc[31:5]`.\\n3. Detect `is_branch = (imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1100011)` and\\n   `is_jal = (imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111)`.  Eligible prediction\\n   only when `btb_hit && (is_branch || is_jal)`.\\n4. Drive `out.predict_taken = btb_hit && (is_branch || is_jal)`.\\n5. Change `next_pc` to:\\n     `redirect ? redirect_target :\\n      (predict_taken ? btb_target : pc + 32'd4)`\\n   This keeps the existing `redirect` path untouched.\\n6. Add registered BTB update inputs (`btb_update`, `btb_update_idx[2:0]`,\\n   `btb_update_tag[26:0]`, `btb_update_target[31:0]`).  On update,\\n   write valid=1, tag, and target into the indexed entry.\\n7. Keep all existing I-cache logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"1. Read `in.predict_taken` from the ID/EX register.\\n2. Compute mispredict with separate branch and jump arms:\\n     `branch_mispredict = in.ctrl.is_branch && (branch_taken != in.predict_taken);`\\n     `jump_mispredict   = in.ctrl.is_jump   && !in.predict_taken;`\\n     `redirect          = (branch_mispredict || jump_mispredict) && !misalign_fault;`\\n3. Leave `redirect_target` exactly as baseline:\\n     `redirect_target = in.ctrl.is_jump ? jump_target : branch_target;`\\n4. Leave the EX/MEM `pc_next` register assignment exactly as baseline\\n   (actual outcome, not prediction).  DO NOT tie pc_next to `redirect`.\\n5. Add combinational outputs:\\n     `btb_update        = (in.ctrl.is_branch && branch_taken) || in.ctrl.is_jal;`\\n     `btb_update_idx    = in.pc[4:2];`\\n     `btb_update_tag    = in.pc[31:5];`\\n     `btb_update_target = redirect_target;`\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"1. Wire the new `btb_update*` outputs from `u_ex` to the new\\n   `btb_update*` inputs on `u_if` so the BTB is updated when branches\\n   or JALs resolve.\\n2. No other top-level changes needed; `predict_taken` flows through the\\n   existing struct connections.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a single `logic predict_taken` field to `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t`\\npipeline bundles so the prediction travels with the instruction.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"1. Add 8-entry BTB arrays: `btb_valid[0:7]`, `btb_tag[0:7][26:0]`,\\n   `btb_data[0:7][31:0]`.\\n2. Combinational read indexed by `pc[4:2]`; hit when valid and tag\\n   matches `pc[31:5]`.\\n3. Detect `is_branch = (imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1100011)` and\\n   `is_jal = (imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111)`.  Eligible prediction\\n   only when `btb_hit && (is_branch || is_jal)`.\\n4. Drive `out.predict_taken = btb_hit && (is_branch || is_jal)`.\\n5. Change `next_pc` to:\\n     `redirect ? redirect_target :\\n      (predict_taken ? btb_target : pc + 32'd4)`\\n   This keeps the existing `redirect` path untouched.\\n6. Add registered BTB update inputs (`btb_update`, `btb_update_idx[2:0]`,\\n   `btb_update_tag[26:0]`, `btb_update_target[31:0]`).  On update,\\n   write valid=1, tag, and target into the indexed entry.\\n7. Keep all existing I-cache logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"1. Read `in.predict_taken` from the ID/EX register.\\n2. Compute mispredict with separate branch and jump arms:\\n     `branch_mispredict = in.ctrl.is_branch && (branch_taken != in.predict_taken);`\\n     `jump_mispredict   = in.ctrl.is_jump   && !in.predict_taken;`\\n     `redirect          = (branch_mispredict || jump_mispredict) && !misalign_fault;`\\n3. Leave `redirect_target` exactly as baseline:\\n     `redirect_target = in.ctrl.is_jump ? jump_target : branch_target;`\\n4. Leave the EX/MEM `pc_next` register assignment exactly as baseline\\n   (actual outcome, not prediction).  DO NOT tie pc_next to `redirect`.\\n5. Add combinational outputs:\\n     `btb_update        = (in.ctrl.is_branch && branch_taken) || in.ctrl.is_jal;`\\n     `btb_update_idx    = in.pc[4:2];`\\n     `btb_update_tag    = in.pc[31:5];`\\n     `btb_update_target = redirect_target;`\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"1. Wire the new `btb_update*` outputs from `u_ex` to the new\\n   `btb_update*` inputs on `u_if` so the BTB is updated when branches\\n   or JALs resolve.\\n2. No other top-level changes needed; `predict_taken` flows through the\\n   existing struct connections.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 334.35, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 18.22, \"fmax_mhz\": 139.7, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4178194, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9980, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [139.7, 149.25, 136.74], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T15:10:16.584625Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 7, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r7s2 (regression, +0.00%): A tiny 8-entry direct-mapped BTB thrashes continuously on CoreMark's many active branch/jump sites; the mispredicts caused by aliasing evictions consume exactly the cycles saved by rare correct predictions, neutralizing any IPC gain over the always-not-taken baseline.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Split ALU into fast and M-extension paths with final 2:1 mux\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"A prior hypothesis proved that gating multiply evaluation inside alu.sv\\nraises Fmax by removing multiplier hardware from the critical path of\\nnon-M ops.  However, the ALU still selects its result through a single\\n19-entry case statement where the large multiplier/divider outputs are\\ninputs to the same mux tree as the fast ADD/SUB/LOGIC/SHIFT ops.\\nSynthesis tools may not fully prune those heavy inputs from the fast-path\\nmux delay.  By explicitly separating the ALU into a fast path (ADD/SUB/\\nLOGIC/SHIFT/SLT/LUI) and a slow M-extension path (MUL/DIV/REM) and\\nselecting between them with a single 2:1 mux, the fast path sees a much\\nsmaller combinational cloud and should achieve a slightly higher Fmax\\nwith zero IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"A prior hypothesis proved that gating multiply evaluation inside alu.sv\\nraises Fmax by removing multiplier hardware from the critical path of\\nnon-M ops.  However, the ALU still selects its result through a single\\n19-entry case statement where the large multiplier/divider outputs are\\ninputs to the same mux tree as the fast ADD/SUB/LOGIC/SHIFT ops.\\nSynthesis tools may not fully prune those heavy inputs from the fast-path\\nmux delay.  By explicitly separating the ALU into a fast path (ADD/SUB/\\nLOGIC/SHIFT/SLT/LUI) and a slow M-extension path (MUL/DIV/REM) and\\nselecting between them with a single 2:1 mux, the fast path sees a much\\nsmaller combinational cloud and should achieve a slightly higher Fmax\\nwith zero IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure rtl/alu.sv so that:\\n1. A \\\"fast\\\" always_comb block computes ADD, SUB, AND, OR, XOR, SLT,\\n   SLTU, SLL, SRL, SRA, and LUI into a local `fast_out` variable.\\n2. A separate \\\"muldiv\\\" always_comb block (guarded by the existing\\n   opcode if-gate) computes the 64-bit products and DIV/REM results\\n   into a local `m_out` variable.\\n3. A final assignment `out = (op >= ALU_MUL) ? m_out : fast_out;`\\n   drives the output through a single 2:1 mux instead of a 19:1 case\\n   statement.  This keeps the ALTOPS branch intact and does not change\\n   any bit-level results.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Split the single always_comb block into a fast path for base-integer\\nops, a guarded M-extension path, and a final 2:1 mux.  The fast path\\nuses a smaller case statement (11 entries) and the M path keeps the\\nexisting guarded multiply/divide logic.  No other files are touched.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Split the single always_comb block into a fast path for base-integer\\nops, a guarded M-extension path, and a final 2:1 mux.  The fast path\\nuses a smaller case statement (11 entries) and the M path keeps the\\nexisting guarded multiply/divide logic.  No other files are touched.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 396.13, \"delta_pct\": 18.48, \"vs_baseline\": 40.06, \"fmax_mhz\": 165.51, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4178194, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9927, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [153.54, 165.51, 166.97], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T15:52:25.889516Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 8, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r8s0 (improvement, +18.48%): Opcode gating alone does not fully remove multiplier/divider inputs from the fast-path mux tree when heavy and light ops share a large case statement; explicitly splitting the ALU into fast and M-extension paths with a final 2:1 mux is required to truly shorten the critical path for base integer ops.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-002-r8s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r8s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r8s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r8s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 8}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"2-entry return-address stack for JALR prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline pays a 2-cycle flush bubble for every taken JALR (function return).\\nCoreMark is call-heavy, so returns are a significant fraction of dynamic control flow.\\nPrior BTB attempts either thrashed (8-entry) or were synthesized away (implementation bugs),\\nand static BTFN predictors destroyed Fmax by adding an imem_data->adder->next_pc critical path.\\nA tiny 2-entry RAS predicts returns with near-perfect accuracy, avoids an IF-stage adder entirely,\\nand targets a different instruction class (returns vs branches) than all previous predictor attempts.\\nCorrectly predicted returns eliminate the flush bubble, directly improving IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline pays a 2-cycle flush bubble for every taken JALR (function return).\\nCoreMark is call-heavy, so returns are a significant fraction of dynamic control flow.\\nPrior BTB attempts either thrashed (8-entry) or were synthesized away (implementation bugs),\\nand static BTFN predictors destroyed Fmax by adding an imem_data->adder->next_pc critical path.\\nA tiny 2-entry RAS predicts returns with near-perfect accuracy, avoids an IF-stage adder entirely,\\nand targets a different instruction class (returns vs branches) than all previous predictor attempts.\\nCorrectly predicted returns eliminate the flush bubble, directly improving IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 2-entry Return Address Stack (RAS) in core.sv and change EX-stage redirect to\\nmispredict-only so that correct return predictions do not flush the pipeline.\\n\\n1. RAS logic in core.sv (top level, no new module):\\n   - Detect push:  jal with rd==ra  (opcode 1101111, instr[11:7]==1).\\n   - Detect pop/predict: jalr with rs1==ra (opcode 1100111, instr[19:15]==1).\\n   - Two 32-bit registers (ras_top, ras_next) plus pointer implied by the swap.\\n   - On push: ras_next <= ras_top; ras_top <= io_imemAddr + 32'd4.\\n   - On pop:  ras_top <= ras_next.\\n   - Updates are gated by !ex_redirect && !flush_if && !stall_if so wrong-path\\n     instructions during flushes do not corrupt the stack.\\n   - ras_predict = is_jalr_ra && !ex_redirect && !flush_if && !stall_if.\\n   - ras_target  = ras_top.\\n\\n2. Redirect muxing in core.sv:\\n   - Keep the raw ex_redirect / ex_redirect_target wires from ex_stage.\\n   - Drive if_stage inputs with combined signals:\\n       if_redirect       = ex_redirect || ras_predict;\\n       if_redirect_target = ras_predict ? ras_target : ex_redirect_target;\\n   - Hazard unit MUST continue to receive the raw ex_redirect (not the combined\\n     signal) so that correct predictions do not spuriously flush IF/ID.\\n   - Create an intermediate if_id_t signal from if_stage output, override\\n     predict_taken = ras_predict and predicted_target = ras_target, then feed\\n     that to id_stage.  This keeps the RAS out of the timing-critical if_stage\\n     next-pc path and avoids pc_fwd violations.\\n\\n3. Pipeline-bundle extension in core_pkg.sv:\\n   - Add `logic predict_taken;` and `logic [31:0] predicted_target;` to both\\n     `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t`.\\n\\n4. ID stage capture in id_stage.sv:\\n   - In the ID/EX register always_ff, capture:\\n       reg_q.predict_taken    <= in.predict_taken;\\n       reg_q.predicted_target <= in.predicted_target;\\n\\n5. EX-stage mispredict logic in ex_stage.sv:\\n   - Keep the existing redirect_target and pc_next assignments UNCHANGED.\\n     (This is the #1 source of prior pc_fwd failures; do not touch them.)\\n   - Add:\\n       logic actual_taken = in.ctrl.is_jump || branch_taken;\\n       logic target_mismatch = in.ctrl.is_jump &&\\n                               ({jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0} != in.predicted_target);\\n       assign redirect = ((actual_taken != in.predict_taken) ||\\n                          (in.predict_taken && target_mismatch)) && !misalign_fault;\\n   - For baseline behavior (predict_taken=0, predicted_target=0) this collapses\\n     to the original redirect expression.\\n   - On a correctly predicted return, redirect stays low and the pipeline\\n     continues fetching from the return address without a bubble.\\n   - On a RAS miss, EX asserts redirect to the true jump target and the\\n     hazard unit flushes IF/ID as usual.\\n\\nCost estimate: ~65 LUTs (32 for the redirect_target mux, ~31 for the 32-bit\\nequality comparator in EX, plus decode/control).  Previous cores with ~10200\\nLUTs still evaluated successfully, so the modest area increase is acceptable\\nfor the IPC gain.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `logic predict_taken;` and `logic [31:0] predicted_target;`\\nto both `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t` pipeline bundles.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Add the 2-entry RAS (ras_top, ras_next), push/pop decode from io_imemData,\\nras_predict / ras_target generation, combined redirect mux\\n(if_redirect = ex_redirect || ras_predict; if_redirect_target muxed),\\nfeed raw ex_redirect to hazard_unit.redirect, and override predict_taken\\n/ predicted_target on the if_id_t path to id_stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.predict_taken and in.predicted_target into the ID/EX register.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-bit equality comparator between the resolved jump target\\n({jalr_sum[31:1],1'b0}) and in.predicted_target.  Change redirect to\\nmispredict-only: ((actual_taken != predict_taken) ||\\n(predict_taken && target_mismatch)) && !misalign_fault.\\nDO NOT modify pc_next, redirect_target, or any other EX logic.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `logic predict_taken;` and `logic [31:0] predicted_target;`\\nto both `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t` pipeline bundles.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Add the 2-entry RAS (ras_top, ras_next), push/pop decode from io_imemData,\\nras_predict / ras_target generation, combined redirect mux\\n(if_redirect = ex_redirect || ras_predict; if_redirect_target muxed),\\nfeed raw ex_redirect to hazard_unit.redirect, and override predict_taken\\n/ predicted_target on the if_id_t path to id_stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.predict_taken and in.predicted_target into the ID/EX register.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-bit equality comparator between the resolved jump target\\n({jalr_sum[31:1],1'b0}) and in.predicted_target.  Change redirect to\\nmispredict-only: ((actual_taken != predict_taken) ||\\n(predict_taken && target_mismatch)) && !misalign_fault.\\nDO NOT modify pc_next, redirect_target, or any other EX logic.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 169.08, \"delta_pct\": -49.43, \"vs_baseline\": -40.22, \"fmax_mhz\": 70.4, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4163814, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10352, \"ff\": 1959, \"seeds\": [70.4, 63.32, 73.15], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T16:17:13.429883Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 8, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"JAL pre-decode in IF to eliminate unconditional jump bubbles\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Every JAL currently costs a one-cycle bubble: while JAL travels through ID,\\nthe IF stage blindly fetches PC+4; when JAL reaches EX it redirects, flushing\\nthe wrongly fetched instruction.  JAL is unconditional and its target is\\nknown the moment the instruction is fetched (PC + J-immediate).  Since there\\nis no mispredict possibility for aligned JAL, the IF stage can safely jump\\nimmediately, removing the bubble entirely without any prediction state or\\nrecovery logic.  This improves IPC for all function calls with no risk of\\nmispredict penalties.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Every JAL currently costs a one-cycle bubble: while JAL travels through ID,\\nthe IF stage blindly fetches PC+4; when JAL reaches EX it redirects, flushing\\nthe wrongly fetched instruction.  JAL is unconditional and its target is\\nknown the moment the instruction is fetched (PC + J-immediate).  Since there\\nis no mispredict possibility for aligned JAL, the IF stage can safely jump\\nimmediately, removing the bubble entirely without any prediction state or\\nrecovery logic.  This improves IPC for all function calls with no risk of\\nmispredict penalties.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add combinational JAL detection and target computation inside if_stage.sv.\\nWhen the instruction being emitted to ID is a JAL and its computed target is\\naligned, override next_pc with the JAL target instead of PC+4.  The PC\\nregister updates to the target in the same cycle JAL enters ID, so the\\npipeline fetches the target instruction one cycle earlier.  In ex_stage.sv,\\nsuppress the redirect signal for JAL (keep it only for branches and JALR);\\nbecause IF already fetched the correct target, there is nothing to flush.\\nMisaligned JAL falls back to PC+4 in IF, preserving the baseline trap-and-\\nfallthrough semantics in EX.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"In the combinational always_comb block that drives out.*, add:\\n  1. JAL opcode detection: is_jal = (out.instr[6:0] == 7'b1101111).\\n  2. J-immediate extraction from out.instr:\\n       jal_imm = {{11{out.instr[31]}}, out.instr[31], out.instr[19:12],\\n                  out.instr[20], out.instr[30:21], 1'b0};\\n  3. Target adder: jal_target = pc + jal_imm.\\n  4. next_pc mux:\\n       next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target\\n               : (is_jal && (jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00)) ? jal_target\\n               : pc + 32'd4;\\nDeclare is_jal, jal_imm, and jal_target as local logic signals.\\nDo NOT remove or alter the existing I-cache, flush, or stall logic.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change the redirect assignment so JAL does not assert redirect:\\n  assign redirect = (branch_taken || (in.ctrl.is_jump && in.ctrl.is_jalr))\\n                    && !misalign_fault;\\nLeave redirect_target, jump_target, branch_target, jalr_sum, and the\\nEX/MEM always_ff block completely unchanged.  JAL still computes\\npc_next = jump_target and alu_result = pc+4 in the register block as\\nbefore; the only difference is that EX no longer flushes the pipeline\\nfor aligned JAL because IF already redirected.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"In the combinational always_comb block that drives out.*, add:\\n  1. JAL opcode detection: is_jal = (out.instr[6:0] == 7'b1101111).\\n  2. J-immediate extraction from out.instr:\\n       jal_imm = {{11{out.instr[31]}}, out.instr[31], out.instr[19:12],\\n                  out.instr[20], out.instr[30:21], 1'b0};\\n  3. Target adder: jal_target = pc + jal_imm.\\n  4. next_pc mux:\\n       next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target\\n               : (is_jal && (jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00)) ? jal_target\\n               : pc + 32'd4;\\nDeclare is_jal, jal_imm, and jal_target as local logic signals.\\nDo NOT remove or alter the existing I-cache, flush, or stall logic.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change the redirect assignment so JAL does not assert redirect:\\n  assign redirect = (branch_taken || (in.ctrl.is_jump && in.ctrl.is_jalr))\\n                    && !misalign_fault;\\nLeave redirect_target, jump_target, branch_target, jalr_sum, and the\\nEX/MEM always_ff block completely unchanged.  JAL still computes\\npc_next = jump_target and alu_result = pc+4 in the register block as\\nbefore; the only difference is that EX no longer flushes the pipeline\\nfor aligned JAL because IF already redirected.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 396.13, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 40.06, \"fmax_mhz\": 165.51, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4178194, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9927, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [153.54, 165.51, 166.97], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T16:39:40.877429Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 9, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-002-r9s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r9s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r9s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r9s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 9}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"ICache-integrated JAL and backward-branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline flushes IF/ID on every taken JAL and backward branch, costing 2 cycles each.\\nPrior predictor attempts failed for three reasons: an 8-entry standalone BTB thrashed on\\nCoreMark's many active sites (0% IPC gain), a 2-entry RAS decoded io_imemData in core.sv\\nand fed it back to IF (Fmax crashed to 70 MHz), and a BTFN static predictor broke\\nrvfi_pc_fwd by altering EX-stage pc_next.  The existing 8-entry I-cache already stores\\ninstructions indexed by PC with tag match.  Extending each entry with a single valid bit\\nand a 32-bit target reuses the cache's fast read path, stays entirely inside IF, avoids\\nany combinational decode of external imemData, and costs only ~50 LUT4s.  By predicting\\nonly unconditional JAL and backward branches\\u2014whose targets are stable and highly\\nrepetitive in loop-heavy CoreMark\\u2014we avoid the aliasing thrashing that neutralized the\\nprior BTB, while mispredict-only redirect keeps EX's architectural pc_next completely\\nunchanged, preserving rvfi_pc_fwd.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline flushes IF/ID on every taken JAL and backward branch, costing 2 cycles each.\\nPrior predictor attempts failed for three reasons: an 8-entry standalone BTB thrashed on\\nCoreMark's many active sites (0% IPC gain), a 2-entry RAS decoded io_imemData in core.sv\\nand fed it back to IF (Fmax crashed to 70 MHz), and a BTFN static predictor broke\\nrvfi_pc_fwd by altering EX-stage pc_next.  The existing 8-entry I-cache already stores\\ninstructions indexed by PC with tag match.  Extending each entry with a single valid bit\\nand a 32-bit target reuses the cache's fast read path, stays entirely inside IF, avoids\\nany combinational decode of external imemData, and costs only ~50 LUT4s.  By predicting\\nonly unconditional JAL and backward branches\\u2014whose targets are stable and highly\\nrepetitive in loop-heavy CoreMark\\u2014we avoid the aliasing thrashing that neutralized the\\nprior BTB, while mispredict-only redirect keeps EX's architectural pc_next completely\\nunchanged, preserving rvfi_pc_fwd.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Integrate a tiny JAL + backward-branch target predictor into the existing 8-entry I-cache.\\nEach cache entry gains `pred_valid` (1 bit) and `pred_target[31:0]`.  `pred_valid` is\\ncleared on every cache refill and set only by EX when a JAL or taken backward branch\\nresolves, storing the resolved target.\\n\\nIn `if_stage`, on a cache hit, the cached instruction is decoded locally (opcode and\\nsign bit) to decide eligibility:\\n  `is_jal      = (icache_data[cache_idx][6:0] == 7'b1101111)`\\n  `is_branch   = (icache_data[cache_idx][6:0] == 7'b1100011)`\\n  `is_backward = icache_data[cache_idx][31]`\\n  `predict_taken = icache_hit && pred_valid[cache_idx] && !flush && !redirect &&\\n                   (is_jal || (is_branch && is_backward))`\\n`next_pc` becomes `redirect ? redirect_target :\\n                   predict_taken ? pred_target[cache_idx] : pc + 32'd4`.\\nBecause the predictor reads registered state and reuses the existing cache hit signal,\\nit does not create the long combinational io_imemData path that destroyed the RAS Fmax.\\n\\nA single `predict_taken` bit is added to `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t` and captured by\\n`id_stage`.  In `ex_stage` redirect changes to mispredict-only:\\n  `actual_taken = in.ctrl.is_jump || branch_taken`\\n  `redirect     = (!in.predict_taken && actual_taken && !misalign_fault) ||\\n                  ( in.predict_taken && (!actual_taken || misalign_fault))`\\n  `redirect_target = misalign_fault          ? (in.pc + 32'd4) :\\n                     !actual_taken           ? (in.pc + 32'd4) :\\n                     in.ctrl.is_jump         ? jump_target :\\n                                               branch_target`\\nThe EX/MEM `pc_next` assignment is left completely untouched, guaranteeing rvfi_pc_fwd.\\nEX also drives combinational update outputs back to IF:\\n  `pred_update       = (in.ctrl.is_jump && !in.ctrl.is_jalr) ||\\n                       (in.ctrl.is_branch && branch_taken && in.imm[31])`\\n  `pred_update_idx   = in.pc[4:2]`\\n  `pred_update_tag   = in.pc[31:5]`\\n  `pred_update_target = redirect_target`\\n`core.sv` wires the update path and passes `predict_taken` through the struct bundles.\\nThe hazard unit needs no changes\\u2014its `redirect` input naturally flushes on mispredict\\nonly, which is exactly the desired behavior.\\n\\nCost estimate: ~50 LUT4s and 264 FFs.  Fmax should stay near the current ~165 MHz\\nbecause the critical path remains in the ALU fast path and the IF loop sees only a\\nslightly wider next-pc mux.  IPC should rise 5-10 % by eliminating bubbles on the\\nmost frequent control-flow patterns in CoreMark.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `logic predict_taken;` to `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t` pipeline bundles.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `pred_valid[0:7]` and `pred_target[0:7][31:0]` arrays plus `pred_update*`\\ninputs.  Combinational prediction uses the cached instruction opcode/sign bit\\ngated by `icache_hit` and `pred_valid`.  `next_pc` becomes a 3:1 mux choosing\\nredirect_target, pred_target, or pc+4.  Clear `pred_valid` on every cache refill\\nand write it (along with target) on `pred_update`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture `in.predict_taken` into the ID/EX register.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Read `in.predict_taken`.  Replace unconditional redirect with mispredict-only\\nredirect using `actual_taken`.  Compute `redirect_target` so that misaligned or\\nnot-taken predicted branches redirect to pc+4.  Leave the EX/MEM `pc_next`\\nregister assignment completely unchanged.  Add `pred_update` combinational\\noutputs that fire for JAL or taken backward branches.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire `pred_update*` from `u_ex` to `u_if`.  Pass `predict_taken` through the\\nexisting `if_id_t` connection to `u_id`.  No other top-level changes needed.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `logic predict_taken;` to `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t` pipeline bundles.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `pred_valid[0:7]` and `pred_target[0:7][31:0]` arrays plus `pred_update*`\\ninputs.  Combinational prediction uses the cached instruction opcode/sign bit\\ngated by `icache_hit` and `pred_valid`.  `next_pc` becomes a 3:1 mux choosing\\nredirect_target, pred_target, or pc+4.  Clear `pred_valid` on every cache refill\\nand write it (along with target) on `pred_update`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture `in.predict_taken` into the ID/EX register.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Read `in.predict_taken`.  Replace unconditional redirect with mispredict-only\\nredirect using `actual_taken`.  Compute `redirect_target` so that misaligned or\\nnot-taken predicted branches redirect to pc+4.  Leave the EX/MEM `pc_next`\\nregister assignment completely unchanged.  Add `pred_update` combinational\\noutputs that fire for JAL or taken backward branches.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire `pred_update*` from `u_ex` to `u_if`.  Pass `predict_taken` through the\\nexisting `if_id_t` connection to `u_id`.  No other top-level changes needed.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 396.13, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 40.06, \"fmax_mhz\": 165.51, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4178194, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9927, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [153.54, 165.51, 166.97], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T16:58:37.251660Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 9, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 10, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench ALU currently computes three separate 32\\u00d732 products\\n(signed\\u00d7signed, unsigned\\u00d7unsigned, signed\\u00d7unsigned). Yosys does not\\nmerge them, so the design pays for three multipliers worth of DSP/LUT\\narea.  With LUT4 already at 9927/10000, placement congestion is severe\\nand likely limits the achievable Fmax of the fast integer path.\\nRemoving two of the three multipliers frees substantial area without\\nchanging IPC or adding pipeline stages.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace mul_ss, mul_uu and mul_su with a single unsigned\\u00d7unsigned\\nproduct.  MUL/MULHU reuse the low/high halves directly.  MULH and\\nMULHSU high halves are recovered with a cheap 32-bit correction\\nsubtractor: MULHSU subtracts b when a is negative; MULH additionally\\nsubtracts a when b is negative.  The ALTOPS formal branch and the\\ndivider path are untouched, and the fast-path 2:1 mux is preserved.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Collapse three multipliers into one unsigned product; add correction subtractors for MULH/MULHSU high halves.\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-002-r10s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r10s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r10s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r10s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 10}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"ICache-integrated JAL/backward-branch predictor with tag-matched retention\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline with an 8-entry I-cache and ALU fast path achieves 396.13 fitness,\\nbut still flushes IF/ID on every taken JAL and backward branch, costing two cycles.\\nA prior attempt to integrate target prediction into the I-cache (hyp-20260514-003-r9s2)\\nproduced exactly 0 % delta because the predictor valid bit was cleared on every\\ncache refill, so predictions were never visible when the branch PC was fetched again.\\nBy storing a partial tag with each prediction entry and qualifying the hit with\\ntag equality, the predictor state survives across repeated fetches and evictions\\nwithout needing explicit invalidation logic.  This reuses the existing fast I-cache\\nread path (registered state, no external imem_data combinational delay) and adds\\nonly ~250 FFs and a small next-pc mux, well within the remaining LUT4 headroom.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline with an 8-entry I-cache and ALU fast path achieves 396.13 fitness,\\nbut still flushes IF/ID on every taken JAL and backward branch, costing two cycles.\\nA prior attempt to integrate target prediction into the I-cache (hyp-20260514-003-r9s2)\\nproduced exactly 0 % delta because the predictor valid bit was cleared on every\\ncache refill, so predictions were never visible when the branch PC was fetched again.\\nBy storing a partial tag with each prediction entry and qualifying the hit with\\ntag equality, the predictor state survives across repeated fetches and evictions\\nwithout needing explicit invalidation logic.  This reuses the existing fast I-cache\\nread path (registered state, no external imem_data combinational delay) and adds\\nonly ~250 FFs and a small next-pc mux, well within the remaining LUT4 headroom.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the existing 8-entry I-cache in if_stage.sv with a tiny target predictor:\\n- Add `pred_valid[0:7]`, `pred_tag[0:7][26:0]`, and `pred_target[0:7][31:0]`.\\n- Combinational prediction (no imem_data in the path):\\n    `is_jal      = (icache_data[cache_idx][6:0] == 7'b1101111)`\\n    `is_branch   = (icache_data[cache_idx][6:0] == 7'b1100011)`\\n    `is_backward = icache_data[cache_idx][31]`\\n    `predict_taken = icache_hit && pred_valid[cache_idx] &&\\n                     (pred_tag[cache_idx] == cache_tag) &&\\n                     !flush && !redirect &&\\n                     (is_jal || (is_branch && is_backward))`\\n    `next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target :\\n               predict_taken ? pred_target[cache_idx] : pc + 32'd4;`\\n- In ex_stage, change redirect to mispredict-only and expose update outputs:\\n    `actual_taken    = in.ctrl.is_jump || branch_taken;`\\n    `redirect        = ((!in.predict_taken && actual_taken) ||\\n                        (in.predict_taken && (!actual_taken || misalign_fault)))\\n                       && !misalign_fault;`\\n    `redirect_target = misalign_fault          ? (in.pc + 32'd4) :\\n                       !actual_taken           ? (in.pc + 32'd4) :\\n                       in.ctrl.is_jump         ? jump_target :\\n                                                 branch_target;`\\n    `pred_update       = !misalign_fault && in.valid &&\\n                         ((in.ctrl.is_jump && !in.ctrl.is_jalr) ||\\n                          (in.ctrl.is_branch && branch_taken && in.imm[31]));`\\n    `pred_update_idx   = in.pc[4:2];`\\n    `pred_update_tag   = in.pc[31:5];`\\n    `pred_update_target = redirect_target;`\\n- Leave the EX/MEM `pc_next` register assignment completely untouched so\\n  rvfi_pc_fwd stays correct.\\n- In core.sv, wire the four `pred_update*` outputs from u_ex into new inputs\\n  on u_if, and pass `predict_taken` through the existing struct bundles.\\n- Reset clears all `pred_valid`; EX updates set `pred_valid`+`pred_tag`+`pred_target`\\n  synchronously.  No eviction-clear logic is required because the tag match\\n  suppresses stale entries automatically.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a single `logic predict_taken;` field to `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t`\\npipeline bundles so the prediction flag travels with the instruction.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"1. Add `pred_valid[0:7]`, `pred_tag[0:7][26:0]`, `pred_target[0:7][31:0]` arrays.\\n2. On reset clear all `pred_valid`.\\n3. Accept new inputs `pred_update`, `pred_update_idx[2:0]`,\\n   `pred_update_tag[26:0]`, `pred_update_target[31:0]`.\\n4. On `pred_update` write `pred_valid[pred_update_idx] <= 1'b1`,\\n   `pred_tag[pred_update_idx] <= pred_update_tag`,\\n   `pred_target[pred_update_idx] <= pred_update_target`.\\n5. Combinational prediction uses the cached instruction opcode/sign bit\\n   gated by `icache_hit`, `pred_valid`, and tag equality.\\n6. `next_pc` becomes a 3:1 mux: redirect_target, pred_target, or pc+4.\\n7. Drive `out.predict_taken` with the combinational prediction signal.\\n8. Keep all existing I-cache logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture `in.predict_taken` into the ID/EX register so it reaches EX stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"1. Read `in.predict_taken`.\\n2. Replace unconditional redirect with mispredict-only redirect using\\n   `actual_taken` and `misalign_fault` exactly as specified.\\n3. Drive `redirect_target` so a predicted-taken / not-taken mispredict\\n   recovers to pc+4.\\n4. Leave the EX/MEM `pc_next` register assignment completely untouched.\\n5. Add combinational `pred_update*` outputs that fire for JAL or taken\\n   backward branches, gated by `!misalign_fault && in.valid`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the four `pred_update*` outputs from `u_ex` to the new inputs on\\n`u_if`.  Pass `predict_taken` through the existing `if_id_t` connection\\nto `u_id`.  No other top-level changes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a single `logic predict_taken;` field to `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t`\\npipeline bundles so the prediction flag travels with the instruction.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"1. Add `pred_valid[0:7]`, `pred_tag[0:7][26:0]`, `pred_target[0:7][31:0]` arrays.\\n2. On reset clear all `pred_valid`.\\n3. Accept new inputs `pred_update`, `pred_update_idx[2:0]`,\\n   `pred_update_tag[26:0]`, `pred_update_target[31:0]`.\\n4. On `pred_update` write `pred_valid[pred_update_idx] <= 1'b1`,\\n   `pred_tag[pred_update_idx] <= pred_update_tag`,\\n   `pred_target[pred_update_idx] <= pred_update_target`.\\n5. Combinational prediction uses the cached instruction opcode/sign bit\\n   gated by `icache_hit`, `pred_valid`, and tag equality.\\n6. `next_pc` becomes a 3:1 mux: redirect_target, pred_target, or pc+4.\\n7. Drive `out.predict_taken` with the combinational prediction signal.\\n8. Keep all existing I-cache logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture `in.predict_taken` into the ID/EX register so it reaches EX stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"1. Read `in.predict_taken`.\\n2. Replace unconditional redirect with mispredict-only redirect using\\n   `actual_taken` and `misalign_fault` exactly as specified.\\n3. Drive `redirect_target` so a predicted-taken / not-taken mispredict\\n   recovers to pc+4.\\n4. Leave the EX/MEM `pc_next` register assignment completely untouched.\\n5. Add combinational `pred_update*` outputs that fire for JAL or taken\\n   backward branches, gated by `!misalign_fault && in.valid`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the four `pred_update*` outputs from `u_ex` to the new inputs on\\n`u_if`.  Pass `predict_taken` through the existing `if_id_t` connection\\nto `u_id`.  No other top-level changes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 396.13, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 40.06, \"fmax_mhz\": 165.51, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4178194, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9927, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [153.54, 165.51, 166.97], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T17:27:51.871399Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 10, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r10s2 (regression, +0.00%): Tag-matched predictor retention prevents state corruption on I-cache refill, but an 8-entry direct-mapped cache is too small to retain CoreMark's active branch instructions across loop iterations; the branch PC is evicted by the loop body itself before the next fetch, so `predict_taken` never qualifies on `icache_hit` and the integration yields zero IPC gain.\"}\n","metadata":{"output":"...\n\ng IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 2-entry Return Address Stack (RAS) in core.sv and change EX-stage redirect to\\nmispredict-only so that correct return predictions do not flush the pipeline.\\n\\n1. RAS logic in core.sv (top level, no new module):\\n   - Detect push:  jal with rd==ra  (opcode 1101111, instr[11:7]==1).\\n   - Detect pop/predict: jalr with rs1==ra (opcode 1100111, instr[19:15]==1).\\n   - Two 32-bit registers (ras_top, ras_next) plus pointer implied by the swap.\\n   - On push: ras_next <= ras_top; ras_top <= io_imemAddr + 32'd4.\\n   - On pop:  ras_top <= ras_next.\\n   - Updates are gated by !ex_redirect && !flush_if && !stall_if so wrong-path\\n     instructions during flushes do not corrupt the stack.\\n   - ras_predict = is_jalr_ra && !ex_redirect && !flush_if && !stall_if.\\n   - ras_target  = ras_top.\\n\\n2. Redirect muxing in core.sv:\\n   - Keep the raw ex_redirect / ex_redirect_target wires from ex_stage.\\n   - Drive if_stage inputs with combined signals:\\n       if_redirect       = ex_redirect || ras_predict;\\n       if_redirect_target = ras_predict ? ras_target : ex_redirect_target;\\n   - Hazard unit MUST continue to receive the raw ex_redirect (not the combined\\n     signal) so that correct predictions do not spuriously flush IF/ID.\\n   - Create an intermediate if_id_t signal from if_stage output, override\\n     predict_taken = ras_predict and predicted_target = ras_target, then feed\\n     that to id_stage.  This keeps the RAS out of the timing-critical if_stage\\n     next-pc path and avoids pc_fwd violations.\\n\\n3. Pipeline-bundle extension in core_pkg.sv:\\n   - Add `logic predict_taken;` and `logic [31:0] predicted_target;` to both\\n     `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t`.\\n\\n4. ID stage capture in id_stage.sv:\\n   - In the ID/EX register always_ff, capture:\\n       reg_q.predict_taken    <= in.predict_taken;\\n       reg_q.predicted_target <= in.predicted_target;\\n\\n5. EX-stage mispredict logic in ex_stage.sv:\\n   - Keep the existing redirect_target and pc_next assignments UNCHANGED.\\n     (This is the #1 source of prior pc_fwd failures; do not touch them.)\\n   - Add:\\n       logic actual_taken = in.ctrl.is_jump || branch_taken;\\n       logic target_mismatch = in.ctrl.is_jump &&\\n                               ({jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0} != in.predicted_target);\\n       assign redirect = ((actual_taken != in.predict_taken) ||\\n                          (in.predict_taken && target_mismatch)) && !misalign_fault;\\n   - For baseline behavior (predict_taken=0, predicted_target=0) this collapses\\n     to the original redirect expression.\\n   - On a correctly predicted return, redirect stays low and the pipeline\\n     continues fetching from the return address without a bubble.\\n   - On a RAS miss, EX asserts redirect to the true jump target and the\\n     hazard unit flushes IF/ID as usual.\\n\\nCost estimate: ~65 LUTs (32 for the redirect_target mux, ~31 for the 32-bit\\nequality comparator in EX, plus decode/control).  Previous cores with ~10200\\nLUTs still evaluated successfully, so the modest area increase is acceptable\\nfor the IPC gain.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `logic predict_taken;` and `logic [31:0] predicted_target;`\\nto both `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t` pipeline bundles.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Add the 2-entry RAS (ras_top, ras_next), push/pop decode from io_imemData,\\nras_predict / ras_target generation, combined redirect mux\\n(if_redirect = ex_redirect || ras_predict; if_redirect_target muxed),\\nfeed raw ex_redirect to hazard_unit.redirect, and override predict_taken\\n/ predicted_target on the if_id_t path to id_stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.predict_taken and in.predicted_target into the ID/EX register.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-bit equality comparator between the resolved jump target\\n({jalr_sum[31:1],1'b0}) and in.predicted_target.  Change redirect to\\nmispredict-only: ((actual_taken != predict_taken) ||\\n(predict_taken && target_mismatch)) && !misalign_fault.\\nDO NOT modify pc_next, redirect_target, or any other EX logic.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `logic predict_taken;` and `logic [31:0] predicted_target;`\\nto both `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t` pipeline bundles.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Add the 2-entry RAS (ras_top, ras_next), push/pop decode from io_imemData,\\nras_predict / ras_target generation, combined redirect mux\\n(if_redirect = ex_redirect || ras_predict; if_redirect_target muxed),\\nfeed raw ex_redirect to hazard_unit.redirect, and override predict_taken\\n/ predicted_target on the if_id_t path to id_stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.predict_taken and in.predicted_target into the ID/EX register.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-bit equality comparator between the resolved jump target\\n({jalr_sum[31:1],1'b0}) and in.predicted_target.  Change redirect to\\nmispredict-only: ((actual_taken != predict_taken) ||\\n(predict_taken && target_mismatch)) && !misalign_fault.\\nDO NOT modify pc_next, redirect_target, or any other EX logic.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 169.08, \"delta_pct\": -49.43, \"vs_baseline\": -40.22, \"fmax_mhz\": 70.4, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4163814, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10352, \"ff\": 1959, \"seeds\": [70.4, 63.32, 73.15], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T16:17:13.429883Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 8, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"JAL pre-decode in IF to eliminate unconditional jump bubbles\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Every JAL currently costs a one-cycle bubble: while JAL travels through ID,\\nthe IF stage blindly fetches PC+4; when JAL reaches EX it redirects, flushing\\nthe wrongly fetched instruction.  JAL is unconditional and its target is\\nknown the moment the instruction is fetched (PC + J-immediate).  Since there\\nis no mispredict possibility for aligned JAL, the IF stage can safely jump\\nimmediately, removing the bubble entirely without any prediction state or\\nrecovery logic.  This improves IPC for all function calls with no risk of\\nmispredict penalties.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Every JAL currently costs a one-cycle bubble: while JAL travels through ID,\\nthe IF stage blindly fetches PC+4; when JAL reaches EX it redirects, flushing\\nthe wrongly fetched instruction.  JAL is unconditional and its target is\\nknown the moment the instruction is fetched (PC + J-immediate).  Since there\\nis no mispredict possibility for aligned JAL, the IF stage can safely jump\\nimmediately, removing the bubble entirely without any prediction state or\\nrecovery logic.  This improves IPC for all function calls with no risk of\\nmispredict penalties.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add combinational JAL detection and target computation inside if_stage.sv.\\nWhen the instruction being emitted to ID is a JAL and its computed target is\\naligned, override next_pc with the JAL target instead of PC+4.  The PC\\nregister updates to the target in the same cycle JAL enters ID, so the\\npipeline fetches the target instruction one cycle earlier.  In ex_stage.sv,\\nsuppress the redirect signal for JAL (keep it only for branches and JALR);\\nbecause IF already fetched the correct target, there is nothing to flush.\\nMisaligned JAL falls back to PC+4 in IF, preserving the baseline trap-and-\\nfallthrough semantics in EX.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"In the combinational always_comb block that drives out.*, add:\\n  1. JAL opcode detection: is_jal = (out.instr[6:0] == 7'b1101111).\\n  2. J-immediate extraction from out.instr:\\n       jal_imm = {{11{out.instr[31]}}, out.instr[31], out.instr[19:12],\\n                  out.instr[20], out.instr[30:21], 1'b0};\\n  3. Target adder: jal_target = pc + jal_imm.\\n  4. next_pc mux:\\n       next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target\\n               : (is_jal && (jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00)) ? jal_target\\n               : pc + 32'd4;\\nDeclare is_jal, jal_imm, and jal_target as local logic signals.\\nDo NOT remove or alter the existing I-cache, flush, or stall logic.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change the redirect assignment so JAL does not assert redirect:\\n  assign redirect = (branch_taken || (in.ctrl.is_jump && in.ctrl.is_jalr))\\n                    && !misalign_fault;\\nLeave redirect_target, jump_target, branch_target, jalr_sum, and the\\nEX/MEM always_ff block completely unchanged.  JAL still computes\\npc_next = jump_target and alu_result = pc+4 in the register block as\\nbefore; the only difference is that EX no longer flushes the pipeline\\nfor aligned JAL because IF already redirected.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"In the combinational always_comb block that drives out.*, add:\\n  1. JAL opcode detection: is_jal = (out.instr[6:0] == 7'b1101111).\\n  2. J-immediate extraction from out.instr:\\n       jal_imm = {{11{out.instr[31]}}, out.instr[31], out.instr[19:12],\\n                  out.instr[20], out.instr[30:21], 1'b0};\\n  3. Target adder: jal_target = pc + jal_imm.\\n  4. next_pc mux:\\n       next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target\\n               : (is_jal && (jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00)) ? jal_target\\n               : pc + 32'd4;\\nDeclare is_jal, jal_imm, and jal_target as local logic signals.\\nDo NOT remove or alter the existing I-cache, flush, or stall logic.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change the redirect assignment so JAL does not assert redirect:\\n  assign redirect = (branch_taken || (in.ctrl.is_jump && in.ctrl.is_jalr))\\n                    && !misalign_fault;\\nLeave redirect_target, jump_target, branch_target, jalr_sum, and the\\nEX/MEM always_ff block completely unchanged.  JAL still computes\\npc_next = jump_target and alu_result = pc+4 in the register block as\\nbefore; the only difference is that EX no longer flushes the pipeline\\nfor aligned JAL because IF already redirected.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 396.13, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 40.06, \"fmax_mhz\": 165.51, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4178194, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9927, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [153.54, 165.51, 166.97], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T16:39:40.877429Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 9, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-002-r9s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r9s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r9s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r9s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 9}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"ICache-integrated JAL and backward-branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline flushes IF/ID on every taken JAL and backward branch, costing 2 cycles each.\\nPrior predictor attempts failed for three reasons: an 8-entry standalone BTB thrashed on\\nCoreMark's many active sites (0% IPC gain), a 2-entry RAS decoded io_imemData in core.sv\\nand fed it back to IF (Fmax crashed to 70 MHz), and a BTFN static predictor broke\\nrvfi_pc_fwd by altering EX-stage pc_next.  The existing 8-entry I-cache already stores\\ninstructions indexed by PC with tag match.  Extending each entry with a single valid bit\\nand a 32-bit target reuses the cache's fast read path, stays entirely inside IF, avoids\\nany combinational decode of external imemData, and costs only ~50 LUT4s.  By predicting\\nonly unconditional JAL and backward branches\\u2014whose targets are stable and highly\\nrepetitive in loop-heavy CoreMark\\u2014we avoid the aliasing thrashing that neutralized the\\nprior BTB, while mispredict-only redirect keeps EX's architectural pc_next completely\\nunchanged, preserving rvfi_pc_fwd.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline flushes IF/ID on every taken JAL and backward branch, costing 2 cycles each.\\nPrior predictor attempts failed for three reasons: an 8-entry standalone BTB thrashed on\\nCoreMark's many active sites (0% IPC gain), a 2-entry RAS decoded io_imemData in core.sv\\nand fed it back to IF (Fmax crashed to 70 MHz), and a BTFN static predictor broke\\nrvfi_pc_fwd by altering EX-stage pc_next.  The existing 8-entry I-cache already stores\\ninstructions indexed by PC with tag match.  Extending each entry with a single valid bit\\nand a 32-bit target reuses the cache's fast read path, stays entirely inside IF, avoids\\nany combinational decode of external imemData, and costs only ~50 LUT4s.  By predicting\\nonly unconditional JAL and backward branches\\u2014whose targets are stable and highly\\nrepetitive in loop-heavy CoreMark\\u2014we avoid the aliasing thrashing that neutralized the\\nprior BTB, while mispredict-only redirect keeps EX's architectural pc_next completely\\nunchanged, preserving rvfi_pc_fwd.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Integrate a tiny JAL + backward-branch target predictor into the existing 8-entry I-cache.\\nEach cache entry gains `pred_valid` (1 bit) and `pred_target[31:0]`.  `pred_valid` is\\ncleared on every cache refill and set only by EX when a JAL or taken backward branch\\nresolves, storing the resolved target.\\n\\nIn `if_stage`, on a cache hit, the cached instruction is decoded locally (opcode and\\nsign bit) to decide eligibility:\\n  `is_jal      = (icache_data[cache_idx][6:0] == 7'b1101111)`\\n  `is_branch   = (icache_data[cache_idx][6:0] == 7'b1100011)`\\n  `is_backward = icache_data[cache_idx][31]`\\n  `predict_taken = icache_hit && pred_valid[cache_idx] && !flush && !redirect &&\\n                   (is_jal || (is_branch && is_backward))`\\n`next_pc` becomes `redirect ? redirect_target :\\n                   predict_taken ? pred_target[cache_idx] : pc + 32'd4`.\\nBecause the predictor reads registered state and reuses the existing cache hit signal,\\nit does not create the long combinational io_imemData path that destroyed the RAS Fmax.\\n\\nA single `predict_taken` bit is added to `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t` and captured by\\n`id_stage`.  In `ex_stage` redirect changes to mispredict-only:\\n  `actual_taken = in.ctrl.is_jump || branch_taken`\\n  `redirect     = (!in.predict_taken && actual_taken && !misalign_fault) ||\\n                  ( in.predict_taken && (!actual_taken || misalign_fault))`\\n  `redirect_target = misalign_fault          ? (in.pc + 32'd4) :\\n                     !actual_taken           ? (in.pc + 32'd4) :\\n                     in.ctrl.is_jump         ? jump_target :\\n                                               branch_target`\\nThe EX/MEM `pc_next` assignment is left completely untouched, guaranteeing rvfi_pc_fwd.\\nEX also drives combinational update outputs back to IF:\\n  `pred_update       = (in.ctrl.is_jump && !in.ctrl.is_jalr) ||\\n                       (in.ctrl.is_branch && branch_taken && in.imm[31])`\\n  `pred_update_idx   = in.pc[4:2]`\\n  `pred_update_tag   = in.pc[31:5]`\\n  `pred_update_target = redirect_target`\\n`core.sv` wires the update path and passes `predict_taken` through the struct bundles.\\nThe hazard unit needs no changes\\u2014its `redirect` input naturally flushes on mispredict\\nonly, which is exactly the desired behavior.\\n\\nCost estimate: ~50 LUT4s and 264 FFs.  Fmax should stay near the current ~165 MHz\\nbecause the critical path remains in the ALU fast path and the IF loop sees only a\\nslightly wider next-pc mux.  IPC should rise 5-10 % by eliminating bubbles on the\\nmost frequent control-flow patterns in CoreMark.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `logic predict_taken;` to `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t` pipeline bundles.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `pred_valid[0:7]` and `pred_target[0:7][31:0]` arrays plus `pred_update*`\\ninputs.  Combinational prediction uses the cached instruction opcode/sign bit\\ngated by `icache_hit` and `pred_valid`.  `next_pc` becomes a 3:1 mux choosing\\nredirect_target, pred_target, or pc+4.  Clear `pred_valid` on every cache refill\\nand write it (along with target) on `pred_update`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture `in.predict_taken` into the ID/EX register.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Read `in.predict_taken`.  Replace unconditional redirect with mispredict-only\\nredirect using `actual_taken`.  Compute `redirect_target` so that misaligned or\\nnot-taken predicted branches redirect to pc+4.  Leave the EX/MEM `pc_next`\\nregister assignment completely unchanged.  Add `pred_update` combinational\\noutputs that fire for JAL or taken backward branches.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire `pred_update*` from `u_ex` to `u_if`.  Pass `predict_taken` through the\\nexisting `if_id_t` connection to `u_id`.  No other top-level changes needed.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `logic predict_taken;` to `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t` pipeline bundles.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `pred_valid[0:7]` and `pred_target[0:7][31:0]` arrays plus `pred_update*`\\ninputs.  Combinational prediction uses the cached instruction opcode/sign bit\\ngated by `icache_hit` and `pred_valid`.  `next_pc` becomes a 3:1 mux choosing\\nredirect_target, pred_target, or pc+4.  Clear `pred_valid` on every cache refill\\nand write it (along with target) on `pred_update`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture `in.predict_taken` into the ID/EX register.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Read `in.predict_taken`.  Replace unconditional redirect with mispredict-only\\nredirect using `actual_taken`.  Compute `redirect_target` so that misaligned or\\nnot-taken predicted branches redirect to pc+4.  Leave the EX/MEM `pc_next`\\nregister assignment completely unchanged.  Add `pred_update` combinational\\noutputs that fire for JAL or taken backward branches.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire `pred_update*` from `u_ex` to `u_if`.  Pass `predict_taken` through the\\nexisting `if_id_t` connection to `u_id`.  No other top-level changes needed.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 396.13, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 40.06, \"fmax_mhz\": 165.51, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4178194, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9927, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [153.54, 165.51, 166.97], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T16:58:37.251660Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 9, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 10, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench ALU currently computes three separate 32\\u00d732 products\\n(signed\\u00d7signed, unsigned\\u00d7unsigned, signed\\u00d7unsigned). Yosys does not\\nmerge them, so the design pays for three multipliers worth of DSP/LUT\\narea.  With LUT4 already at 9927/10000, placement congestion is severe\\nand likely limits the achievable Fmax of the fast integer path.\\nRemoving two of the three multipliers frees substantial area without\\nchanging IPC or adding pipeline stages.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace mul_ss, mul_uu and mul_su with a single unsigned\\u00d7unsigned\\nproduct.  MUL/MULHU reuse the low/high halves directly.  MULH and\\nMULHSU high halves are recovered with a cheap 32-bit correction\\nsubtractor: MULHSU subtracts b when a is negative; MULH additionally\\nsubtracts a when b is negative.  The ALTOPS formal branch and the\\ndivider path are untouched, and the fast-path 2:1 mux is preserved.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Collapse three multipliers into one unsigned product; add correction subtractors for MULH/MULHSU high halves.\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-002-r10s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r10s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r10s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r10s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 10}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"ICache-integrated JAL/backward-branch predictor with tag-matched retention\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline with an 8-entry I-cache and ALU fast path achieves 396.13 fitness,\\nbut still flushes IF/ID on every taken JAL and backward branch, costing two cycles.\\nA prior attempt to integrate target prediction into the I-cache (hyp-20260514-003-r9s2)\\nproduced exactly 0 % delta because the predictor valid bit was cleared on every\\ncache refill, so predictions were never visible when the branch PC was fetched again.\\nBy storing a partial tag with each prediction entry and qualifying the hit with\\ntag equality, the predictor state survives across repeated fetches and evictions\\nwithout needing explicit invalidation logic.  This reuses the existing fast I-cache\\nread path (registered state, no external imem_data combinational delay) and adds\\nonly ~250 FFs and a small next-pc mux, well within the remaining LUT4 headroom.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline with an 8-entry I-cache and ALU fast path achieves 396.13 fitness,\\nbut still flushes IF/ID on every taken JAL and backward branch, costing two cycles.\\nA prior attempt to integrate target prediction into the I-cache (hyp-20260514-003-r9s2)\\nproduced exactly 0 % delta because the predictor valid bit was cleared on every\\ncache refill, so predictions were never visible when the branch PC was fetched again.\\nBy storing a partial tag with each prediction entry and qualifying the hit with\\ntag equality, the predictor state survives across repeated fetches and evictions\\nwithout needing explicit invalidation logic.  This reuses the existing fast I-cache\\nread path (registered state, no external imem_data combinational delay) and adds\\nonly ~250 FFs and a small next-pc mux, well within the remaining LUT4 headroom.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the existing 8-entry I-cache in if_stage.sv with a tiny target predictor:\\n- Add `pred_valid[0:7]`, `pred_tag[0:7][26:0]`, and `pred_target[0:7][31:0]`.\\n- Combinational prediction (no imem_data in the path):\\n    `is_jal      = (icache_data[cache_idx][6:0] == 7'b1101111)`\\n    `is_branch   = (icache_data[cache_idx][6:0] == 7'b1100011)`\\n    `is_backward = icache_data[cache_idx][31]`\\n    `predict_taken = icache_hit && pred_valid[cache_idx] &&\\n                     (pred_tag[cache_idx] == cache_tag) &&\\n                     !flush && !redirect &&\\n                     (is_jal || (is_branch && is_backward))`\\n    `next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target :\\n               predict_taken ? pred_target[cache_idx] : pc + 32'd4;`\\n- In ex_stage, change redirect to mispredict-only and expose update outputs:\\n    `actual_taken    = in.ctrl.is_jump || branch_taken;`\\n    `redirect        = ((!in.predict_taken && actual_taken) ||\\n                        (in.predict_taken && (!actual_taken || misalign_fault)))\\n                       && !misalign_fault;`\\n    `redirect_target = misalign_fault          ? (in.pc + 32'd4) :\\n                       !actual_taken           ? (in.pc + 32'd4) :\\n                       in.ctrl.is_jump         ? jump_target :\\n                                                 branch_target;`\\n    `pred_update       = !misalign_fault && in.valid &&\\n                         ((in.ctrl.is_jump && !in.ctrl.is_jalr) ||\\n                          (in.ctrl.is_branch && branch_taken && in.imm[31]));`\\n    `pred_update_idx   = in.pc[4:2];`\\n    `pred_update_tag   = in.pc[31:5];`\\n    `pred_update_target = redirect_target;`\\n- Leave the EX/ME