mproved CoreMark cycle count but lost more Fmax than they gained,\\nwhile the 4-entry RAS also regressed because it added stack state, push/pop\\nbookkeeping, and enough IF routing to lower median Fmax. The useful signal\\nfrom the RAS experiment is that returns exist in the timed path, but the\\npredictor must be much narrower and cheaper than a general stack.\\n\\nA one-entry last-return target predictor targets the same remaining JALR\\nhole with less state and less control. CoreMark's hot call/return behavior is\\ntypically dominated by repeated returns from stable call sites, so a single\\ncached canonical-return target can remove many return flushes without a BTB,\\nbranch table, multi-entry stack, or speculative architectural state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry return target cache in IF. When EX resolves a valid,\\nnon-trapping canonical return JALR (`jalr x0, 0(x1)` or `jalr x0, 0(x5)`),\\nrecord the return instruction PC and its resolved next PC. When IF later\\nfetches the same canonical return PC and the entry is valid, predict the\\ncached target through the existing `predicted_taken` / `predicted_target`\\nmetadata path. Change JALR redirect generation to the same resolved-next-PC\\nmismatch check used for predicted JALs, so correctly predicted cached returns\\ndo not flush and all other JALRs retain the current EX re... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-013-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Cold High-Half Multiply Unit\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best result came from moving cold DIV/REM hardware out of the\\nuniversal EX-stage ALU path: CoreMark cycles barely changed, while median\\nFmax rose sharply and LUT pressure dropped. The same shape remains in the\\nmultiply path, but with a narrower target. `rtl/alu.sv` still builds three\\nindependent 64-bit products every cycle for MUL, MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU.\\nCoreMark's timed kernels need ordinary low-half MUL, but high-half multiply\\nvariants are normally absent or cold in this benchmark. The previous 33x33\\nshared-multiplier rewrite proved that reshaping the hot MUL primitive itself\\ncan badly hurt placement, so the better micro-optimization is to leave the\\nexisting low-half MUL fast path intact and remove only the cold high-half\\nmultiplier variants from the one-cycle ALU.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best result came from moving cold DIV/REM hardware out of the\\nuniversal EX-stage ALU path: CoreMark cycles barely changed, while median\\nFmax rose sharply and LUT pressure dropped. The same shape remains in the\\nmultiply path, but with a narrower target. `rtl/alu.sv` still builds three\\nindependent 64-bit products every cycle for MUL, MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU.\\nCoreMark's timed kernels need ordinary low-half MUL, but high-half multiply\\nvariants are normally absent or cold in this benchmark. The previous 33x33\\nshared-multiplier rewrite proved that reshaping the hot MUL primitive itself\\ncan badly hurt placement, so the better micro-optimization is to leave the\\nexisting low-half MUL fast path intact and remove only the cold high-half\\nmultiplier variants from the one-cycle ALU.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep ALU_MUL as the only single-cycle hardware multiply in the hot ALU path,\\nusing the existing unsigned 32x32 product low half. Move MULH, MULHU, and\\nMULHSU into a small long-latency `mulh_unit` launched only for those three\\no... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-014-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Single-Entry Retiring Store Buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core gained a large Fmax and LUT win by moving DIV/REM out\\nof the hot EX path, so the next structural bottleneck is less likely to be\\nraw datapath area and more likely to be cycles lost to the random dmem\\nhandshake model. Today every dmem-not-ready cycle for a STORE freezes the\\nwhole pipeline, even though the store address, replicated data, byte mask,\\nand RVFI memory metadata are already known in MEM and the store produces no\\nregister result for younger ALU/control instructions. A prior two-entry\\nstore buffer proved the idea through formal and cosim but failed placement\\non the larger pre-DIV RTL. A smaller one-entry RAM-store buffer should retain\\nmost of the useful stall hiding while keeping the arbitration, state, and\\nplacement pressure low enough for the post-DIV design.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core gained a large Fmax and LUT win by moving DIV/REM out\\nof the hot EX path, so the next structural bottleneck is less likely to be\\nraw datapath area and more likely to be cycles lost to the random dmem\\nhandshake model. Today every dmem-not-ready cycle for a STORE freezes the\\nwhole pipeline, even though the store address, replicated data, byte mask,\\nand RVFI memory metadata are already known in MEM and the store produces no\\nregister result for younger ALU/control instructions. A prior two-entry\\nstore buffer proved the idea through formal and cosim but failed placement\\non the larger pre-DIV RTL. A smaller one-entry RAM-store buffer should retain\\nmost of the useful stall hiding while keeping the arbitration, state, and\\nplacement pressure low enough for the post-DIV design.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add one in-order retiring store slot for legal aligned stores to normal RAM\\nonly. When such a store reaches MEM and io_dmemReady is low, capture its\\nbyte address, replicated write data, byte mask, and RV... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-015-r7s2\", \"title\": \"One-Entry Return Target Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best RTL already predicts backward conditional branches and\\ndirect JAL targets in IF, and the latest winning change moved cold DIV/REM\\noff the critical ALU path. The predictor slot should therefore avoid broad\\nlearned branch tables that have already shown a bad cycle-count versus Fmax\\ntradeoff: the 64-entry agree table and 16-entry forward override both reduced\\nCoreMark cycles but lost more clock than they recovered.\\n\\nThe remaining high-value predictor miss is JALR return control flow. The\\n4-entry RAS experiment showed returns exist in the timed path, but its stack\\nbookkeeping and IF routing were still too expensive. A single tagged return\\ntarget entry is a narrower bet: it targets recurring canonical return PCs\\nwith one PC tag, one target register, and one IF compare, avoiding a BTB,\\nmulti-entry stack, or conditional-branch table.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best RTL already predicts backward conditional branches and\\ndirect JAL targets in IF, and the latest winning change moved cold DIV/REM\\noff the critical ALU path. The predictor slot should therefore avoid broad\\nlearned branch tables that have already shown a bad cycle-count versus Fmax\\ntradeoff: the 64-entry agree table and 16-entry forward override both reduced\\nCoreMark cycles but lost more clock than they recovered.\\n\\nThe remaining high-value predictor miss is JALR return control flow. The\\n4-entry RAS experiment showed returns exist in the timed path, but its stack\\nbookkeeping and IF routing were still too expensive. A single tagged return\\ntarget entry is a narrower bet: it targets recurring canonical return PCs\\nwith one PC tag, one target register, and one IF compare, avoiding a BTB,\\nmulti-entry stack, or conditional-branch table.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry return target predictor for canonical return JALRs. When EX\\nresolves a valid... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-016-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Reset-Valid LUTRAM Register File\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The post-DIV best core has removed the largest cold arithmetic block from\\nthe EX critical path, so the next micro-optimization should target FPGA\\nplacement pressure without changing CoreMark cycles. The current register\\nfile is a 32x32 array with a synchronous reset loop that clears every data\\nbit. That resettable array is likely implemented as ordinary flip-flops or\\nreset-muxed logic instead of compact distributed RAM, adding roughly 1024\\nresettable state bits plus reset fanout to the already timing-sensitive\\nfetch/decode/register-read region.\\n\\nArchitectural software only needs the externally visible reset behavior of\\nreading zero before a register has been written. It does not require the\\nphysical register data array itself to be synchronously cleared. A valid-zero\\nmask can preserve the current tests and reset semantics while allowing the\\n32x32 data storage to become resetless.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The post-DIV best core has removed the largest cold arithmetic block from\\nthe EX critical path, so the next micro-optimization should target FPGA\\nplacement pressure without changing CoreMark cycles. The current register\\nfile is a 32x32 array with a synchronous reset loop that clears every data\\nbit. That resettable array is likely implemented as ordinary flip-flops or\\nreset-muxed logic instead of compact distributed RAM, adding roughly 1024\\nresettable state bits plus reset fanout to the already timing-sensitive\\nfetch/decode/register-read region.\\n\\nArchitectural software only needs the externally visible reset behavior of\\nreading zero before a register has been written. It does not require the\\nphysical register data array itself to be synchronously cleared. A valid-zero\\nmask can preserve the current tests and reset semantics while allowing the\\n32x32 data storage to become resetless.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the regist... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-017-r8s1\", \"title\": \"One-Deep Store Retirement Slot With Direct Fast Path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core is dominated by the post-DIV/REM timing shape, with\\nmedian Fmax now high enough that broad datapath changes have mostly hurt\\nplacement. The remaining structural opportunity with measured evidence is\\nstore backpressure: the previous one-entry store buffer reduced CoreMark\\ncycles from 4,259,618 to 4,226,169, but its dmem arbitration and MEM-stage\\nmuxing cost slightly more Fmax than the cycle gain recovered.\\n\\nThe promising angle is therefore not a larger buffer, but a smaller and more\\ntiming-local retiring store slot. Keep the zero-wait store path identical to\\nthe current best design, and add state only for the uncommon case where a\\nnormal RAM store reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. That targets the same\\nrandom-dStall cycles as the prior structural attempt while avoiding a\\npermanent dmem-port mux on every load/store cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core is dominated by the post-DIV/REM timing shape, with\\nmedian Fmax now high enough that broad datapath changes have mostly hurt\\nplacement. The remaining structural opportunity with measured evidence is\\nstore backpressure: the previous one-entry store buffer reduced CoreMark\\ncycles from 4,259,618 to 4,226,169, but its dmem arbitration and MEM-stage\\nmuxing cost slightly more Fmax than the cycle gain recovered.\\n\\nThe promising angle is therefore not a larger buffer, but a smaller and more\\ntiming-local retiring store slot. Keep the zero-wait store path identical to\\nthe current best design, and add state only for the uncommon case where a\\nnormal RAM store reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. That targets the same\\nrandom-dStall cycles as the prior structural attempt while avoiding a\\npermanent dmem-port mux on every load/store cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-deep pending-store retirement slot that is used only on a... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-018-r8s2\", \"title\": \"Funct3-Biased Static Branch Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best frontend already has the two predictor features that have\\nactually paid off: backward conditional branches predict taken, and direct\\nJAL targets are predicted in IF. The learned predictor attempts point in the\\nother direction: both the 64-entry agree table and the 16-entry forward-only\\noverride table reduced CoreMark cycles, but their table read/update routing\\ncost more Fmax than the saved mispredicts recovered. Return prediction was\\neven less attractive after the post-DIV timing win, with only small cycle\\nsavings and a large clock regression.\\n\\nThe remaining promising predictor angle is therefore a zero-state refinement\\nof the static conditional-branch rule. A quick dynamic profile of the timed\\nCoreMark region shows that the baseline BTFNT rule is especially wrong for\\ntwo simple branch classes: backward BEQ branches, which are mostly not taken\\nin this binary, and forward BNE branches, which are usually taken. Those two\\nclasses account for a large fraction of residual static predictor mistakes,\\nand they can be recognized from the funct3 bits already examined in IF for\\nbranch legality. This targets iterations/cycle without adding a predictor\\nRAM, update feedback path, BTB, RAS, or extra target adder.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best frontend already has the two predictor features that have\\nactually paid off: backward conditional branches predict taken, and direct\\nJAL targets are predicted in IF. The learned predictor attempts point in the\\nother direction: both the 64-entry agree table and the 16-entry forward-only\\noverride table reduced CoreMark cycles, but their table read/update routing\\ncost more Fmax than the saved mispredicts recovered. Return prediction was\\neven less attractive after the post-DIV timing win, with only small cycle\\nsavings and a large clock regression.\\n\\nThe remaining p... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(Output capped at 50 KB. Showing lines 1-25. Use offset=26 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260427-001\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest (no implementation change)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Used by the orchestrator integration test (--from-hypothesis path).\\nMeasures the unchanged baseline through the full eval pipeline so the\\nresulting log entry locks in the first fitness number for phase 8.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"No RTL changes \\u2014 exercises the worktree -> emit_verilog -> formal ->\\ncosim -> fpga path on the existing rtl/*.sv to confirm the orchestrator\\nproduces a structured log entry.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 0, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Sentinel \\u2014 no real change. skip_implementation:true below bypasses\\nthe implementation agent, so the file path here is metadata only;\\nit just has to satisfy the schema's rtl/<file> pattern. core.sv is\\nalways present and untouched.\\n\"}], \"skip_implementation\": true, \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 301.04, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 135.21, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"lut4\": 9880, \"ff\": 1858, \"seeds\": [121.29, 135.21, 136.07], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-04-28T02:16:49.012016+00:00\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260427-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Move DIV/REM off the single-cycle ALU path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline ALU places RV32M multiplication and division in the same\\ncombinational EX-stage result mux as common integer operations. A 32-bit\\ncombinational divider is very likely to dominate LUT depth and area on\\nthe Tang Nano 20K, yet CoreMark's timed region is matrix/list/state code\\nthat is multiply-heavy and effectively division-free. Keeping DIV/REM\\nsingle-cycle optimizes an uncommon path while lowering Fmax for every\\ninstruction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline ALU places RV32M multiplication and division in the same\\ncombinational EX-stage result mux as common integer operations. A 32-bit\\ncombinational divider is very likely to dominate LUT depth and area on\\nthe Tang Nano 20K, yet CoreMark's timed region is matrix/list/state code\\nthat is multiply-heavy and effectively division-free. Keeping DIV/REM\\nsingle-cycle optimizes an uncommon path while lowering Fmax for every\\ninstruction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases in rtl/alu.sv with a\\nsmall iterative RV32M divide/remainder unit and add an EX-stage interlock\\nonly when one of those opcodes is in flight. Leave ADD/SUB/logic/shift,\\nbranches, loads/stores, jumps, and MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU on the current\\nsingle-cycle path. The timed CoreMark loop should pay no meaningful IPC\\npenalty because it does not execute DIV/REM, while the FPGA critical path\\nshould shrink from divider-through-ALU-mux to the existing add/compare/mul\\npaths. Preserve exact RV32M divide-by-zero and INT_MIN/-1 semantics and\\nkeep the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions for formal builds.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 15, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real combinational DIV/REM hardware from the normal ALU result\\nmux, retaining single-cycle non-divide ALU and MUL behavior plus the\\nexisting A... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260427-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Elastic Fetch Skid Buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline frontend has no real IF/ID storage: instruction data flows\\ndirectly from io_imemData into decode, and hazard_unit globally freezes the\\nPC on load-use, dmem stalls, and imem stalls. Under the tournament's ~22%\\nrandom imem backpressure, every not-ready fetch becomes a visible decode\\nbubble. Under dmem backpressure, the independent imem port is also idle even\\nthough it could be fetching sequential instructions for after the stall.\\nCoreMark's IPC is already close to the single-issue limit, so the best\\nstructural win is to recover wasted frontend cycles without widening the\\ncore or lengthening the EX critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline frontend has no real IF/ID storage: instruction data flows\\ndirectly from io_imemData into decode, and hazard_unit globally freezes the\\nPC on load-use, dmem stalls, and imem stalls. Under the tournament's ~22%\\nrandom imem backpressure, every not-ready fetch becomes a visible decode\\nbubble. Under dmem backpressure, the independent imem port is also idle even\\nthough it could be fetching sequential instructions for after the stall.\\nCoreMark's IPC is already close to the single-issue limit, so the best\\nstructural win is to recover wasted frontend cycles without widening the\\ncore or lengthening the EX critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the combinational IF/ID handoff with an elastic 2-entry fetch skid\\nbuffer that decouples instruction fetch from decode. The fetch side advances\\nthe PC and captures sequential instructions whenever io_imemReady is high\\nand the buffer is not full, even while ID/EX is held by a dmem stall. The\\ndecode side consumes one buffered instruction per non-stalled cycle. Preserve\\nthe baseline zero-latency behavior with an empty-buffer bypass from\\nio_imemData to decode when the backend is ready and imem is ready, so the\\nno-stall path and branch target... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260427-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Backward-Branch Taken Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX and fetches strictly pc+4 until that resolution, so every taken loop branch in CoreMark pays a two-instruction wrong-path flush. CoreMark's hot loops are dominated by short backward conditional branches whose direction is highly biased toward taken. A small static predictor can remove most loop-back redirect bubbles without adding a learned-state table, RAM, or speculative architectural state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX and fetches strictly pc+4 until that resolution, so every taken loop branch in CoreMark pays a two-instruction wrong-path flush. CoreMark's hot loops are dominated by short backward conditional branches whose direction is highly biased toward taken. A small static predictor can remove most loop-back redirect bubbles without adding a learned-state table, RAM, or speculative architectural state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a decode-light static branch predictor in IF that recognizes B-type instructions and predicts backward branches taken when the sign bit of the branch immediate is set. Compute the B immediate in IF, redirect the next PC to pc+imm for predicted-taken backward branches, and carry predicted_taken plus predicted_target through IF/ID and ID/EX. In EX, compare the actual branch result and target against the prediction, redirect only on mispredict, and set rvfi pc_wdata to the actual next PC as today. JAL/JALR remain resolved in EX to keep the predictor slot focused on conditional branches and avoid adding a return-address stack or BTB.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8.0, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles with predicted_taken and predicted_target fields so EX can distinguish correct predictions f... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260427-004-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Single Shared RV32M Multiplier\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU builds three independent wide products every cycle:\\nsigned*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and signed*unsigned. Those products feed\\nthe same EX-stage result mux as ordinary integer operations, so their area and\\nrouting pressure can lower Fmax even when most instructions are ADD/logic,\\nbranches, loads, and stores. CoreMark does use MUL, so making multiplication\\nmulti-cycle risks losing IPC; however all RV32M multiply variants can be\\nimplemented by one signedness-controlled 33x33 product with no latency change.\\nThis is a narrower and lower-risk micro-optimization than the prior failed\\nDIV/REM interlock attempt because it leaves divider behavior, pipeline stalls,\\nand RVFI ordering untouched.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU builds three independent wide products every cycle:\\nsigned*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and signed*unsigned. Those products feed\\nthe same EX-stage result mux as ordinary integer operations, so their area and\\nrouting pressure can lower Fmax even when most instructions are ADD/logic,\\nbranches, loads, and stores. CoreMark does use MUL, so making multiplication\\nmulti-cycle risks losing IPC; however all RV32M multiply variants can be\\nimplemented by one signedness-controlled 33x33 product with no latency change.\\nThis is a narrower and lower-risk micro-optimization than the prior failed\\nDIV/REM interlock attempt because it leaves divider behavior, pipeline stalls,\\nand RVFI ordering untouched.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the three unconditional multiplier expressions in rtl/alu.sv with a\\nsingle shared 33-bit-by-33-bit product. For MUL, zero-extend both operands and\\nuse the low 32 bits; for MULH, sign-extend both operands; for MULHSU,\\nsign-extend rs1 and zero-extend rs2; for MULHU, zero-extend both operands.\\nSelect product[63:32] for the high-half operations and product[31:0] for MUL.\\nKeep the RISC... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260427-005-r2s1\", \"title\": \"MEM-to-EX Load-Use Bypass\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline still has the textbook structural load-use gap: a load in EX always forces the immediately following consumer to wait one extra cycle, even when the dmem bus is ready and the loaded word is already available combinationally in MEM. CoreMark's list, matrix, and state kernels contain many load-to-use pairs, so this fixed bubble directly lowers iterations per cycle. The recent predictor win improved control flow without changing the backend; the next most promising structural angle is to add the missing MEM-to-EX load-data path and remove the mandatory interlock while preserving the single-issue in-order retirement contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline still has the textbook structural load-use gap: a load in EX always forces the immediately following consumer to wait one extra cycle, even when the dmem bus is ready and the loaded word is already available combinationally in MEM. CoreMark's list, matrix, and state kernels contain many load-to-use pairs, so this fixed bubble directly lowers iterations per cycle. The recent predictor win improved control flow without changing the backend; the next most promising structural angle is to add the missing MEM-to-EX load-data path and remove the mandatory interlock while preserving the single-issue in-order retirement contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a direct load-result forwarding path from the MEM stage's existing sign/zero-extended load_data to the EX operand muxes. When an instruction in EX consumes the rd of a load currently in MEM, select this MEM load result for rs1 and/or rs2 instead of stalling for the value to appear in MEM/WB. If io_dmemReady is low for that load, keep the current dmem hold behavior and suppress any younger EX redirect until the load data is valid; once ready, the dependent instruction executes in the same cycle the load ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260427-006-r2s2\", \"title\": \"IF Direct-Jump Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best RTL already predicts backward conditional branches in IF,\\nbut ex_stage still asserts a redirect for every JAL/JALR. That leaves\\nunconditional direct jumps, calls, and compiler-generated `j` control-flow\\nskips paying the same wrong-path flush as an unpredicted taken branch, even\\nthough a JAL target is fully encoded in the fetched instruction. CoreMark's\\noptimized RV32IM image contains many direct JAL/J sites, so eliminating those\\nredirect bubbles should improve iterations/cycle with much less timing risk\\nthan adding a BTB or learned direction table to the IF path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best RTL already predicts backward conditional branches in IF,\\nbut ex_stage still asserts a redirect for every JAL/JALR. That leaves\\nunconditional direct jumps, calls, and compiler-generated `j` control-flow\\nskips paying the same wrong-path flush as an unpredicted taken branch, even\\nthough a JAL target is fully encoded in the fetched instruction. CoreMark's\\noptimized RV32IM image contains many direct JAL/J sites, so eliminating those\\nredirect bubbles should improve iterations/cycle with much less timing risk\\nthan adding a BTB or learned direction table to the IF path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the existing IF-stage predictor from backward conditional branches to\\ndirect JAL targets. Recognize opcode 1101111 in IF, form the J immediate,\\npredict pc+imm as the next PC when the target is word-aligned, and carry the\\nexisting predicted_taken/predicted_target metadata with the instruction. In\\nEX, make JAL redirect mispredict-only by comparing the resolved jump target\\nagainst the carried prediction; JALR remains unpredicted and still redirects\\nfrom EX. This should remove the two-cycle recovery penalty from correctly\\npredicted direct jumps and calls while preserving RVFI pc_wdata, misaligned\\njump traps, and the single-retire c... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Operand-Aware Load-Use Interlock\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard check is deliberately conservative: every load\\nin ID/EX stalls the next instruction when the load destination matches either\\nraw rs1 or raw rs2 bitfield in IF/ID. That creates real bubbles for true\\nload consumers, but it also creates false bubbles for common CoreMark\\ninstructions whose rs fields are immediates or destinations rather than\\nsource operands, especially OP-IMM shifts/arithmetic, LOAD, JAL, LUI, and\\nAUIPC. The prior full MEM-to-EX load bypass recovered many load-use cycles\\nbut cost too much Fmax because it added a new MEM-data path into EX. A\\ndecode-light operand-use filter should recover the false-stall subset with\\nalmost no new datapath depth and no change to branch prediction, memory\\ntiming, or RVFI retirement.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard check is deliberately conservative: every load\\nin ID/EX stalls the next instruction when the load destination matches either\\nraw rs1 or raw rs2 bitfield in IF/ID. That creates real bubbles for true\\nload consumers, but it also creates false bubbles for common CoreMark\\ninstructions whose rs fields are immediates or destinations rather than\\nsource operands, especially OP-IMM shifts/arithmetic, LOAD, JAL, LUI, and\\nAUIPC. The prior full MEM-to-EX load bypass recovered many load-use cycles\\nbut cost too much Fmax because it added a new MEM-data path into EX. A\\ndecode-light operand-use filter should recover the false-stall subset with\\nalmost no new datapath depth and no change to branch prediction, memory\\ntiming, or RVFI retirement.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refine the hazard_unit load-use predicate so it only compares the load rd\\nagainst source fields that the IF/ID instruction actually reads. Compute\\nsimple uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 bits from the IF/ID opcode: rs1 is used by\\nOP, OP-IMM, LOAD, STORE, BRANCH, and JALR; rs2 is used only by... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Two-Entry Retiring Store Buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core treats every dmem-not-ready cycle on a store as a\\nfull pipeline freeze, even though a store's data and byte mask are already\\nknown in MEM and no register result is needed by younger ALU/control\\ninstructions. With the tournament's random dmem stalls, this turns store bus\\nbackpressure into lost frontend and execute bandwidth. The prior MEM-to-EX\\nload-use bypass proved that backend bubbles matter, but it put dmem read data\\non the EX operand critical path and lost too much Fmax. A small in-order store\\nbuffer targets the store-only part of the same structural bottleneck while\\nkeeping load data, branch compare, and ALU timing out of the new path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core treats every dmem-not-ready cycle on a store as a\\nfull pipeline freeze, even though a store's data and byte mask are already\\nknown in MEM and no register result is needed by younger ALU/control\\ninstructions. With the tournament's random dmem stalls, this turns store bus\\nbackpressure into lost frontend and execute bandwidth. The prior MEM-to-EX\\nload-use bypass proved that backend bubbles matter, but it put dmem read data\\non the EX operand critical path and lost too much Fmax. A small in-order store\\nbuffer targets the store-only part of the same structural bottleneck while\\nkeeping load data, branch compare, and ALU timing out of the new path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a two-entry FIFO for normal RAM stores. When a legal aligned store to the\\nRAM address range reaches MEM and the external dmem port is not immediately\\navailable, retire the store into the FIFO with its address, replicated write\\ndata, byte mask, and RVFI metadata, then let younger non-memory instructions\\ncontinue through the pipeline while the FIFO drains oldest-first on the dmem\\nport. Loads, stores when the FIFO is full, and all MMIO/marker/UART st... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Static-Biased Branch Agree Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best frontend already removes most obvious control bubbles by\\npredicting backward conditional branches taken and direct JAL targets in IF.\\nThe remaining predictor loss is now dominated by conditional branches that\\nstatic BTFNT handles poorly: biased forward branches, backward branches with\\nnon-loop behavior, and alias-heavy branch sites in CoreMark's list and state\\nkernels. A small learned direction predictor can attack those residual\\nmispredicts without adding a BTB, a target adder beyond the existing branch\\nimmediate path, or any speculative architectural state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best frontend already removes most obvious control bubbles by\\npredicting backward conditional branches taken and direct JAL targets in IF.\\nThe remaining predictor loss is now dominated by conditional branches that\\nstatic BTFNT handles poorly: biased forward branches, backward branches with\\nnon-loop behavior, and alias-heavy branch sites in CoreMark's list and state\\nkernels. A small learned direction predictor can attack those residual\\nmispredicts without adding a BTB, a target adder beyond the existing branch\\nimmediate path, or any speculative architectural state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 64-entry, PC-indexed, two-bit \\\"agree\\\" predictor for conditional branch\\ndirection. IF still computes the existing static BTFNT direction and branch\\ntarget from the fetched instruction; the table counter predicts whether the\\ndynamic outcome will agree with that static direction. Initialize counters to\\nstrongly agree so cold branches behave exactly like the current predictor.\\nFor legal aligned B-type branches, predict taken when the table prediction\\ncombined with the static direction says taken, and carry the existing\\npredicted_taken/predicted_target metadata into EX. Direct JAL prediction\\nremains unchanged, and JALR remains ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-004-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Hot-Bit ALU Result Mux\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core is now Fmax-sensitive in the EX-stage ALU path. The\\nALU operation encoding is dense across both common RV32I operations and the\\nRV32M operations, and rtl/alu.sv selects every result through one broad case\\nstatement. Recent experiments showed that touching the multiplier primitive\\nitself is risky: the 33x33 shared-multiplier rewrite preserved IPC but badly\\nhurt Fmax. A safer micro-optimization is to leave every arithmetic primitive\\nand pipeline handshake unchanged, but make the ALU control encoding expose a\\nhot/cold split so synthesis can build a shallower result mux for the common\\ninteger/address/branch work.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core is now Fmax-sensitive in the EX-stage ALU path. The\\nALU operation encoding is dense across both common RV32I operations and the\\nRV32M operations, and rtl/alu.sv selects every result through one broad case\\nstatement. Recent experiments showed that touching the multiplier primitive\\nitself is risky: the 33x33 shared-multiplier rewrite preserved IPC but badly\\nhurt Fmax. A safer micro-optimization is to leave every arithmetic primitive\\nand pipeline handshake unchanged, but make the ALU control encoding expose a\\nhot/cold split so synthesis can build a shallower result mux for the common\\ninteger/address/branch work.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Re-encode ALU op constants so bit 4 is a registered \\\"M-extension operation\\\"\\ndiscriminator: all RV32I/simple operations keep op[4]=0, while MUL/MULH/\\nMULHSU/MULHU/DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU move to op[4]=1 with op[2:0] matching the\\nRV32M funct3 order. Refactor rtl/alu.sv into a hot simple-result mux for\\nADD/SUB/logic/compare/shift/LUI and a