ct to IF in the same cycle the JALR enters ID/EX. The\\nID/EX prediction metadata is overwritten with that resolved target so the\\nlater EX-stage instance of the same JALR does not redirect a second time.\\nWhen rs1 is waiting on an older instruction in ID/EX or EX/MEM, or when the\\nbackend is ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-006-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Return-Address Stack JALR Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best frontend already predicts backward conditional branches and\\ndirect JAL targets in IF, which removes most loop-back and direct-call\\ncontrol bubbles. The remaining obvious predictor hole is JALR: every return\\nstill resolves in EX and forces the same wrong-path flush even though CoreMark\\nuses direct calls paired with register-indirect returns. A tiny return-address\\nstack targets that specific loss with lower timing risk than another indexed\\nbranch table, because IF only needs to recognize the canonical return\\nencoding and mux in a registered stack top.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best frontend already predicts backward conditional branches and\\ndirect JAL targets in IF, which removes most loop-back and direct-call\\ncontrol bubbles. The remaining obvious predictor hole is JALR: every return\\nstill resolves in EX and forces the same wrong-path flush even though CoreMark\\nuses direct calls paired with register-indirect returns. A tiny return-address\\nstack targets that specific loss with lower timing risk than another indexed\\nbranch table, because IF only needs to recognize the canonical return\\nencoding and mux in a registered stack top.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small non-speculative return-address stack for link-register control\\nflow. When a valid non-trapping JAL or JALR call with rd=x1 or rd=x5 advances\\nthrough EX, push pc+4 into a 4-entry stack. When a valid canonical return\\nJALR with rd=x0, rs1=x1 or rs1=x5, funct3=000, and imm=0 advances through EX,\\npop one entry. In IF, recognize the same canonical return instruction and,\\nwhen the stack is non-empty, predict the next PC as the stack top using the\\nexisting predicted_taken/predicted_target metadata path. Change JALR redirect\\ngeneration in EX to the same resolved-next-PC mismatch check used for\\npredicted JALs: unpredicted or incorrectly predicted JA... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-007-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Explicit MEM Byte-Lane Steering\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best RTL still leaves a small but likely timing-relevant barrel\\nshifter in the MEM stage: load data is selected with `dmem_rdata >>\\n(addr[1:0] * 8)`, and store byte masks are formed with variable shifts.\\nOn an FPGA this is usually inferred as wider mux/shifter logic than needed,\\neven though RV32I memory accesses only need four fixed byte lanes and two\\nlegal halfword lanes. CoreMark is load/store heavy, and the dmem read-data\\nto MEM/WB path can compete with the EX ALU path for Fmax. A lane-case rewrite\\nis a narrow micro-optimization that should not affect IPC, branch prediction,\\nmemory ordering, RVFI retirement, or any RV32IM arithmetic behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best RTL still leaves a small but likely timing-relevant barrel\\nshifter in the MEM stage: load data is selected with `dmem_rdata >>\\n(addr[1:0] * 8)`, and store byte masks are formed with variable shifts.\\nOn an FPGA this is usually inferred as wider mux/shifter logic than needed,\\neven though RV32I memory accesses only need four fixed byte lanes and two\\nlegal halfword lanes. CoreMark is load/store heavy, and the dmem read-data\\nto MEM/WB path can compete with the EX ALU path for Fmax. A lane-case rewrite\\nis a narrow micro-optimization that should not affect IPC, branch prediction,\\nmemory ordering, RVFI retirement, or any RV32IM arithmetic behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rewrite `rtl/mem_stage