. A late store-data bypass\\ntargets a useful subset of those bubbles while keeping load data off the ALU,\\nbranch compare, and JALR critical paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Allow a legal STORE immediately after a LOAD to proceed without the normal\\nload-use bubble when the load destination matches only the STORE rs2 data\\nfield and not the STORE rs1 address field. The store computes its address in\\nEX as usual, carries its rs2 register number into MEM, and selects the final\\nstore data in MEM from the MEM/WB writeback value when that older i... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-009-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny Forward-Branch Override Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best frontend already predicts backward conditional branches and\\ndirect JAL targets in IF, reaching 324.48 fitness. The 64-entry agree\\npredictor experiment showed that residual conditional-branch misses still\\nmatter: it reduced CoreMark cycles from 4,259,699 to 4,194,484, but the\\nlarger always-consulted table cost enough Fmax to regress overall fitness.\\nThat result points to a narrower predictor: keep the proven BTFNT and direct\\nJAL behavior intact, but learn only the static predictor's most expensive\\nblind spot, biased forward conditional branches. A tiny forward-only override\\nshould retain much of the cycle-count gain with far less table area, fanout,\\nand IF routing pressure than the full agree predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best frontend already predicts backward conditional branches and\\ndirect JAL targets in IF, reaching 324.48 fitness. The 64-entry agree\\npredictor experiment showed that residual conditional-branch misses still\\nmatter: it reduced CoreMark cycles from 4,259,699 to 4,194,484, but the\\nlarger always-consulted table cost enough Fmax to regress overall fitness.\\nThat result points to a narrower predictor: keep the proven BTFNT and direct\\nJAL behavior intact, but learn only the static predictor's most expensive\\nblind spot, biased forward conditional branches. A tiny forward-only override\\nshould retain much of the cycle-count gain with far less table area, fanout,\\nand IF routing pressure than the full agree predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 16-entry PC-indexed two-bit saturating override table that is consulted\\nonly for legal, aligned, forward B-type conditional branches. Backward\\nbranches keep the current static taken prediction, and direct JAL prediction\\nremains unchanged. Forward branches cold-start as strongly not-taken so the\\nreset behavior exactly matches the current... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-010-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Cold Multi-Cycle DIV/REM Unit\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core still keeps DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU in the same\\ncombinational EX-stage ALU result path as ADD, address generation, branch\\ncompare support, and MUL. The generated FPGA critical paths are dominated by\\nlong EX-stage carry/mux structures, while the CoreMark timed loop is\\neffectively division-cold: the static binary has only a few DIVU sites, and\\nthose are in setup/printing paths rather than the hot matrix/list/state\\niteration body. Prior multiplier and MEM-lane rewrites showed that reshaping\\nalready-mapped hot datapaths can badly hurt placement; the better\\nmicro-optimization is to remove the cold divider/remainder hardware from the\\none-cycle ALU path entirely while leaving multiply and all RV32I operations\\nsingle-cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core still keeps DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU in the same\\ncombinational EX-stage ALU result path as ADD, address generation, branch\\ncompare support, and MUL. The generated FPGA critical paths are dominated by\\nlong EX-stage carry/mux structures, while the CoreMark timed loop is\\neffectively division-cold: the static binary has only a few DIVU sites, and\\nthose are in setup/printing paths rather than the hot matrix/list/state\\niteration body. Prior multiplier and MEM-lane rewrites showed that reshaping\\nalready-mapped hot datapaths can badly hurt placement; the better\\nmicro-optimization is to remove the cold divider/remainder hardware from the\\none-cycle ALU path entirely while leaving multiply and all RV32I operations\\nsingle-cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the real combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases with a small\\niterative divider/remainder unit that is only entered for those four ALU\\nopcodes. Normal RV32I operations, branches, jumps, loads/stores, and all MUL\\nvariants remain one-cycle and keep the current forwarding behavior. When a\\ndivide-class instruction reaches... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-011-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Registered Fetch/Decode Cutpoint\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core still has no real IF/ID register: the PC drives imem, the returned instruction is decoded, the register file is read, and the ID/EX register captures the result in one cycle. That preserves a short frontend latency, but it also leaves a large structural timing path through instruction memory data, IF prediction decode, full instruction decode, immediate generation, and regfile read fanout. Prior elastic-fetch work kept an empty-buffer bypass to avoid latency, so it retained much of this path and lost Fmax. A cleaner structural bet is to deliberately insert the missing fetch/decode cutpoint and trade one extra frontend pipeline stage for a higher median FPGA clock.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core still has no real IF/ID register: the PC drives imem, the returned instruction is decoded, the register file is read, and the ID/EX register captures the result in one cycle. That preserves a short frontend latency, but it also leaves a large structural timing path through instruction memory data, IF prediction decode, full instruction decode, immediate generation, and regfile read fanout. Prior elastic-fetch work kept an empty-buffer bypass to avoid latency, so it retained much of this path and lost Fmax. A cleaner structural bet is to deliberately insert the missing fetch/decode cutpoint and trade one extra frontend pipeline stage for a higher median FPGA clock.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert the IF/ID handoff into a real registered pipeline boundary with no zero-latency imem-data-to-decode bypass. IF captures {pc, instr, predicted_taken, predicted_target, valid} when io_imemReady is high and the decode side can accept an entry; ID decodes only the registered entry on the following cycle. Redirects and reset flush the IF/ID register and restart fetch at the resolved target, while load-use and dmem stalls hold the re... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-012-r6s2\", \"title\": \"experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260428-012-r6s2.yaml\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"schema_error: 1.5 is not of type 'integer'\\n\\nFailed validating 'type' in schema['properties']['expected_impact']['properties']['fitness_delta_pct']:\\n    {'type': 'integer'}\\n\\nOn instance['expected_impact']['fitness_delta_pct']:\\n    1.5\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 6, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor stack is static backward-branch taken plus IF\\ndirect-JAL prediction. Attempts to add broader learned conditional-branch\\npredictors improved CoreMark cycle count but lost more Fmax than they gained,\\nwhile the 4-entry RAS also regressed because it added stack state, push/pop\\nbookkeeping, and enough IF routing to lower median Fmax. The useful signal\\nfrom the RAS experiment is that returns exist in the timed path, but the\\npredictor must be much narrower and cheaper than a general stack.\\n\\nA one-entry last-return target predictor targets the same remaining JALR\\nhole with less state and less control. CoreMark's hot call/return behavior is\\ntypically dominated by repeated returns from stable call sites, so a single\\ncached canonical-return target can remove many return flushes without a BTB,\\nbranch table, multi-entry stack, or speculative architectural state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry return target cache in IF. When EX resolves a valid,\\nnon-trapping canonical return JALR (`jalr x0, 0(x1)` or `jalr x0, 0(x5)`),\\nrecord the return instruction PC and its resolved next PC. When IF later\\nfetches the same canonical return PC and the entry is valid, predict the\\ncached target through the existing `predicted_taken` / `predicted_target`\\nmetadata path. Change JALR redirect generation to the same resolved-next-PC\\nmismatch check used for predicted JALs, so correctly predicted cached returns\\ndo not flush and all other JALRs retain the current EX re... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-013-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Cold High-Half Multiply Unit\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best result came from moving cold DIV/REM hardware out of the\\nuniversal EX-stage ALU path: CoreMark cycles barely changed, while median\\nFmax rose sharply and LUT pressure dropped. The same shape remains in the\\nmultiply path, but with a narrower target. `rtl/alu.sv` still builds three\\nindependent 64-bit products every cycle for MUL, MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU.\\nCoreMark's timed kernels need ordinary low-half MUL, but high-half multiply\\nvariants are normally absent or cold in this benchmark. The previous 33x33\\nshared-multiplier rewrite proved that reshaping the hot MUL primitive itself\\ncan badly hurt placement, so the better micro-optimization is to leave the\\nexisting low-half MUL fast path intact and remove only the cold high-half\\nmultiplier variants from the one-cycle ALU.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best result came from moving cold DIV/REM hardware out of the\\nuniversal EX-stage ALU path: CoreMark cycles barely changed, while median\\nFmax rose sharply and LUT pressure dropped. The same shape remains in the\\nmultiply path, but with a narrower target. `rtl/alu.sv` still builds three\\nindependent 64-bit products every cycle for MUL, MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU.\\nCoreMark's timed kernels need ordinary low-half MUL, but high-half multiply\\nvariants are normally absent or cold in this benchmark. The previous 33x33\\nshared-multiplier rewrite proved that reshaping the hot MUL primitive itself\\ncan badly hurt placement, so the better micro-optimization is to leave the\\nexisting low-half MUL fast path intact and remove only the cold high-half\\nmultiplier variants from the one-cycle ALU.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep ALU_MUL as the only single-cycle hardware multiply in the hot ALU path,\\nusing the existing unsigned 32x32 product low half. Move MULH, MULHU, and\\nMULHSU into a small long-latency `mulh_unit` launched only for those three\\no... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/v1/experiments/log.jsonl","time":{"start":1778754001869,"end":1778754001875}},"id":"prt_e26001980001B3LodKTWDqxhMl","sessionID":"ses_1da081598ffelSLGjQATF56q6S","messageID":"msg_e25ffeaba001uccx0QgExs2QJv"}}
