onical return instruction and,\\nwhen the stack is non-empty, predict the next PC as the stack top using the\\nexisting predicted_taken/predicted_target metadata path. Change JALR redirect\\ngeneration in EX to the same resolved-next-PC mismatch check used for\\npredicted JALs: unpredicted or incorrectly predicted JA...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-007-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Explicit MEM Byte-Lane Steering\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best RTL still leaves a small but likely timing-relevant barrel\\nshifter in the MEM stage: load data is selected with `dmem_rdata >>\\n(addr[1:0] * 8)`, and store byte masks are formed with variable shifts.\\nOn an FPGA this is usually inferred as wider mux/shifter logic than needed,\\neven though RV32I memory accesses only need four fixed byte lanes and two\\nlegal halfword lanes. CoreMark is load/store heavy, and the dmem read-data\\nto MEM/WB path can compete with the EX ALU path for Fmax. A lane-case rewrite\\nis a narrow micro-optimization that should not affect IPC, branch prediction,\\nmemory ordering, RVFI retirement, or any RV32IM arithmetic behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best RTL still leaves a small but likely timing-relevant barrel\\nshifter in the MEM stage: load data is selected with `dmem_rdata >>\\n(addr[1:0] * 8)`, and store byte masks are formed with variable shifts.\\nOn an FPGA this is usually inferred as wider mux/shifter logic than needed,\\neven though RV32I memory accesses only need four fixed byte lanes and two\\nlegal halfword lanes. CoreMark is load/store heavy, and the dmem read-data\\nto MEM/WB path can compete with the EX ALU path for Fmax. A lane-case rewrite\\nis a narrow micro-optimization that should not affect IPC, branch prediction,\\nmemory ordering, RVFI retirement, or any RV32IM arithmetic behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rewrite `rtl/mem_stage.sv` to decode `in.alu_result[1:0]` explicitly for\\nbyte/halfword steering instead of using variable shifts. Build `byte_val`,\\n`hword_val`, `byte_mask`, and replicated store data from small `case` tables\\nover the low address bits and access width. Preserve the existing misalignment\\ntrap rules, dmem gating on traps, RVFI aligned `mem_addr`, raw `mem_rdata`,\\nreplicated `mem_wdata`, and exact load sign/zero extension semantics. The\\nexpected gain is a mode...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-008-r5s1\", \"title\": \"MEM-Stage Store-Data Forwarding\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core still treats every immediate load-use match as a\\nfull one-cycle interlock, including the common case where the younger\\ninstruction is a STORE that only needs the loaded register as store data\\n(rs2), not as the address base (rs1). That bubble is structurally avoidable:\\nstore data is not consumed by the EX ALU, and the actual dmem write data is\\nformed one stage later in MEM. The prior full MEM-to-EX load bypass showed\\nthat CoreMark has meaningful load-use pressure, but it lost too much Fmax by\\nrouting dmem load data into the EX operand muxes. A late store-data bypass\\ntargets a useful subset of those bubbles while keeping load data off the ALU,\\nbranch compare, and JALR critical paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core still treats every immediate load-use match as a\\nfull one-cycle interlock, including the common case where the younger\\ninstruction is a STORE that only needs the loaded register as store data\\n(rs2), not as the address base (rs1). That bubble is structurally avoidable:\\nstore data is not consumed by the EX ALU, and the actual dmem write data is\\nformed one stage later in MEM. The prior full MEM-to-EX load bypass showed\\nthat CoreMark has meaningful load-use pressure, but it lost too much Fmax by\\nrouting dmem load data into the EX operand muxes. A late store-data bypass\\ntargets a useful subset of those bubbles while keeping load data off the ALU,\\nbranch compare, and JALR critical paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Allow a legal STORE immediately after a LOAD to proceed without the normal\\nload-use bubble when the load destination matches only the STORE rs2 data\\nfield and not the STORE rs1 address field. The store computes its address in\\nEX as usual, carries its rs2 register number into MEM, and selects the final\\nstore data in MEM from the MEM/WB writeback value when that older i...\n  Line 16: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-009-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny Forward-Branch Override Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best frontend already predicts backward conditional branches and\\ndirect JAL targets in IF, reaching 324.48 fitness. The 64-entry agree\\npredictor experiment showed that residual conditional-branch misses still\\nmatter: it reduced CoreMark cycles from 4,259,699 to 4,194,484, but the\\nlarger always-consulted table cost enough Fmax to regress overall fitness.\\nThat result points to a narrower predictor: keep the proven BTFNT and direct\\nJAL behavior intact, but learn only the static predictor's most expensive\\nblind spot, biased forward conditional branches. A tiny forward-only override\\nshould retain much of the cycle-count gain with far less table area, fanout,\\nand IF routing pressure than the full agree predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best frontend already predicts backward conditional branches and\\ndirect JAL targets in IF, reaching 324.48 fitness. The 64-entry agree\\npredictor experiment showed that residual conditional-branch misses still\\nmatter: it reduced CoreMark cycles from 4,259,699 to 4,194,484, but the\\nlarger always-consulted table cost enough Fmax to regress overall fitness.\\nThat result points to a narrower predictor: keep the proven BTFNT and direct\\nJAL behavior intact, but learn only the static predictor's most expensive\\nblind spot, biased forward conditional branches. A tiny forward-only override\\nshould retain much of the cycle-count gain with far less table area, fanout,\\nand IF routing pressure than the full agree predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 16-entry PC-indexed two-bit saturating override table that is consulted\\nonly for legal, aligned, forward B-type conditional branches. Backward\\nbranches keep the current static taken prediction, and direct JAL prediction\\nremains unchanged. Forward branches cold-start as strongly not-taken so the\\nreset behavior exactly matches the current...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-010-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Cold Multi-Cycle DIV/REM Unit\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core still keeps DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU in the same\\ncombinational EX-stage ALU result path as ADD, address generation, branch\\ncompare support, and MUL. The generated FPGA critical paths are dominated by\\nlong EX-stage carry/mux structures, while the CoreMark timed loop is\\neffectively division-cold: the static binary has only a few DIVU sites, and\\nthose are in setup/printing paths rather than the hot matrix/list/state\\niteration body. Prior multiplier and MEM-lane rewrites showed that reshaping\\nalready-mapped hot datapaths can badly hurt placement; the better\\nmicro-optimization is to remove the cold divider/remainder hardware from the\\none-cycle ALU path entirely while leaving multiply and all RV32I operations\\nsingle-cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core still keeps DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU in the same\\ncombinational EX-stage ALU result path as ADD, address generation, branch\\ncompare support, and MUL. The generated FPGA critical paths are dominated by\\nlong EX-stage carry/mux structures, while the CoreMark timed loop is\\neffectively division-cold: the static binary has only a few DIVU sites, and\\nthose are in setup/printing paths rather than the hot matrix/list/state\\niteration body. Prior multiplier and MEM-lane rewrites showed that reshaping\\nalready-mapped hot datapaths can badly hurt placement; the better\\nmicro-optimization is to remove the cold divider/remainder hardware from the\\none-cycle ALU path entirely while leaving multiply and all RV32I operations\\nsingle-cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the real combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases with a small\\niterative divider/remainder unit that is only entered for those four ALU\\nopcodes. Normal RV32I operations, branches, jumps, loads/stores, and all MUL\\nvariants remain one-cycle and keep the current forwarding behavior. When a\\ndivide-class instruction reaches...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-011-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Registered Fetch/Decode Cutpoint\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core still has no real IF/ID register: the PC drives imem, the returned instruction is decoded, the register file is read, and the ID/EX register captures the result in one cycle. That preserves a short frontend latency, but it also leaves a large structural timing path through instruction memory data, IF prediction decode, full instruction decode, immediate generation, and regfile read fanout. Prior elastic-fetch work kept an empty-buffer bypass to avoid latency, so it retained much of this path and lost Fmax. A cleaner structural bet is to deliberately insert the missing fetch/decode cutpoint and trade one extra frontend pipeline stage for a higher median FPGA clock.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core still has no real IF/ID register: the PC drives imem, the returned instruction is decoded, the register file is read, and the ID/EX register captures the result in one cycle. That preserves a short frontend latency, but it also leaves a large structural timing path through instruction memory data, IF prediction decode, full instruction decode, immediate generation, and regfile read fanout. Prior elastic-fetch work kept an empty-buffer bypass to avoid latency, so it retained much of this path and lost Fmax. A cleaner structural bet is to deliberately insert the missing fetch/decode cutpoint and trade one extra frontend pipeline stage for a higher median FPGA clock.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert the IF/ID handoff into a real registered pipeline boundary with no zero-latency imem-data-to-decode bypass. IF captures {pc, instr, predicted_taken, predicted_target, valid} when io_imemReady is high and the decode side can accept an entry; ID decodes only the registered entry on the following cycle. Redirects and reset flush the IF/ID register and restart fetch at the resolved target, while load-use and dmem stalls hold the re...\n  Line 20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-013-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Cold High-Half Multiply Unit\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best result came from moving cold DIV/REM hardware out of the\\nuniversal EX-stage ALU path: CoreMark cycles barely changed, while median\\nFmax rose sharply and LUT pressure dropped. The same shape remains in the\\nmultiply path, but with a narrower target. `rtl/alu.sv` still builds three\\nindependent 64-bit products every cycle for MUL, MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU.\\nCoreMark's timed kernels need ordinary low-half MUL, but high-half multiply\\nvariants are normally absent or cold in this benchmark. The previous 33x33\\nshared-multiplier rewrite proved that reshaping the hot MUL primitive itself\\ncan badly hurt placement, so the better micro-optimization is to leave the\\nexisting low-half MUL fast path intact and remove only the cold high-half\\nmultiplier variants from the one-cycle ALU.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best result came from moving cold DIV/REM hardware out of the\\nuniversal EX-stage ALU path: CoreMark cycles barely changed, while median\\nFmax rose sharply and LUT pressure dropped. The same shape remains in the\\nmultiply path, but with a narrower target. `rtl/alu.sv` still builds three\\nindependent 64-bit products every cycle for MUL, MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU.\\nCoreMark's timed kernels need ordinary low-half MUL, but high-half multiply\\nvariants are normally absent or cold in this benchmark. The previous 33x33\\nshared-multiplier rewrite proved that reshaping the hot MUL primitive itself\\ncan badly hurt placement, so the better micro-optimization is to leave the\\nexisting low-half MUL fast path intact and remove only the cold high-half\\nmultiplier variants from the one-cycle ALU.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep ALU_MUL as the only single-cycle hardware multiply in the hot ALU path,\\nusing the existing unsigned 32x32 product low half. Move MULH, MULHU, and\\nMULHSU into a small long-latency `mulh_unit` launched only for those three\\no...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-014-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Single-Entry Retiring Store Buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core gained a large Fmax and LUT win by moving DIV/REM out\\nof the hot EX path, so the next structural bottleneck is less likely to be\\nraw datapath area and more likely to be cycles lost to the random dmem\\nhandshake model. Today every dmem-not-ready cycle for a STORE freezes the\\nwhole pipeline, even though the store address, replicated data, byte mask,\\nand RVFI memory metadata are already known in MEM and the store produces no\\nregister result for younger ALU/control instructions. A prior two-entry\\nstore buffer proved the idea through formal and cosim but failed placement\\non the larger pre-DIV RTL. A smaller one-entry RAM-store buffer should retain\\nmost of the useful stall hiding while keeping the arbitration, state, and\\nplacement pressure low enough for the post-DIV design.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core gained a large Fmax and LUT win by moving DIV/REM out\\nof the hot EX path, so the next structural bottleneck is less likely to be\\nraw datapath area and more likely to be cycles lost to the random dmem\\nhandshake model. Today every dmem-not-ready cycle for a STORE freezes the\\nwhole pipeline, even though the store address, replicated data, byte mask,\\nand RVFI memory metadata are already known in MEM and the store produces no\\nregister result for younger ALU/control instructions. A prior two-entry\\nstore buffer proved the idea through formal and cosim but failed placement\\non the larger pre-DIV RTL. A smaller one-entry RAM-store buffer should retain\\nmost of the useful stall hiding while keeping the arbitration, state, and\\nplacement pressure low enough for the post-DIV design.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add one in-order retiring store slot for legal aligned stores to normal RAM\\nonly. When such a store reaches MEM and io_dmemReady is low, capture its\\nbyte address, replicated write data, byte mask, and RV...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-015-r7s2\", \"title\": \"One-Entry Return Target Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best RTL already predicts backward conditional branches and\\ndirect JAL targets in IF, and the latest winning change moved cold DIV/REM\\noff the critical ALU path. The predictor slot should therefore avoid broad\\nlearned branch tables that have already shown a bad cycle-count versus Fmax\\ntradeoff: the 64-entry agree table and 16-entry forward override both reduced\\nCoreMark cycles but lost more clock than they recovered.\\n\\nThe remaining high-value predictor miss is JALR return control flow. The\\n4-entry RAS experiment showed returns exist in the timed path, but its stack\\nbookkeeping and IF routing were still too expensive. A single tagged return\\ntarget entry is a narrower bet: it targets recurring canonical return PCs\\nwith one PC tag, one target register, and one IF compare, avoiding a BTB,\\nmulti-entry stack, or conditional-branch table.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best RTL already predicts backward conditional branches and\\ndirect JAL targets in IF, and the latest winning change moved cold DIV/REM\\noff the critical ALU path. The predictor slot should therefore avoid broad\\nlearned branch tables that have already shown a bad cycle-count versus Fmax\\ntradeoff: the 64-entry agree table and 16-entry forward override both reduced\\nCoreMark cycles but lost more clock than they recovered.\\n\\nThe remaining high-value predictor miss is JALR return control flow. The\\n4-entry RAS experiment showed returns exist in the timed path, but its stack\\nbookkeeping and IF routing were still too expensive. A single tagged return\\ntarget entry is a narrower bet: it targets recurring canonical return PCs\\nwith one PC tag, one target register, and one IF compare, avoiding a BTB,\\nmulti-entry stack, or conditional-branch table.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry return target predictor for canonical return JALRs. When EX\\nresolves a valid...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-016-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Reset-Valid LUTRAM Register File\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The post-DIV best core has removed the largest cold arithmetic block from\\nthe EX critical path, so the next micro-optimization should target FPGA\\nplacement pressure without changing CoreMark cycles. The current register\\nfile is a 32x32 array with a synchronous reset loop that clears every data\\nbit. That resettable array is likely implemented as ordinary flip-flops or\\nreset-muxed logic instead of compact distributed RAM, adding roughly 1024\\nresettable state bits plus reset fanout to the already timing-sensitive\\nfetch/decode/register-read region.\\n\\nArchitectural software only needs the externally visible reset behavior of\\nreading zero before a register has been written. It does not require the\\nphysical register data array itself to be synchronously cleared. A valid-zero\\nmask can preserve the current tests and reset semantics while allowing the\\n32x32 data storage to become resetless.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The post-DIV best core has removed the largest cold arithmetic block from\\nthe EX critical path, so the next micro-optimization should target FPGA\\nplacement pressure without changing CoreMark cycles. The current register\\nfile is a 32x32 array with a synchronous reset loop that clears every data\\nbit. That resettable array is likely implemented as ordinary flip-flops or\\nreset-muxed logic instead of compact distributed RAM, adding roughly 1024\\nresettable state bits plus reset fanout to the already timing-sensitive\\nfetch/decode/register-read region.\\n\\nArchitectural software only needs the externally visible reset behavior of\\nreading zero before a register has been written. It does not require the\\nphysical register data array itself to be synchronously cleared. A valid-zero\\nmask can preserve the current tests and reset semantics while allowing the\\n32x32 data storage to become resetless.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the regist...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-017-r8s1\", \"title\": \"One-Deep Store Retirement Slot With Direct Fast Path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core is dominated by the post-DIV/REM timing shape, with\\nmedian Fmax now high enough that broad datapath changes have mostly hurt\\nplacement. The remaining structural opportunity with measured evidence is\\nstore backpressure: the previous one-entry store buffer reduced CoreMark\\ncycles from 4,259,618 to 4,226,169, but its dmem arbitration and MEM-stage\\nmuxing cost slightly more Fmax than the cycle gain recovered.\\n\\nThe promising angle is therefore not a larger buffer, but a smaller and more\\ntiming-local retiring store slot. Keep the zero-wait store path identical to\\nthe current best design, and add state only for the uncommon case where a\\nnormal RAM store reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. That targets the same\\nrandom-dStall cycles as the prior structural attempt while avoiding a\\npermanent dmem-port mux on every load/store cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core is dominated by the post-DIV/REM timing shape, with\\nmedian Fmax now high enough that broad datapath changes have mostly hurt\\nplacement. The remaining structural opportunity with measured evidence is\\nstore backpressure: the previous one-entry store buffer reduced CoreMark\\ncycles from 4,259,618 to 4,226,169, but its dmem arbitration and MEM-stage\\nmuxing cost slightly more Fmax than the cycle gain recovered.\\n\\nThe promising angle is therefore not a larger buffer, but a smaller and more\\ntiming-local retiring store slot. Keep the zero-wait store path identical to\\nthe current best design, and add state only for the uncommon case where a\\nnormal RAM store reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. That targets the same\\nrandom-dStall cycles as the prior structural attempt while avoiding a\\npermanent dmem-port mux on every load/store cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-deep pending-store retirement slot that is used only on a...\n  Line 25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-018-r8s2\", \"title\": \"Funct3-Biased Static Branch Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best frontend already has the two predictor features that have\\nactually paid off: backward conditional branches predict taken, and direct\\nJAL targets are predicted in IF. The learned predictor attempts point in the\\nother direction: both the 64-entry agree table and the 16-entry forward-only\\noverride table reduced CoreMark cycles, but their table read/update routing\\ncost more Fmax than the saved mispredicts recovered. Return prediction was\\neven less attractive after the post-DIV timing win, with only small cycle\\nsavings and a large clock regression.\\n\\nThe remaining promising predictor angle is therefore a zero-state refinement\\nof the static conditional-branch rule. A quick dynamic profile of the timed\\nCoreMark region shows that the baseline BTFNT rule is especially wrong for\\ntwo simple branch classes: backward BEQ branches, which are mostly not taken\\nin this binary, and forward BNE branches, which are usually taken. Those two\\nclasses account for a large fraction of residual static predictor mistakes,\\nand they can be recognized from the funct3 bits already examined in IF for\\nbranch legality. This targets iterations/cycle without adding a predictor\\nRAM, update feedback path, BTB, RAS, or extra target adder.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best frontend already has the two predictor features that have\\nactually paid off: backward conditional branches predict taken, and direct\\nJAL targets are predicted in IF. The learned predictor attempts point in the\\nother direction: both the 64-entry agree table and the 16-entry forward-only\\noverride table reduced CoreMark cycles, but their table read/update routing\\ncost more Fmax than the saved mispredicts recovered. Return prediction was\\neven less attractive after the post-DIV timing win, with only small cycle\\nsavings and a large clock regression.\\n\\nThe remaining p...\n  Line 27: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-020-r9s1\", \"title\": \"Store-Slot-Aware Fetch Skid Queue\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best design combines the two changes that have paid off most:\\ncold DIV/REM is off the universal EX path, and a one-deep pending-store slot\\nlets a stalled normal-RAM store retire while the physical dmem write drains\\nlater. That store slot reduced CoreMark cycles, but the frontend is still\\nstructurally brittle under the tournament's random imem stalls: `if_stage`\\npresents live imem data directly to decode, and `hazard_unit` still turns\\nraw `io_imemReady=0` into a global pipeline stall.\\n\\nA previous generic elastic fetch buffer regressed because it added permanent\\nfrontend queue/arbitration cost before the divider and store-slot timing\\nwins, and it tried to prefetch through all backend stalls. The better\\nstructural angle now is narrower: use a tiny fetch skid queue only to absorb\\ninstruction-memory backpressure and to keep fetch productive while the new\\nstore slot is draining for older stores. This targets the measured\\nstore-slot cycle win's remaining companion bottleneck without touching the\\nhot EX operand path, load data forwarding, branch predictor state, or RVFI\\nretirement width.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best design combines the two changes that have paid off most:\\ncold DIV/REM is off the universal EX path, and a one-deep pending-store slot\\nlets a stalled normal-RAM store retire while the physical dmem write drains\\nlater. That store slot reduced CoreMark cycles, but the frontend is still\\nstructurally brittle under the tournament's random imem stalls: `if_stage`\\npresents live imem data directly to decode, and `hazard_unit` still turns\\nraw `io_imemReady=0` into a global pipeline stall.\\n\\nA previous generic elastic fetch buffer regressed because it added permanent\\nfrontend queue/arbitration cost before the divider and store-slot timing\\nwins, and it tried to prefetch through all backend stalls. T...\n  Line 28: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-021-r9s2\", \"title\": \"X1 Last-Call Return Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best RTL already has the predictor features that have proven\\nuseful without excessive timing cost: backward conditional branches are\\npredicted taken and direct JAL targets are predicted in IF. Broader learned\\ndirection tables did reduce CoreMark cycles, but the IF table read and EX\\nupdate routing cost more Fmax than the saved redirects recovered. The return\\npredictor attempts also showed that return bubbles exist, but the 4-entry\\nstack and the PC-tagged one-entry cache added too much frontend comparison,\\nbookkeeping, and routing.\\n\\nThe narrow remaining predictor opportunity is to keep only the useful part\\nof a return-address stack: the standard ABI link register x1. CoreMark is\\ncompiled as ordinary RV32IM C code, so direct calls write x1 and returns are\\ncanonical `jalr x0, 0(x1)`. A single last-call target register can predict\\nthe common innermost return without a BTB, tag compare, multi-entry stack, or\\nconditional-branch table. It intentionally gives up nested-return coverage in\\nexchange for a much smaller IF critical-path footprint.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best RTL already has the predictor features that have proven\\nuseful without excessive timing cost: backward conditional branches are\\npredicted taken and direct JAL targets are predicted in IF. Broader learned\\ndirection tables did reduce CoreMark cycles, but the IF table read and EX\\nupdate routing cost more Fmax than the saved redirects recovered. The return\\npredictor attempts also showed that return bubbles exist, but the 4-entry\\nstack and the PC-tagged one-entry cache added too much frontend comparison,\\nbookkeeping, and routing.\\n\\nThe narrow remaining predictor opportunity is to keep only the useful part\\nof a return-address stack: the standard ABI link register x1. CoreMark is\\ncompiled as ordinary RV32IM C code, so direct calls write x1 and r...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-022-r10s0\", \"title\": \"Collapse Redundant EX/MEM Metadata\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best RTL already captured the large available wins: cold\\nDIV/REM is out of the one-cycle ALU path, and the pending store slot reduces\\nrandom dmem-stall exposure. The remaining micro-opt slot should therefore\\navoid new predictors, queues, or arithmetic units and instead trim logic that\\nis already proven unnecessary on the hot pipeline boundary.\\n\\nThe EX/MEM bundle still carries several fields that do not add architectural\\ninformation. `write_data` is always assigned the same post-forwarded rs2\\nvalue as `rs2_val`, while `branch_taken` and `branch_target` are registered\\nbut never consumed by MEM, WB, RVFI, forwarding, or hazard logic. Those bits\\nadd about 65 EX/MEM flops plus mux/load on the EX branch-target and rs2 data\\npaths, exactly where the post-DIV design is trying to preserve Fmax. Pruning\\nthis redundant metadata should not change CoreMark cycles, bus behavior,\\nbranch prediction, RVFI ordering, or any ISA-visible result.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best RTL already captured the large available wins: cold\\nDIV/REM is out of the one-cycle ALU path, and the pending store slot reduces\\nrandom dmem-stall exposure. The remaining micro-opt slot should therefore\\navoid new predictors, queues, or arithmetic units and instead trim logic that\\nis already proven unnecessary on the hot pipeline boundary.\\n\\nThe EX/MEM bundle still carries several fields that do not add architectural\\ninformation. `write_data` is always assigned the same post-forwarded rs2\\nvalue as `rs2_val`, while `branch_taken` and `branch_target` are registered\\nbut never consumed by MEM, WB, RVFI, forwarding, or hazard logic. Those bits\\nadd about 65 EX/MEM flops plus mux/load on the EX branch-target and rs2 data\\npaths, exactly where the post-DIV design is trying to preserve Fmax. Pruning\\nthis redundant metadata should not change CoreMark cycl...\n  Line 30: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-023-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Stall-Only I-Fetch Replay Cache\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core has already removed the cold DIV/REM datapath from\\nEX and added a one-deep pending-store slot, so the remaining structural\\nloss is less about store backpressure and more about the instruction side\\nof the tournament's random bus model. Today `io_imemReady=0` still becomes\\na global frontend stall: the PC holds, IF emits a bubble, and decode cannot\\nuse an instruction even if the same hot-loop PC was fetched many times\\nearlier.\\n\\nThe previous fetch skid queues tried to decouple live imem traffic from\\ndecode, but they added permanent queue and PC-control logic on the zero-wait\\npath and lost too much Fmax. A better structural angle is a stall-only\\nreplay cache: keep the current direct live-imem path whenever the external\\nbus is ready, and consult a tiny cached copy only on cycles where imem would\\notherwise stall. CoreMark's timed code repeatedly executes the same matrix,\\nlist, state, CRC, and loop-control instructions over a 10-iteration run, so\\neven a small direct-mapped instruction replay table should turn many random\\niStall bubbles into normal fetch cycles after warmup.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core has already removed the cold DIV/REM datapath from\\nEX and added a one-deep pending-store slot, so the remaining structural\\nloss is less about store backpressure and more about the instruction side\\nof the tournament's random bus model. Today `io_imemReady=0` still becomes\\na global frontend stall: the PC holds, IF emits a bubble, and decode cannot\\nuse an instruction even if the same hot-loop PC was fetched many times\\nearlier.\\n\\nThe previous fetch skid queues tried to decouple live imem traffic from\\ndecode, but they added permanent queue and PC-control logic on the zero-wait\\npath and lost too much Fmax. A better structural angle is a stall-only\\nreplay cache: keep the current direct live-im...\n  Line 31: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-024-r10s2\", \"title\": \"Single-Adder Static Control Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor features are the simple ones that already paid\\nfor themselves: backward conditional branches are predicted taken and direct\\nJAL targets are predicted in IF. The learned direction tables and return\\npredictors reduced CoreMark cycles slightly, but each added enough IF-state,\\ncomparison, or EX-to-IF update routing to lose more Fmax than it recovered.\\n\\nThe remaining predictor opportunity is therefore to make the profitable\\nstatic predictor cheaper rather than adding more prediction state. Today\\n`if_stage` forms branch and JAL targets with two separate `pc + imm` adders\\nand uses the full adder results for target-alignment gating before choosing\\nthe next PC. Since B- and J-type immediates always have bit 0 clear, the\\ntarget alignment test can be derived from the encoded imm[1] bit and the PC\\nlow bits without waiting for a 32-bit target adder. Branch and JAL are also\\nmutually exclusive opcodes, so one selected-immediate target adder is enough.\\n\\nThis attacks predictor-path Fmax with no intended CoreMark cycle-count risk:\\nthe set of predicted conditional branches and direct JALs remains the same\\nas the current best design for all aligned PCs, and EX still repairs any\\nwrong prediction through the existing resolved-next-PC mismatch path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor features are the simple ones that already paid\\nfor themselves: backward conditional branches are predicted taken and direct\\nJAL targets are predicted in IF. The learned direction tables and return\\npredictors reduced CoreMark cycles slightly, but each added enough IF-state,\\ncomparison, or EX-to-IF update routing to lose more Fmax than it recovered.\\n\\nThe remaining predictor opportunity is therefore to make the profitable\\nstatic predictor cheaper rather than adding more prediction state. Today\\n`if_stage` forms bra...\n  Line 32: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-025-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Segmented RVFI Order Counter\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best design has already captured the large architectural wins:\\nDIV/REM is off the one-cycle EX path, and the one-deep store slot reduces\\nrandom dmem-stall exposure. Recent micro-opt attempts that reshaped hot\\ndatapaths, predictor target logic, or EX/MEM metadata mostly lost Fmax to\\nplacement noise or new muxing. The next micro-opt should therefore target a\\nguaranteed always-present timing structure without changing IPC.\\n\\nThe top-level RVFI order counter is currently a single 64-bit increment:\\n`rvfi_order_q <= rvfi_order_q + 64'b1` on every retirement. The FPGA\\nbenchmark wrapper intentionally retains RVFI fanout by XOR-reducing the RVFI\\noutputs into an LED, so this counter cannot be assumed dead in synthesis.\\nA 64-bit carry self-loop is not architectural work for the CoreMark datapath,\\nbut it can still consume carry-chain/routing budget and compete with the hot\\npipeline for median Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best design has already captured the large architectural wins:\\nDIV/REM is off the one-cycle EX path, and the one-deep store slot reduces\\nrandom dmem-stall exposure. Recent micro-opt attempts that reshaped hot\\ndatapaths, predictor target logic, or EX/MEM metadata mostly lost Fmax to\\nplacement noise or new muxing. The next micro-opt should therefore target a\\nguaranteed always-present timing structure without changing IPC.\\n\\nThe top-level RVFI order counter is currently a single 64-bit increment:\\n`rvfi_order_q <= rvfi_order_q + 64'b1` on every retirement. The FPGA\\nbenchmark wrapper intentionally retains RVFI fanout by XOR-reducing the RVFI\\noutputs into an LED, so this counter cannot be assumed dead in synthesis.\\nA 64-bit carry self-loop is not architectural work for the CoreMark datapath,\\nbut it can still consume carry-chain/routing budget and compete with the hot\\npipeline for median Fmax.\\n\", ...\n  Line 33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-026-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Narrow Stall-Only I-Fetch Replay Cache\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core combines the two structural/timing wins that have\\nactually paid off: cold DIV/REM is off the one-cycle EX path, and the\\none-deep pending-store slot hides store-only dmem stalls without hurting the\\nready-store path. The remaining measured structural opportunity is on the\\ninstruction side. The 256-entry stall-only replay cache cut CoreMark cycles\\nfrom 4,226,169 to 3,459,314, showing that random iStall bubbles are a large\\npart of the remaining IPC loss, but its wide IF table/tag/data mux dropped\\nmedian Fmax enough to miss the current best.\\n\\nThat result points to a narrower replay structure rather than a broader\\nfetch queue. CoreMark's timed hot code repeatedly executes compact inner\\nloops and call bodies, so a smaller direct-mapped replay table should retain\\nmuch of the iStall hit-rate benefit while reducing the IF storage mux,\\ncomparator fanout, and PC-control load that hurt Fmax in the 256-entry\\nversion. This keeps the zero-wait path direct and targets only cycles that\\nwould otherwise be external imem stalls.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core combines the two structural/timing wins that have\\nactually paid off: cold DIV/REM is off the one-cycle EX path, and the\\none-deep pending-store slot hides store-only dmem stalls without hurting the\\nready-store path. The remaining measured structural opportunity is on the\\ninstruction side. The 256-entry stall-only replay cache cut CoreMark cycles\\nfrom 4,226,169 to 3,459,314, showing that random iStall bubbles are a large\\npart of the remaining IPC loss, but its wide IF table/tag/data mux dropped\\nmedian Fmax enough to miss the current best.\\n\\nThat result points to a narrower replay structure rather than a broader\\nfetch queue. CoreMark's timed hot code repeatedly executes compact inner\\nloops and call bodies, so a smaller direct-mapped replay t...\n  Line 34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-027-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Small Stall-Only I-Fetch Replay Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The predictor changes that have paid so far are the ones that avoid broad\\nlearned direction state: backward conditional branches and direct JAL targets\\nare predicted in IF, while the larger branch tables and return predictors\\nlost more Fmax than their cycle savings recovered. The one exception with a\\nlarge cycle signal was the stall-only instruction replay experiment: it cut\\nCoreMark cycles substantially by serving hot-loop instructions during random\\nimem stalls, but its 256-entry full-tag table pulled median Fmax below the\\ncurrent best.\\n\\nThat result suggests a narrower predictor, not a new branch-direction table.\\nCoreMark's timed region repeatedly executes a relatively small hot text\\nfootprint, so a smaller replay predictor should retain much of the random\\niStall hiding while shortening the IF tag/data muxes that hurt the 256-entry\\nattempt. This stays in the predictor slot because the table predicts the\\ninstruction word for the current PC only when the external fetch bus would\\notherwise provide no word; normal ready fetches still use live imem data.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The predictor changes that have paid so far are the ones that avoid broad\\nlearned direction state: backward conditional branches and direct JAL targets\\nare predicted in IF, while the larger branch tables and return predictors\\nlost more Fmax than their cycle savings recovered. The one exception with a\\nlarge cycle signal was the stall-only instruction replay experiment: it cut\\nCoreMark cycles substantially by serving hot-loop instructions during random\\nimem stalls, but its 256-entry full-tag table pulled median Fmax below the\\ncurrent best.\\n\\nThat result suggests a narrower predictor, not a new branch-direction table.\\nCoreMark's timed region repeatedly executes a relatively small hot text\\nfootprint, so a smaller replay predictor should reta...\n  Line 35: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-028-r12s0\", \"title\": \"Byte-Segmented RVFI Order Counter\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best result came from a pure timing micro-optimization: replacing\\nthe monolithic 64-bit RVFI order increment with four 16-bit counter chunks.\\nThat change did not alter CoreMark cycles, memory behavior, branch\\nprediction, divider latency, or retirement semantics, but it raised median\\nFmax enough to become the new best fitness. This strongly suggests the\\nRVFI-order feedback path is still visible to synthesis and placement because\\nthe FPGA wrapper keeps RVFI outputs alive.\\n\\nThe current implementation still has a 16-bit carry-chain self-loop in the\\nlow order chunk, and each retirement toggles that chunk. A narrower exact\\nchunk size is the most direct follow-up in the micro_opt slot: it targets the\\nsame measured timing structure that just paid off, avoids another datapath or\\npredictor rewrite, and should leave CoreMark iterations/cycle unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best result came from a pure timing micro-optimization: replacing\\nthe monolithic 64-bit RVFI order increment with four 16-bit counter chunks.\\nThat change did not alter CoreMark cycles, memory behavior, branch\\nprediction, divider latency, or retirement semantics, but it raised median\\nFmax enough to become the new best fitness. This strongly suggests the\\nRVFI-order feedback path is still visible to synthesis and placement because\\nthe FPGA wrapper keeps RVFI outputs alive.\\n\\nThe current implementation still has a 16-bit carry-chain self-loop in the\\nlow order chunk, and each retirement toggles that chunk. A narrower exact\\nchunk size is the most direct follow-up in the micro_opt slot: it targets the\\nsame measured timing structure that just paid off, avoids another datapath or\\npredictor rewrite, and should leave CoreMark iterations/cycle unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refine the RVFI order counter in `rtl/core.sv` from four 16-bit chunks t...\n  Line 36: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-029-r12s1\", \"title\": \"MEM-Stage Load Replay Buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core has already captured the two strongest proven wins:\\ncold DIV/REM is off the universal EX path, and the one-deep pending-store\\nslot hides store-only dmem backpressure while preserving the ready-store fast\\npath. The next structural bottleneck is therefore load-side dmem stalls. A\\nload whose word was recently read still freezes the whole pipeline whenever\\n`io_dmemReady` is low, even though CoreMark repeatedly touches a compact 6 KB\\nworking set across list, matrix, state, stack, and CRC code.\\n\\nInstruction replay experiments showed that serving repeated hot accesses\\nduring random bus stalls can cut many cycles, but putting a wide replay table\\nin IF cost too much Fmax. A smaller load replay structure in MEM attacks the\\nsame random-stall problem on the data side, where the lookup is off the\\nbranch/JAL predictor path and does not add load data to the EX operand muxes.\\nThis is a structural stall-hiding change, not a broader predictor or\\narithmetic rewrite.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core has already captured the two strongest proven wins:\\ncold DIV/REM is off the universal EX path, and the one-deep pending-store\\nslot hides store-only dmem backpressure while preserving the ready-store fast\\npath. The next structural bottleneck is therefore load-side dmem stalls. A\\nload whose word was recently read still freezes the whole pipeline whenever\\n`io_dmemReady` is low, even though CoreMark repeatedly touches a compact 6 KB\\nworking set across list, matrix, state, stack, and CRC code.\\n\\nInstruction replay experiments showed that serving repeated hot accesses\\nduring random bus stalls can cut many cycles, but putting a wide replay table\\nin IF cost too much Fmax. A smaller load replay structure in MEM attacks the\\nsame random-stall problem on the data side, where the lookup is off the\\nbranch/JAL predictor pat...\n  Line 37: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-030-r12s2\", \"title\": \"Registered Lookahead I-Fetch Replay Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor state is still the simple static frontend:\\nbackward conditional branches and direct JAL targets are predicted in IF.\\nBroader learned branch 