 of the 256-entry replay table's large\\nrandom-iStall cycle reduction while moving the same-cycle tag lookup off the\\nIF decision path. That win also makes the replay table one of the remaining\\nhigh-leverage timing structures. The table still stores a full 32-bit PC tag\\nfor every entry even though the direct-mapped index already encodes\\n`pc[9:2]` and all reachable fetch PCs are word-aligned. It also resets the\\ntag and instruction arrays even though the valid bits alone determine\\nwhether those payloads can be consumed.\\n\\nRecent micro-opt results show that exact timing-only cleanups can matter:\\nthe 16-bit segmented RVFI order counter improved Fmax without changing\\nCoreMark cycles, while broader datapath rewrites and smaller replay tables\\nlost either hit rate or placement quality. Compressing and de-resetting the\\nexisting replay metadata is the same kind of narrow micro-optimization: keep\\nthe current replay behavior and cycle count, but reduce IF table width,\\nreset fanout, and registered-candidate comparison logic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best fitness comes from the registered lookahead instruction\\nreplay predictor: it preserves most of the 256-entry replay table's large\\nrandom-iStall cycle reduction while moving the same-cycle tag lookup off the\\nIF decision path. That win also makes the replay table one of the remaining\\nhigh-leverage timing structures. The table still stores a full 32-bit PC tag\\nfor every entry even though the direct-mapped index already encodes\\n`pc[9:2]` and all reachable fetch PCs are word-aligned. It also resets the\\ntag and instruction arrays even though the valid bits alone determine\\nwhether those payloads can be consumed.\\n\\nRecent micro-opt results show that exact timing-on...\n  Line 39: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-032-r13s1\", \"title\": \"MEM-Stage Load Replay Behind I-Fetch Replay\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core gets its large gain 