motivation\": \"The current best predictor result is the registered lookahead instruction\\nreplay predictor. It kept the large cycle win of the earlier stall-only\\nreplay cache, reducing CoreMark cycles from 4,226,169 to 3,459,314, while\\nmoving the tag/data lookup off the same-cycle IF decision path enough to\\nreach 472.96 fitness. The predictor experiments after BTFNT and direct JAL\\nshow the useful signal clearly: hiding random imem stalls pays much more\\nthan adding another branch-direction table or return predictor.\\n\\nThe remaining replay loss is likely capacity conflict, not replay timing.\\nThe 64-entry replay attempts gave up many cycles versus the 256-entry\\nversion, so hot text footprint and aliasing matter. Simply doubling a\\nfull-tag word table risks growing the registered lookup mux and tag storage\\nin the IF stage. A better predictor-shaped next step is to pack adjacent\\ninstruction words under one line tag: it increases effective replay\\ncapacity for sequential CoreMark code while amortizing the full PC tag over\\ntwo instructions and preserving the current registered-candidate timing\\nmodel.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor result is the registered lookahead instruction\\nreplay predictor. It kept the large cycle win of the earlier stall-only\\nreplay cache, reducing CoreMark cycles from 4,226,169 to 3,459,314, while\\nmoving the tag/data lookup off the same-cycle IF decision path enough to\\nreach 472.96 fitness. The predictor experiments after BTFNT and direct JAL\\nshow the useful signal clearly: hiding random imem stalls pays much more\\nthan adding another branch-direction table or return predictor.\\n\\nThe remaining replay loss is likely capacity conflict, not replay timing.\\nThe 64-entry replay attempts gave up many cycles versus the 256-entry\\nversion, so hot text footprint and aliasing matter. Simply doubling a\\nful...\n  Line 41: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-034-r14s0\", \"title\": \"Elide Replay Candidate PC Compare\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best result is dominated by the registered lookahead instruction\\nreplay predictor. Compressing the replay table tags improved Fmax without\\nchanging CoreMark cycles, which shows the replay-hit/fetch-ready path is now\\none of the most timing-sensitive structures left in the design.\\n\\nThe IF stage still carries a full 32-bit `replay_cand_pc_q` register and\\ncompares it against the current `pc` every cycle before a replay candidate\\ncan satisfy an external imem stall. That guard is logically redundant with\\nthe current lookahead update discipline: on every clock, the replay candidate\\nis computed for exactly the PC that will be held or loaded into the PC\\nregister on the next cycle. Redirect loads both PC and candidate from the\\nredirect target, a non-stalled fetch loads both from `next_pc`, and a stalled\\nfetch recomputes the candidate for the held PC.\\n\\nRemoving this full-width equality check is a narrow micro-optimization in the\\nsame proven area as the current best. It should reduce IF-side compare\\nfanout, remove 32 candidate-PC flops, and shorten the `fetch_ready` decision\\npath without changing replay hit rate, branch/JAL prediction policy,\\npipeline timing, memory behavior, RVFI reporting, or CoreMark cycle count.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best result is dominated by the registered lookahead instruction\\nreplay predictor. Compressing the replay table tags improved Fmax without\\nchanging CoreMark cycles, which shows the replay-hit/fetch-ready path is now\\none of the most timing-sensitive structures left in the design.\\n\\nThe IF stage still carries a full 32-bit `replay_cand_pc_q` register and\\ncompares it against the current `pc` every cycle before a replay candidate\\ncan satisfy an external imem stall. That guard is logically redundant with\\nthe current lookahead update discipline: on every clock, the replay c...\n  Line 42: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-035-r14s1\", \"title\": \"Registered MEM Load-Replay Candidate\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core gets its largest IPC gain from registered lookahead\\ninstruction replay: repeated hot instructions can be supplied during random\\nimem stalls without putting a same-cycle replay-table lookup on the IF\\ndecision path. The analogous remaining structural loss is on the data side.\\nLoads still freeze the whole in-order pipeline whenever io_dmemReady is low,\\neven when the same normal-RAM word was recently returned by dmem.\\n\\nThe earlier MEM-stage load replay experiment showed the opportunity: it cut\\nCoreMark cycles, but the combinational replay-table lookup, tag compare, and\\nstore merge logic in MEM lowered Fmax enough to miss the current best. The\\npromising structural angle is to keep the replay behavior while moving the\\nlookup off the MEM critical path, just as the successful IF replay predictor\\ndid for instruction stalls.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core gets its largest IPC gain from registered lookahead\\ninstruction replay: repeated hot instructions can be supplied during random\\nimem stalls without putting a same-cycle replay-table lookup on the IF\\ndecision path. The analogous remaining structural loss is on the data side.\\nLoads still freeze the whole in-order pipeline whenever io_dmemReady is low,\\neven when the same normal-RAM word was recently returned by dmem.\\n\\nThe earlier MEM-stage load replay experiment showed the opportunity: it cut\\nCoreMark cycles, but the combinational replay-table lookup, tag compare, and\\nstore merge logic in MEM lowered Fmax enough to miss the current best. The\\npromising structural angle is to keep the replay behavior while moving the\\nlookup off the MEM critical path, just as the successful IF replay predictor\\ndid for instruction stalls.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small normal-RAM load replay table with