`RESET_PC` and `NOP`, even though those fields are\\nconsumed only when `replay_cand_valid_q` is asserted and the existing full-PC\\nguard matches the current fetch PC. Reset muxes and reset fanout on these\\n64 payload bits sit next to the IF replay/fetch-ready path that now matters\\nmost for Fmax. Clearing only ...\n  Line 49: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-042-r16s2\", \"title\": \"Replay-Cached Next-PC Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the compressed, resetless registered\\nlookahead instruction replay table. It keeps the large random-iStall cycle\\nwin of the 256-entry replay cache while avoiding a same-cycle table lookup\\non the IF decision path. Later predictor experiments show that adding new\\nbranch-direction tables, return predictors, victim entries, or wider replay\\nlines either saves very few cycles or loses more Fmax than it recovers.\\n\\nThe remaining promising predictor work is therefore inside the replay path\\nthat already wins. On a replay hit, the IF stage currently feeds the cached\\ninstruction word back through the same static branch/JAL decode and target\\nadders used for live imem data. That means an external imem stall served by\\nreplay still has a flop-to-flop path from `replay_cand_instr_q` through\\nbranch/JAL immediate reconstruction, target adders, the next-PC mux, and the\\nPC register. The replay table already knows the instruction for that PC from\\nan earlier live fetch, so its static next-PC prediction can be cached at fill\\ntime and replayed as metadata instead of recomputed in the hot stall path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the compressed, resetless registered\\nlookahead instruction replay table. It keeps the large random-iStall cycle\\nwin of the 256-entry replay cache while avoiding a same-cycle table lookup\\non the IF decision path. Later predictor experiments show that adding new\\nbranch-direction tables, return predictors, victim entries, or wider replay\\nlines either saves very few cycles or loses more Fmax than it recovers.\\n\\nThe remaining promising predictor work is therefore inside the replay path\\nthat already wins. On a replay hit, the IF stage currently feeds the cached\\ninstruction word back through the same static branch/JAL decode and target\\nadders used for live imem data. That ...\n  Line 50: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-043-r17s0\", \"title\": \"RTL-Only Hot/Cold ALU Opcode Split\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core has already removed the cold DIV/REM arithmetic from\\nthe universal EX path and gained another large timing win from trimming the\\nregistered instruction replay metadata. The remaining micro-opt opportunity\\nshould therefore avoid new queues, predictors, reset rewrites, or\\nmulti-cycle units, and instead reshape logic that is already on the hot\\none-cycle EX datapath.\\n\\n`rtl/alu.sv` still uses a dense ALU operation encoding and a single broad\\nresult case for the common RV32I operations, the single-cycle multiply\\nresults, and dummy DIV/REM results that are now supplied by `div_unit.sv`.\\nThe two previous hot/cold ALU hypotheses never produced architectural data\\nbecause their implementations were rejected for touching an off-limits test\\nhelper, not because the RTL idea failed formal, cosim, or FPGA placement.\\nThe source still has the same dense opcode/mux shape, so this remains the\\ncleanest unevaluated micro-opt angle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core has already removed the cold DIV/REM arithmetic from\\nthe universal EX path and gained another large timing win from trimming the\\nregistered instruction replay metadata. The remaining micro-opt opportunity\\nshould therefore avoid new queues, predictors, reset rewrites, or\\nmulti-cycle units, and instead reshape logic that is already on the hot\\none-cycle EX datapath.\\n\\n`rtl/alu.sv` still uses a dense ALU operation encoding and a single broad\\nresult case for the common RV32I operations, the single-cycle multiply\\nresults, and dummy DIV/REM results that are now supplied by `div_unit.sv`.\\nThe two previous hot/cold ALU hypotheses never produced architectural data\\nbecause their implementations were rejected for touching an off-limits test\\nhelper, not because the RTL idea failed formal, cosim, or FPGA placement.\\nThe source still has the same dense opc...\n  Line 51: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-044-r17s1\", \"title\": \"Tiny MRU Load Replay Latch\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already uses the two structural ideas that have paid\\nclearly: a one-deep pending-store slot for store-only dmem backpressure and\\na registered instruction replay table for random iStall. The remaining\\nstructural stalls are concentrated on normal-RAM loads. A load still freezes\\nthe whole in-order pipeline whenever io_dmemReady is low, even if the same\\naligned word was returned recently.\\n\\nThe prior 16-entry MEM-stage load replay buffer showed that this stall source\\nis real: it reduced CoreMark cycles on top of the instruction replay design.\\nIt missed the current best because the same-cycle table lookup, tag compare,\\nand store-update logic dropped Fmax too much. A much smaller MRU replay latch\\ntargets the same dmem-stall opportunity while keeping the MEM path close to\\nthe current best design.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already uses the two structural ideas that have paid\\nclearly: a one-deep pending-store slot for store-only dmem backpressure and\\na registered instruction replay table for random iStall. The remaining\\nstructural stalls are concentrated on normal-RAM loads. A load still freezes\\nthe whole in-order pipeline whenever io_dmemReady is low, even if the same\\naligned word was returned recently.\\n\\nThe prior 16-entry MEM-stage load replay buffer showed that this stall source\\nis real: it reduced CoreMark cycles on top of the instruction replay design.\\nIt missed the current best because the same-cycle table lookup, tag compare,\\nand store-update logic dropped Fmax too much. A much smaller MRU replay latch\\ntargets the same dmem-stall opportunity while keeping the MEM path close to\\nthe current best design.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a two-entry most-recently-used normal-RAM load replay latch in MEM. Each\\nentry stores a valid bit, an aligned word address tag, and the raw 32-bit word\\nreturned...\n  Line 52: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-045-r17s2\", \"title\": \"Registered Lookahead Agree Branch Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor win is the compressed registered lookahead\\ninstruction replay table. It attacks random iStall cycles without putting a\\nsame-cycle replay lookup on the IF decision path. Other predictor attempts\\nshow the remaining tradeoff clearly: learned conditional-branch tables did\\nreduce CoreMark cycles, but their combinational IF table reads and EX update\\nrouting cost more Fmax than the saved redirects recovered. Return predictors\\nand replay capacity variants had the same problem or saved too few cycles.\\n\\nThe most promising predictor angle is therefore to revisit dynamic branch\\ndirection with the timing discipline that made instruction replay work.\\nKeep the existing static BTFNT plus direct-JAL predictor as the cold and\\ntarget-generation path, but move the learned direction-table lookup into a\\nregistered lookahead candidate for the next fetch PC. That preserves the\\ncurrent IF replay structure and avoids adding a current-cycle counter-array\\nread to the branch/JAL target and fetch-ready path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor win is the compressed registered lookahead\\ninstruction replay table. It attacks random iStall cycles without putting a\\nsame-cycle replay lookup on the IF decision path. Other predictor attempts\\nshow the remaining tradeoff clearly: learned conditional-branch tables did\\nreduce CoreMark cycles, but their combinational IF table reads and EX update\\nrouting cost more Fmax than the saved redirects recovered. Return predictors\\nand replay capacity variants had the same problem or saved too few cycles.\\n\\nThe most promising predictor angle is therefore to revisit dynamic branch\\ndirection with the timing discipline that made instruction replay work.\\nKeep the existing static BTFNT plus direct-JAL predictor as the cold and\\ntarget-generation path, but move the learned d...\n  Line 53: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-046-r18s0\", \"title\": \"Source-Qualified Load-Use Interlock\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best RTL has already harvested the high-leverage Fmax wins:\\nDIV/REM is cold and iterative, the IF replay predictor hides most random\\niStall loss, replay tags are compressed/resetless, the RVFI order counter is\\nsegmented, and the ALU result mux has a hot/cold split. The next micro-opt\\nshould therefore avoid new memories, predictors, queues, or arithmetic units.\\n\\nThe remaining always-present cycle loss in the control path is the\\nconservative load-use detector. It currently stalls whenever the load in\\nID/EX has a nonzero rd matching either raw rs1 or raw rs2 bitfield of the\\nIF/ID instruction. That is necessary for true consumers, but false for many\\nlegal RV32I encodings: OP-IMM, LOAD, and JALR do not read rs2; LUI, AUIPC,\\nJAL, FENCE, and EBREAK do not read either source. CoreMark has many pointer\\nupdates, immediate arithmetic, loads, and control instructions after loads,\\nso these false matches can still inject bubbles even after the instruction\\nreplay predictor improves frontend availability.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best RTL has already harvested the high-leverage Fmax wins:\\nDIV/REM is cold and iterative, the IF replay predictor hides most random\\niStall loss, replay tags are compressed/resetless, the RVFI order counter is\\nsegmented, and the ALU result mux has a hot/cold split. The next micro-opt\\nshould therefore avoid new memories, predictors, queues, or arithmetic units.\\n\\nThe remaining always-present cycle loss in the control path is the\\nconservative load-use detector. It currently stalls whenever the load in\\nID/EX has a nonzero rd matching either raw rs1 or raw rs2 bitfield of the\\nIF/ID instruction. That is necessary for true consumers, but false for many\\nlegal RV32I encodings: OP-IMM, LOAD, and JALR do not read rs2; LUI, AUIPC,\\nJAL, FENCE, and EBREAK do not read either source. CoreMark has...\n  Line 55: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-048-r18s2\", \"title\": \"Kill-Gated I-Fetch Replay Fills\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best design already has the predictor feature with the strongest\\nmeasured payoff: a 256-entry registered lookahead instruction replay table\\nwith compressed tags. It hides random iStall bubbles without putting a\\nsame-cycle table lookup on the IF decision path. Follow-up predictor attempts\\nthat added branch-direction state, return targets, victim entries, wider\\nreplay lines, or replay-cached next-PC metadata either saved too few cycles\\nor lost more Fmax than they recovered.\\n\\nThe next predictor slot should therefore keep the existing replay structure\\nand target replay quality rather than add another table. The current IF\\nstage refreshes the replay table on every live `io_imemReady` fetch, even\\nwhen that fetch is being killed by an EX redirect or IF flush. Those killed\\nwords are architecturally correct immutable instructions, but they are\\nwrong-path for the current execution and can evict useful hot-loop replay\\nentries in the direct-mapped table. Avoiding this pollution is a narrow\\nreplay-predictor improvement with little timing exposure: it changes the\\nreplay write-enable policy, not the current-cycle fetch-ready, branch/JAL\\ntarget, ALU, memory, or retirement paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best design already has the predictor feature with the strongest\\nmeasured payoff: a 256-entry registered lookahead instruction replay table\\nwith compressed tags. It hides random iStall bubbles without putting a\\nsame-cycle table lookup on the IF decision path. Follow-up predictor attempts\\nthat added branch-direction state, return targets, victim entries, wider\\nreplay lines, or replay-cached next-PC metadata either saved too few cycles\\nor lost more Fmax than they recovered.\\n\\nThe next predictor slot should therefore keep the existing replay structure\\nand target replay quality rather than add another table. The cu...\n  Line 56: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-049-r19s0\", \"title\": \"Bitfield RV32M Control Decode\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best result came from making the ALU opcode encoding expose a\\nhot RV32I path and a cold RV32M path. That change improved Fmax without\\nchanging CoreMark cycles, which suggests the next micro-opt should keep\\nexploiting the same encoding rather than adding another replay table,\\npredictor, queue, reset rewrite, or arithmetic unit.\\n\\nSome downstream control logic still decodes RV32M operations with explicit\\nequality trees. In particular, EX detects divide/remainder instructions with\\nfour full `alu_op == ALU_*` compares even though the current encoding makes\\nDIV/DIVU/REM/REMU exactly the `alu_op[4] && alu_op[2]` class. The divider\\nalso reclassifies signed versus unsigned and quotient versus remainder with\\nopcode equality checks even though those are now just low funct3 bits inside\\nthe divide group.\\n\\nThese compares are small, but they sit in always-present EX control and\\nlong-operation stall logic that feeds the frontend hold network. Recent\\nexperiments show broad datapath, reset, and replay changes often lose more\\nplacement quality than they recover, so a narrow decode cleanup in the\\nalready-proven ALU-op encoding is the most attractive micro_opt follow-up.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best result came from making the ALU opcode encoding expose a\\nhot RV32I path and a cold RV32M path. That change improved Fmax without\\nchanging CoreMark cycles, which suggests the next micro-opt should keep\\nexploiting the same encoding rather than adding another replay table,\\npredictor, queue, reset rewrite, or arithmetic unit.\\n\\nSome downstream control logic still decodes RV32M operations with explicit\\nequality trees. In particular, EX detects divide/remainder instructions with\\nfour full `alu_op == ALU_*` compares even though the current encoding makes\\nDIV/DIVU/REM/REMU exactly the `alu_op[4] && alu_op[2]` class. The divider...\n  Line 58: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-051-r19s2\", \"title\": \"XOR-Indexed I-Fetch Replay Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor state is the compressed, resetless registered\\nlookahead instruction replay table. It preserves the large random-iStall\\ncycle reduction of the 256-entry replay predictor while keeping the\\ncurrent-cycle IF path free of a combinational table read. Follow-up\\npredictor attempts show the boundary clearly: extra branch-direction state,\\nreturn targets, replay victim entries, replay-line widening, and cached\\nnext-PC metadata either saved too few cycles or lost more Fmax than they\\nrecovered.\\n\\nThe remaining replay opportunity is likely direct-mapped conflict behavior.\\nThe table is indexed by `pc[9:2]`, so hot instructions separated by 1 KiB\\nalias even though the CoreMark timed region repeatedly visits several loop\\nbodies and helper routines. Smaller tables lost hit rate, and adding ways or\\nvictim entries added too much logic. A hashed direct-map index targets the\\nsame conflict misses while keeping the table size, registered lookahead\\ntiming model, live-imem-first policy, and compressed tag storage intact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor state is the compressed, resetless registered\\nlookahead instruction replay table. It preserves the large random-iStall\\ncycle reduction of the 256-entry replay predictor while keeping the\\ncurrent-cycle IF path free of a combinational table read. Follow-up\\npredictor attempts show the boundary clearly: extra branch-direction state,\\nreturn targets, replay victim entries, replay-line widening, and cached\\nnext-PC metadata either saved too few cycles or lost more Fmax than they\\nrecovered.\\n\\nThe remaining replay opportunity is likely direct-mapped conflict behavior.\\nThe table is indexed by `pc[9:2]`, so hot instructions separated by 1 KiB\\nalias even though the CoreMark timed region repeatedly visits several loop\\nbodies and helper routines. Smaller tabl...\n  Line 59: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-052-r20s0\", \"title\": \"Funct3-Aligned Hot ALU Encoding\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best result came from an RTL-only hot/cold ALU opcode split:\\nRV32M operations were moved behind `alu_op[4]`, letting the common RV32I\\nresult path avoid the cold M-extension mux. That improved Fmax without\\nchanging CoreMark cycles, so the most promising micro_opt follow-up is to\\nkeep refining the same hot EX datapath rather than adding new replay state,\\nqueues, reset rewrites, or arithmetic units.\\n\\nThe remaining RV32I/simple ALU encoding is still arbitrary and dense:\\nADD/SUB/logic/compare/shift/LUI are assigned sequential localparams, so the\\ndecoder emits constants unrelated to the instruction funct3 bits and the ALU\\nstill needs an 11-way simple-result case. RISC-V already groups the hot\\nOP/OP-IMM operations by funct3, with only SUB/SRA needing a modifier bit.\\nRe-encoding the simple ALU controls around that structure should shrink\\ndecode and mux logic on the single-cycle EX result path while preserving the\\nsuccessful `op[4]` M-extension discriminator.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best result came from an RTL-only hot/cold ALU opcode split:\\nRV32M operations were moved behind `alu_op[4]`, letting the common RV32I\\nresult path avoid the cold M-extension mux. That improved Fmax without\\nchanging CoreMark cycles, so the most promising micro_opt follow-up is to\\nkeep refining the same hot EX datapath rather than adding new replay state,\\nqueues, reset rewrites, or arithmetic units.\\n\\nThe remaining RV32I/simple ALU encoding is still arbitrary and dense:\\nADD/SUB/logic/compare/shift/LUI are assigned sequential localparams, so the\\ndecoder emits constants unrelated to the instruction funct3 bits and the ALU\\nstill needs an 11-way simple-result case. RISC-V already groups the hot\\nOP/OP-IMM operations by funct3, with only SUB/SRA needing a modifier bit.\\nRe-encoding the simple ALU controls around that structure should...\n  Line 60: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-053-r20s1\", \"title\": \"Same-Word Store Slot Coalescing\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already includes the structural wins that have survived\\nFPGA evaluation: a one-deep pending-store slot for normal-RAM store stalls\\nand a registered instruction replay table for random iStall. Broader store\\nbuffering attempts found the right bottleneck but were too expensive:\\ntwo-entry pending-store designs either failed placement, and the same-cycle\\nrefill variant also failed placement. That suggests the next structural\\nstore-side step should add capacity only for cases the existing single slot\\ncan handle locally.\\n\\nCoreMark updates list nodes, matrix cells, stack frames, and scalar state with\\nshort bursts of stores. When a pending normal-RAM store is already occupying\\nthe slot and dmem is not ready, a younger store to the same aligned word does\\nnot need a second physical buffer entry. It can be merged into the pending\\nslot because loads and MMIO are still held behind the slot, and there is no\\narchitectural observer between the two normal-RAM stores. This targets the\\nsame store-burst pressure as the failed two-entry FIFO, but with one address\\ncompare and one byte-mask merge instead of another queue entry or a wider\\ndmem arbiter.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already includes the structural wins that have survived\\nFPGA evaluation: a one-deep pending-store slot for normal-RAM store stalls\\nand a registered instruction replay table for random iStall. Broader store\\nbuffering attempts found the right bottleneck but were too expensive:\\ntwo-entry pending-store designs either failed placement, and the same-cycle\\nrefill variant also failed placement. That suggests the next structural\\nstore-side step should add capacity only for cases the existing single slot\\ncan handle locally.\\n\\nCoreMark updates list nodes, matrix cells, stack frames, and scalar state with\\nshort bursts of stores. When a ...\n  Line 61: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-054-r20s2\", \"title\": \"Banked Registered I-Fetch Replay Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor structure is the 256-entry registered lookahead\\ninstruction replay table with compressed resetless tags. It is the only\\npredictor-family change with a large measured cycle signal, because it turns\\nrandom imem stalls into useful hot-instruction replays while keeping the\\ncurrent-cycle IF path free of a combinational table read. Follow-up\\npredictor attempts that added branch-direction state, return targets,\\nvictim entries, wider lines, cached next-PC metadata, or XOR indexing either\\nsaved too few cycles or lost more Fmax than they recovered.\\n\\nThe best remaining replay opportunity is to reduce direct-mapped conflict\\nmisses without adding an associative lookup or changing the current-cycle\\nfetch-ready path. A full victim buffer added several tag compares and\\nregressed. XOR indexing changed conflicts but did not improve the measured\\nhit-rate/Fmax product. A banked direct-mapped predictor is a narrower\\nalternative: keep two small direct-mapped replay banks and choose between\\nthem with a simple per-set MRU bit during registered lookahead generation.\\nThe current cycle still consumes only the already registered replay\\ncandidate, so any extra bank selection work stays off the IF replay-hit path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor structure is the 256-entry registered lookahead\\ninstruction replay table with compressed resetless tags. It is the only\\npredictor-family change with a large measured cycle signal, because it turns\\nrandom imem stalls into useful hot-instruction replays while keeping the\\ncurrent-cycle IF path free of a combinational table read. Follow-up\\npredictor attempts that added branch-direction state, return targets,\\nvictim entries, wider lines, cached next-PC metadata, or XOR indexing either\\nsaved too few cycles or lost more Fmax than they recovered.\\n\\nThe best...\n  Line 62: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-055-r21s0\", \"title\": \"Bank-Aware Replay Fill Select\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core is dominated by the banked registered instruction\\nreplay predictor plus the hot/cold ALU split. The replay predictor is now\\nboth the largest remaining IPC win and one of the most timing-sensitive IF\\nstructures. Follow-up replay experiments show that changing capacity,\\nindexing, victim search, or cached next-PC metadata usually loses more Fmax\\nthan it recovers, so the next micro-opt should keep the successful two-bank\\norganization and trim redundant logic inside it.\\n\\nThe current banked replay table still does two same-cycle tag comparisons for\\nevery live imem fill:\\n`replay_fill_bank0_match` and `replay_fill_bank1_match` re-read the current\\nPC's indexed set to decide whether to refresh bank 0, refresh bank 1, or\\nreplace the non-MRU bank. But the registered lookahead candidate for the\\ncurrent fetch PC was produced by comparing exactly those two banks on the\\nprevious cycle. If that candidate hits and its PC guard matches the current\\nPC, it already identifies that the word is present and which bank supplied\\nit. If it misses, the previous lookup already proved that neither bank held\\nthe current tag, so replacement can use the non-MRU bank directly.\\n\\nReusing the registered candidate's bank for live fills should remove two\\ncurrent-PC tag compare trees and part of the fill-bank muxing from the IF\\nreplay block while keeping the current replay hit rate, table size, MRU\\npolicy, candidate PC guard, and live-imem-first behavior intact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core is dominated by the banked registered instruction\\nreplay predictor plus the hot/cold ALU split. The replay predictor is now\\nboth the largest remaining IPC win and one of the most timing-sensitive IF\\nstructures. Follow-up replay experiments show that changing capacity,\\nindexing, victim search, or cached next-PC metadata usually loses ...\n  Line 63: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-056-r21s1\", \"title\": \"Pending Store Slot Load Forwarding\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already has the structural pieces that have survived\\nFPGA evaluation: a one-deep pending-store slot hides normal-RAM store\\nbackpressure, and the banked registered instruction replay predictor hides\\nmost random iStall bubbles. The structural experiments since then show the\\nboundary clearly. Larger store buffers and same-cycle refill failed\\nplacement, same-word store coalescing did not reduce CoreMark cycles, and\\ndata replay tables recovered some load-stall cycles but cost too much Fmax.\\n\\nThe remaining store-slot bottleneck is narrower. When a normal-RAM store has\\nretired into the pending slot, the core currently blocks every younger memory\\noperation until the physical write drains, even if the younger operation is a\\nload of bytes that are already fully present in the pending store entry. That\\ncase does not require a second store-buffer entry or a dmem access: in\\nprogram order the store is already older and retired, so a same-word covered\\nload should read the store slot's bytes. CoreMark's stack, list, and state\\ncode can produce store/load reuse on nearby words, especially under random\\ndmem stalls that keep the slot valid for multiple cycles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already has the structural pieces that have survived\\nFPGA evaluation: a one-deep pending-store slot hides normal-RAM store\\nbackpressure, and the banked registered instruction replay predictor hides\\nmost random iStall bubbles. The structural experiments since then show the\\nboundary clearly. Larger store buffers and same-cycle refill failed\\nplacement, same-word store coalescing did not reduce CoreMark cycles, and\\ndata replay tables recovered some load-stall cycles but cost too much Fmax.\\n\\nThe remaining store-slot bottleneck is narrower. When a normal-RAM store has\\nretired into the pending slot, the core currentl...\n  Line 64: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-057-r21s2\", \"title\": \"Skewed-Bank I-Fetch Replay Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the two-bank registered lookahead instruction\\nreplay table. It is the only predictor-family structure that has delivered a\\nlarge CoreMark gain and a strong Fmax result: it hides random imem stalls by\\nreplaying hot instructions, while the current IF cycle still chooses only\\nbetween live imem data and an already registered candidate.\\n\\nThe remaining replay misses are likely conflict misses. The current two-bank\\ndesign stores two tags per raw `pc[8:2]` set, so any hot instructions spaced\\nby 512-byte multiples still contend for the same two physical slots. Earlier\\nalternatives show the tradeoff boundary: a single-bank XOR index changed the\\nconflict pattern but gave up the benefit of two-way capacity, and a victim\\nbuffer added associative compares that cost more Fmax than the extra hits\\nrecovered. A skewed second bank targets the same conflict class with no extra\\ntable entries, no victim search, and no current-cycle table read.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the two-bank registered lookahead instruction\\nreplay table. It is the only predictor-family structure that has delivered a\\nlarge CoreMark gain and a strong Fmax result: it hides random imem stalls by\\nreplaying hot instructions, while the current IF cycle still chooses only\\nbetween live imem data and an already registered candidate.\\n\\nThe remaining replay misses are likely conflict misses. The current two-bank\\ndesign stores two tags per raw `pc[8:2]` set, so any hot instructions spaced\\nby 512-byte multiples still contend for the same two physical slots. Earlier\\nalternatives show the tradeoff boundary: a single-bank XOR index changed the\\nconflict pattern but gave up the benefit of two-way capacity, and a victim\\nbuffer added associative compares that cost more Fmax than the extra hits\\nrecovered. A skewed second bank...\n  Line 65: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-058-r22s0\", \"title\": \"Resetless Replay MRU State\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best design is dominated by the two-bank registered instruction\\nreplay predictor. It is the only predictor-family structure that has both\\nreduced random-iStall cycles and improved Fmax, and the successful\\ncompressed-tag follow-up showed that narrow timing cleanups inside this IF\\nreplay block can still move median fitness without changing CoreMark cycles.\\n\\nThe replay table already leaves tag and instruction payload arrays resetless\\nbehind valid bits, but the per-index MRU replacement bits are still\\nsynchronously reset. Those MRU bits are not architectural state and are not\\nneeded for correctness after reset: both replay-bank valid bits are cleared,\\nso the first live fill for a set may choose either bank. After that fill, the\\nMRU bit is immediately written to the bank that was filled and normal\\nreplacement behavior resumes.\\n\\nRemoving reset from this 128-bit replacement-state array is a narrower\\nversion of the reset-elision idea that has already worked for replay\\npayloads. It targets reset fanout and local IF replay placement pressure\\nwithout changing the current-cycle fetch-ready path, replay hit rate after\\nwarmup, branch/JAL prediction policy, ALU datapath, memory behavior, or RVFI\\nretirement.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best design is dominated by the two-bank registered instruction\\nreplay predictor. It is the only predictor-family structure that has both\\nreduced random-iStall cycles and improved Fmax, and the successful\\ncompressed-tag follow-up showed that narrow timing cleanups inside this IF\\nreplay block can still move median fitness without changing CoreMark cycles.\\n\\nThe replay table already leaves tag and instruction payload arrays resetless\\nbehind valid bits, but the per-index MRU replacement bits are still\\nsynchronously reset. Those MRU bits are not architectural state and are not\\nneeded for ...\n  Line 67: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-060-r22s2\", \"title\": \"Stream-Resistant Replay Insertion\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the two-bank registered lookahead instruction\\nreplay table, which reached 577.76 fitness by hiding random imem stalls\\nwithout putting a same-cycle table lookup on the IF decision path. Follow-up\\npredictor attempts show the remaining boundary clearly: adding more branch\\ndirection state, return prediction, victim search, skewed indexing, cached\\nnext-PC metadata, or bank-aware fill logic either saved too few cycles or\\ncost more Fmax than it recovered.\\n\\nThe least intrusive remaining replay opportunity is replacement policy. The\\ncurrent two-bank table uses a per-index MRU bit and marks every miss-filled\\nentry as MRU. That is a normal two-way cache policy, but it is vulnerable to\\none-shot or low-reuse instruction streams, wrong-path fetches, and cold helper\\ncode displacing hot-loop replay entries. CoreMark repeatedly executes compact\\nloops, so protecting the most recently hit replay word from streaming\\npollution may recover some random-iStall hits without adding a table, a tag\\ncompare, a branch update path, or any current-cycle fetch-ready logic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the two-bank registered lookahead instruction\\nreplay table, which reached 577.76 fitness by hiding random imem stalls\\nwithout putting a same-cycle table lookup on the IF decision path. Follow-up\\npredictor attempts show the remaining boundary clearly: adding more branch\\ndirection state, return prediction, victim search, skewed indexing, cached\\nnext-PC metadata, or bank-aware fill logic either saved too few cycles or\\ncost more Fmax than it recovered.\\n\\nThe least intrusive remaining replay opportunity is replacement policy. The\\ncurrent two-bank table uses a per-index MRU bit and marks every miss-filled\\nentry as MRU. That is a normal two-way cache policy, but it is vulnerable to\\none-shot or low-reuse...\n  Line 68: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-061-r23s0\", \"title\": \"Power-of-Two RAM Range Decode\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best design has already captured the large timing wins: cold\\nDIV/REM is off the EX datapath, the hot/cold ALU split simplified the common\\nresult mux, the RVFI order counter is segmented, and the banked registered\\ninstruction replay predictor hides most random iStall loss. Recent broader\\nmicro-opt attempts that changed replay replacement, reset policy, ALU\\nfunct3 encoding, or source-qualified hazards tended to lose Fmax through\\nplacement noise or extra muxing. The next micro_opt should therefore be a\\nvery narrow equivalence rewrite on logic that is still always present.\\n\\nThe MEM stage still classifies bufferable stores with an unsigned 32-bit\\ncomparison against `32'h0010_0000`. That limit is exactly 1 MiB, so for a\\n32-bit byte address the predicate is equivalent to `addr[31:20] == 0`.\\nThe result feeds store-slot enqueue and MEM backpressure, which in turn\\ndrives the global stall network. Replacing the generic less-than form with\\nan explicit high-bit decode should remove carry/comparator structure from\\nthe store-bufferable path without changing the direct ready-store behavior,\\npending-store semantics, memory ordering, or CoreMark cycle count.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best design has already captured the large timing wins: cold\\nDIV/REM is off the EX datapath, the hot/cold ALU split simplified the common\\nresult mux, the RVFI order counter is segmented, and the banked registered\\ninstruction replay predictor hides most random iStall loss. Recent broader\\nmicro-opt attempts that changed replay replacement, reset policy, ALU\\nfunct3 encoding, or source-qualified hazards tended to lose Fmax through\\nplacement noise or extra muxing. The next micro_opt should therefore be a\\nvery narrow equivalence rewrite on logic that is still always present.\\n\\nThe MEM stage still classifies bufferable stores with an unsigned ...\n  Line 69: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-062-r23s1\", \"title\": \"MEM-Wait Simple-ALU Skid Slot\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core is a fast single-issue design with the largest proven\\nwins already in place: cold DIV/REM is off the EX datapath, the hot/cold ALU\\nsplit improved Fmax, the one-entry pending-store slot hides some store-only\\ndmem stalls, and the banked registered instruction replay predictor hides\\nmost random imem stalls. The remaining structural loss is therefore mainly\\nbackend pressure from dmem waits, especially loads. Today a load in MEM with\\n`io_dmemReady=0` freezes IF, ID, and EX even when the younger instruction in\\nID/EX is an independent simple ALU operation whose operands are already\\navailable and whose execution has no memory or control-flow side effects.\\n\\nPrior attempts to attack this bottleneck by replaying load data or adding\\nbroader store buffering reduced cycles but cost too much Fmax or placement\\nquality. A smaller structural decoupling point is more promising: let EX do\\none cycle of useful independent simple-ALU work while the older MEM load or\\nnonbufferable store is waiting, but keep retirement strictly in order. This\\ntargets the exact full-pipeline freeze caused by random dmem backpressure\\nwithout adding load data to EX, another replay table, another store-buffer\\nentry, a branch predictor, or a general superscalar backend.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core is a fast single-issue design with the largest proven\\nwins already in place: cold DIV/REM is off the EX datapath, the hot/cold ALU\\nsplit improved Fmax, the one-entry pending-store slot hides some store-only\\ndmem stalls, and the banked registered instruction replay predictor hides\\nmost random imem stalls. The remaining structural loss is therefore mainly\\nbackend pressure from dmem waits, especially loads. Today a load in MEM with\\n`io_dmemReady=0` freezes IF, ID, and EX even when the younger instruction in\\nID/EX is an independent simp...\n  Line 70: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-063-r23s2\", \"title\": \"Low-Bit Static Target Alignment Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best result is the two-bank registered instruction replay\\npredictor plus the hot/cold ALU split. The replay predictor is the only\\npredictor-family structure that has produced a large CoreMark cycle win and\\na strong Fmax result. Follow-up predictor attempts that added more state,\\nchanged replacement, added victim/skewed indexing, cached next-PC metadata,\\nor added branch-direction tables generally lost more Fmax than they recovered.\\n\\nThe next predictor hypothesis should therefore avoid new predictor memories\\nand preserve the successful two-bank replay structure. The remaining\\nlow-risk predictor timing issue is in the zero-state static control\\npredictor itself: IF currently waits for the full branch and JAL target\\nadders to produce `[1:0]` before deciding whether the predicted target is\\nword-aligned. For B-type and J-type immediates, bit 0 is always zero and bit\\n1 of the target can be derived from `pc[1]` and one encoded immediate bit.\\n\\nA previous single-adder static-control rewrite removed a target adder but\\nintroduced a selected-immediate mux before the target add and regressed. This\\nhypothesis is narrower: keep the existing branch and JAL target adders, but\\nremove their low-bit outputs from the prediction-enable path. That should\\nkeep CoreMark cycles identical while shortening the IF predictor select path\\nin the current best frontend.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best result is the two-bank registered instruction replay\\npredictor plus the hot/cold ALU split. The replay predictor is the only\\npredictor-family structure that has produced a large CoreMark cycle win and\\na strong Fmax result. Follow-up predictor attempts that added more state,\\nchanged replacement, added victim/skewed indexing, cached next-PC metadata,\\nor added branch-direction tables generally lost more Fmax than they recovered...\n  Line 73: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-066-r24s2\", \"title\": \"Registered Lookahead JALR Target Predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor structure is the two-bank registered instruction\\nreplay table. It is the only predictor-family mechanism that has produced a\\nlarge CoreMark cycle win without putting a same-cycle table lookup on the IF\\ndecision path. Follow-up replay changes, direction tables, return stacks,\\nvictim buffers, skewed indexes, and cached static next-PC metadata mostly\\nlost more Fmax than they recovered.\\n\\nThe remaining control-flow hole is narrower: JALR still resolves only in EX.\\nEvery return and indirect call therefore pays the wrong-path recovery cost\\neven when the target is stable from one execution of that JALR PC to the\\nnext. Earlier return predictors showed that JALR bubbles exist, but they put\\ncurrent-cycle compares or stack bookkeeping directly in IF. The successful\\nreplay predictor suggests a better timing shape: look up any target state one\\ncycle ahead, register a candidate for the current fetch PC, and keep the\\ncurrent IF cycle dependent only on that candidate plus the fetched\\ninstruction's opcode bits.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor structure is the two-bank registered instruction\\nreplay table. It is the only predictor-family mechanism that has produced a\\nlarge CoreMark cycle win without putting a same-cycle table lookup on the IF\\ndecision path. Follow-up replay changes, direction tables, return stacks,\\nvictim buffers, skewed indexes, and cached static next-PC metadata mostly\\nlost more Fmax than they recovered.\\n\\nThe remaining control-flow hole is narrower: JALR still resolves only in EX.\\nEvery return and indirect call therefore pays the wrong-path recovery cost\\neven when the target is stable from one execution of that JALR PC to the\\nnext. Earlier return predictors showed that JALR bubbles exist, but they put\\ncurrent-cycle compares or stack bookkeeping directly in IF. ...\n  Line 74: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-068-r25s1\", \"title\": \"Single-Entry Last-Load Replay Latch\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already has the structural wins that have survived the\\nFPGA gate: the one-deep pending-store slot hides some store backpressure, and\\nthe two-bank registered instruction replay predictor hides most random\\niStall bubbles. The remaining structural stalls are mainly data-side load\\nwaits. When a normal-RAM load reaches MEM and `io_dmemReady` is low, the\\nwhole in-order backend freezes even if the same aligned word was just read by\\nan earlier load.\\n\\nLarger load replay attempts proved that this opportunity is real because they\\nreduced CoreMark cycles, but their table lookups, tag compares, and store\\nupdate paths cost too much Fmax. The next structural bet should keep only the\\ncheapest useful form of that idea: one last-load replay entry. CoreMark's\\nstack, list, state, and matrix kernels often reload nearby or identical words\\nacross short loops, so a single MRU word can catch some random dStall cases\\nwithout a table, replacement policy, associative search, or load-data path\\ninto EX.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already has the structural wins that have survived the\\nFPGA gate: the one-deep pending-store slot hides some store backpressure, and\\nthe two-bank registered instruction replay predictor hides most random\\niStall bubbles. The remaining structural stalls are mainly data-side load\\nwaits. When a normal-RAM load reaches MEM and `io_dmemReady` is low, the\\nwhole in-order backend freezes even if the same aligned word was just read by\\nan earlier load.\\n\\nLarger load replay attempts proved that this opportunity is real because they\\nreduced CoreMark cycles, but their table lookups, tag compares, and store\\nupdate paths cost too much Fmax. The next structural bet should keep only the\\ncheapest useful form of that idea: one last-load replay entry. CoreMark's\\nstack, list, state, and matrix ke...","metadata":{"matches":61,"truncated":false},"title":"\"fitness\":\\s*[0-9.]+","time":{"start":1778754066840,"end":1778754066855}},"id":"prt_e26011691002YIFthc2wLF1iEG","sessionID":"ses_1da081598ffelSLGjQATF56q6S","messageID":"msg_e260100a3001oE6lIRviQ4L8Bn"}}
