ion, and regfile read fanout. Prior elastic-fetch work kept an empty-buffer bypass to avoid latency, so it retained much of this path and lost Fmax. A cleaner structural bet is to deliberately insert the missing fetch/decode cutpoint and trade one extra frontend pipeline stage for a higher median FPGA clock.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert the IF/ID handoff into a real registered pipeline boundary with no zero-latency imem-data-to-decode bypass. IF captures {pc, instr, predicted_taken, predicted_target, valid} when io_imemReady is high and the decode side can accept an entry; ID decodes only the registered entry on the following cycle. Redirects and reset flush the IF/ID register and restart fetch at the resolved target, while load-use and dmem stalls hold the re...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-014-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Single-Entry Retiring Store Buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core gained a large Fmax and LUT win by moving DIV/REM out\\nof the hot EX path, so the next structural bottleneck is less likely to be\\nraw datapath area and more likely to be cycles lost to the random dmem\\nhandshake model. Today every dmem-not-ready cycle for a STORE freezes the\\nwhole pipeline, even though the store address, replicated data, byte mask,\\nand RVFI memory metadata are already known in MEM and the store produces no\\nregister result for younger ALU/control instructions. A prior two-entry\\nstore buffer proved the idea through formal and cosim but failed placement\\non the larger pre-DIV RTL. A smaller one-entry RAM-store buffer should retain\\nmost of the useful stall hiding while keeping the arbitration, state, and\\nplacement pressure low enough for the post-DIV design.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core gained a large Fmax and LUT win by moving DIV/REM out\\nof the hot EX path, so the next structural bottleneck is less likely to be\\nraw datapath area and more likely to be cycles lost to the 