{"type":"text","timestamp":1778754358971,"sessionID":"ses_1da081598ffelSLGjQATF56q6S","part":{"id":"prt_e260575630011Y6k4G8jWpe14q","messageID":"msg_e260559a2001My42EOrFbn1CtD","sessionID":"ses_1da081598ffelSLGjQATF56q6S","type":"text","text":"Done. I've written the structural hypothesis to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r1s1.yaml`\n\n**Summary:** The hypothesis proposes restructuring the baseline's monolithic ALU into a fast integer ALU plus a dedicated cold **Multiply-Divide Unit (MDU)**. The hot low-half `MUL` stays single-cycle in the ALU, while the cold ops (`DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU` and `MULH/MULHU/MULHSU`) move to the MDU. The MDU uses a 32-cycle iterative divider and a 2-cycle pipelined high-half multiplier, stalling the pipeline only when those rare opcodes appear. This removes two of the three 64-bit combinational multipliers and the entire combinational divider from the universal EX critical path, which should cut LUT4 utilization by ~1500–2500 and improve Fmax by 8–15 MHz with negligible IPC loss on CoreMark.","time":{"start":1778754352483,"end":1778754358967}}}
