{"type":"text","timestamp":1778758427257,"sessionID":"ses_1d9c3c38fffe6uJhnlz3skQhY5","part":{"id":"prt_e26438965001qMQS8pGH3e2A4x","messageID":"msg_e26437458001sTSdBZE6doJlRM","sessionID":"ses_1d9c3c38fffe6uJhnlz3skQhY5","type":"text","text":"Done. I wrote the hypothesis YAML to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r3s1.yaml`\n\n**Summary of the hypothesis:**\n\n- **Angle:** Structural — eliminate the 1-cycle load-use stall by adding a forwarding path from the MEM-stage load-data output directly into the EX-stage operand muxes.\n- **Why:** CoreMark is pointer- and memory-intensive, so load-use bubbles are a significant IPC drain. Prior structural attempts on branches/MDU/pre-compute targets all failed or were neutral; the forwarding network is the remaining untouched structural knob.\n- **What changes:**\n  1. `mem_stage.sv` — expose combinational `load_data` as `fwd_load_data`.\n  2. `forward_unit.sv` — add a third forwarding priority when `ex_mem` is a load and `rd` matches.\n  3. `ex_stage.sv` — mux the new MEM load data into `rs1`/`rs2`.\n  4. `hazard_unit.sv` — remove `load_use_hazard` from all stall/flush signals.\n  5. `core.sv` — wire the new signals together.\n- **Expected impact:** +7% fitness (medium confidence) from higher IPC, with acceptable timing risk because the new path (BRAM read → byte shift → ALU) should be comparable to existing critical paths on the Tang Nano 20K.","time":{"start":1778758420837,"end":1778758427255}}}
