{"type":"text","timestamp":1778761394062,"sessionID":"ses_1d9986e2cffeRLNJfRC5OOOvq0","part":{"id":"prt_e2670bffa002hvXwzGs8lviS0i","messageID":"msg_e2670a0a200167x4nw45b5JBnm","sessionID":"ses_1d9986e2cffeRLNJfRC5OOOvq0","type":"text","text":"I wrote the structural hypothesis to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r4s1.yaml`.\n\n**Core idea:** Eliminate the 1-cycle load-use stall by forwarding the fully processed (byte-aligned, sign/zero-extended) load result from the MEM stage directly into the existing EX/MEM forward path, and remove the `load_use_hazard` interlock from the hazard unit.\n\n**Why this should work where prior attempts didn't:**\n- A prior micro-optimization (`hyp-20260514-001-r3s0`) described this exact mechanism but produced a no-op — the most likely explanation is the implementing agent changed the forward source but forgot to delete the stall logic, so the bubble was never actually removed.\n- A later structural attempt (`hyp-20260514-002-r3s1`) broke RVFI because it forwarded raw `dmem_rdata` without replicating the shift/sign-extension logic.\n- This proposal forwards the *exact* `load_data` signal that mem_stage already computes for the MEM/WB register, so the forwarded value is bit-exidentical with the WB write path. No new forwarding select encoding is needed — the existing `forward_unit` already selects source `2'd1` for an EX/MEM instruction that writes the matching `rd`.\n\n**Expected impact:** ~6% fitness improvement (medium confidence). CoreMark is pointer- and array-heavy, so removing the load-use bubble should improve IPC measurably, while the extra combinational path (dmem_rdata → byte-select → sext → existing forward mux) is likely shorter than the ALU adder and therefore should not become the new critical path.","time":{"start":1778761383930,"end":1778761394061}}}
