RVFI reg checks).\\nBy forwarding the fully processed load_data from the MEM-stage combinational\\noutput directly into the existing EX/MEM forward path, and explicitly deleting\\nthe load_use_hazard stall logic, the dependent instruction can enter EX on the\\nvery next cycle with the exact same value that will later be written to the\\nregfile.\\n\",\n  \"hypothesis\": {\n    \"motivation\": \"The baseline 5-stage pipeline stalls ID for one cycle on every load-use hazard\\nbecause the load data is only available after it is latched into MEM/WB.\\nCoreMark's list-walk, matrix-access, and pointer-chasing patterns contain a\\nhigh density of back-to-back load-dependent ALU ops, so this bubble is a\\nsignificant IPC limiter. Prior attempts either failed to remove the\\naccompanying hazard-unit interlock (producing a no-op) or forwarded raw\\ndmem_rdata without byte-alignment/sign-extension (breaking RVFI reg checks).\\nBy forwarding the fully processed load_data from the MEM-stage combinational\\noutput directly into the existing EX/MEM forward path, and explicitly deleting\\nthe load_use_hazard stall logic, the dependent instruction can enter EX on the\\nvery next cycle with the exact same value that will later be written to the\\nregfile.\\n\",\n    \"hypothesis\": \"1. In mem_stage.sv, expose the internal combinational `load_data` signal as a\\n   new output port `load_data_out`. This is the same byte-aligned,\\n   sign/zero-extended value that is captured into the MEM/WB register.\\n2. In core.sv, change the `fwd_ex_mem` connection fed into ex_stage from a\\n   plain `ex_mem_w.alu_result` to the multiplexed value\\n   `ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read ? mem_load_data : ex_mem_w.alu_result`.\\n   Because the existing forward_unit already asserts select `2'd1` whenever\\n   the EX/MEM instruction writes the matching `rd`, the EX-stage operand mux\\n   will automatically pick up the actual load result instead of the memory\\n   address.\\n3. In hazard_unit.sv, delete the `load_use_hazard` logic entirely. The signal\\n   must be hard-wired to 0 so the pipeline no longer stalls IF/ID on this\\n   case. The remaining stall sources (imem_ready, dmem_ready, redirect) are\\n   untouched.\\n\\nNo new forwarding select encoding is introduced, no EX-stage operand mux\\ngrows beyond its existing 3-way shape, and the forwarded value is bit-exact\\nwith the WB write path, so RVFI reg checks should pass cleanly.\\n\",\n    \"expected_impact\": {\n      \"fitness_delta_pct\": 6,\n      \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    \"changes\": [\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add an output port `logic [31:0] load_data_out` and assign it to the\\ninternal combinational `load_data` signal that is already computed for\\nthe MEM/WB register.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add a local wire `logic [31:0] mem_load_data` connected to\\n`u_mem.load_data_out`. Change the `fwd_ex_mem` port connection on\\n`u_ex` from `ex_mem_w.alu_result` to\\n`ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read ? mem_load_data : ex_mem_w.alu_result`.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Remove all logic that derives `load_use_hazard` from `id_ex_mem_read`,\\n`id_ex_rd`, `if_id_rs1`, and `if_id_rs2`. Tie `load_use_hazard` to 0.\\nKeep the port declarations (or remove them and their connections in\\ncore.sv) \\u2014 the minimal change is to keep the ports and simply not use\\nthem inside the combinational block.\\n\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"expected_impact\": {\n    \"fitness_delta_pct\": 6,\n    \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n  },\n  \"changes\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add an output port `logic [31:0] load_data_out` and assign it to the\\ninternal combinational `load_data` signal that is already computed for\\nthe MEM/WB register.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add a local wire `logic [31:0] mem_load_data` connected to\\n`u_mem.load_data_out`. Change the `fwd_ex_mem` port connection on\\n`u_ex` from `ex_mem_w.alu_result` to\\n`ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read ? mem_load_data : ex_mem_w.alu_result`.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Remove all logic that derives `load_use_hazard` from `id_ex_mem_read`,\\n`id_ex_rd`, `if_id_rs1`, and `if_id_rs2`. Tie `load_use_hazard` to 0.\\nKeep the port declarations (or remove them and their connections in\\ncore.sv) \\u2014 the minimal change is to keep the ports and simply not use\\nthem inside the combinational block.\\n\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": \"broken\",\n  \"formal_passed\": false,\n  \"cosim_passed\": false,\n  \"error\": \"implementation_compile_failed: \",\n  \"slot\": 1,\n  \"round_id\": 4,\n  \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r4s1 (broken, n/a): MEM-to-EX load forwarding can reuse the existing forward_unit select encoding by muxing the fwd_ex_mem data source in core.sv; adding unused ports to forward_unit caused an implementation compile failure from unconnected inputs.\"\n}\n","metadata":{"output":"{\n  \"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r1s1\",\n  \"title\": \"Cold RV32M High-Half and Divide Unit\",\n  \"category\": \"structural\",\n  \"motivation\": \"The baseline ALU unconditionally builds three independent 64-bit multiply\\nproducts (signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, signed*unsigned) and a\\ncombinational 32-bit divider on every cycle. This bloats area to ~9500 LUT4\\nand places heavy arithmetic on the EX-stage critical path for *all*\\ninstructions, even simple ADD or BRANCH. CoreMark's timed path is multiply-\\nheavy but only uses the low-half MUL result; it is effectively cold for\\nDIV/REM and high-half multiplies (MULH/MULHU/MULHSU). Prior work on similar\\nRV32IM baselines showed that moving cold division off the universal ALU path\\nwas one of the largest pure Fmax wins. Extending that idea to also remove the\\ntwo unused high-half multipliers should compound the area and timing benefit\\nwithout touching the benchmark's hot IPC path.\\n\",\n  \"hypothesis\": {\n    \"motivation\": \"The baseline ALU unconditionally builds three independent 64-bit multiply\\nproducts (signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, signed*unsigned) and a\\ncombinational 32-bit divider on every cycle. This bloats area to ~9500 LUT4\\nand places heavy arithmetic on the EX-stage critical path for *all*\\ninstructions, even simple ADD or BRANCH. CoreMark's timed path is multiply-\\nheavy but only uses the low-half MUL result; it is effectively cold for\\nDIV/REM and high-half multiplies (MULH/MULHU/MULHSU). Prior work on similar\\nRV32IM baselines showed that moving cold division off the universal ALU path\\nwas one of the largest pure Fmax wins. Extending that idea to also remove the\\ntwo unused high-half multipliers should compound the area and timing benefit\\nwithout touching the benchmark's hot IPC path.\\n\",\n    \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure the EX stage into a fast single-cycle integer ALU plus a\\ndedicated cold Multiply-Divide Unit (MDU).\\n\\n- The ALU keeps ADD/SUB/logic/shift/compare/LUI and the existing single-\\n  cycle low-half MUL (mul_uu[31:0]). All other M-extension opcodes are\\n  removed from the ALU result mux.\\n- The new `rtl/mdu.sv` module handles the cold ops:\\n    * DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU using a 32-cycle iterative restoring divider.\\n    * MULH/MULHU/MULHSU using a 2-cycle pipelined 33x33 multiplier whose\\n      high-half result is captured in a registered output.\\n  The divider reuses the proven `div_unit.sv` state machine pattern from\\n  the reference v1 core, adapted for the bench baseline.\\n- `rtl/ex_stage.sv` detects a cold M-extension opcode and asserts a new\\n  `ex_long_busy` signal to the hazard unit, freezing the pipeline until the\\n  MDU signals `done`. On completion the MDU result is written into the\\n  EX/MEM register exactly like a normal ALU result.\\n- The ALTOPS branch in the MDU mirrors the formal substitutions already\\n  present in the baseline ALU, so `make formal` behavior is unchanged.\\n\\nCoreMark should see zero IPC penalty because its timed loop contains no\\nDIV/REM and no MULH variants, while the common RV32I and MUL instructions\\nnow run on a shorter critical path. LUT utilization should drop by\\n~1500-2500, relieving routing congestion and raising median Fmax.\\n\",\n    \"expected_impact\": {\n      \"fitness_delta_pct\": 10,\n      \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    \"changes\": [\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and MULH/MULHU/MULHSU cases from the\\nmain result mux. Keep only the hot RV32I ops plus ALU_MUL (low half\\nof mul_uu). Add a cold-op indicator bit or reuse op[4] so EX stage\\ncan detect when the MDU is needed.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/mdu.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"New module: registered 2-cycle high-half multiplier for MULH/MULHU/\\nMULHSU plus a 32-cycle iterative divider for DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU.\\nIncludes start/busy/done handshake, ALTOPS substitutions under\\n`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS`, and exact RV32M corner-case handling.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Instantiate MDU, route operands to it, detect cold M-op via opcode\\nencoding, assert `ex_long_busy` while MDU is active, and select MDU\\nresult into EX/MEM when done.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Accept `ex_long_busy` alongside existing `dmem_ready` / `imem_ready`\\nstall sources. Treat MDU busy like a dmem stall: freeze IF/ID/EX\\nand bubble EX/MEM until the unit completes.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Wire the new `ex_long_busy` signal from ex_stage into hazard_unit.\\nNo top-level IO changes.\\n\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"expected_impact\": {\n    \"fitness_delta_pct\": 10,\n    \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n  },\n  \"changes\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and MULH/MULHU/MULHSU cases from the\\nmain result mux. Keep only the hot RV32I ops plus ALU_MUL (low half\\nof mul_uu). Add a cold-op indicator bit or reuse op[4] so EX stage\\ncan detect when the MDU is needed.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/mdu.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"New module: registered 2-cycle high-half multiplier for MULH/MULHU/\\nMULHSU plus a 32-cycle iterative divider for DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU.\\nIncludes start/busy/done handshake, ALTOPS substitutions under\\n`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS`, and exact RV32M corner-case handling.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Instantiate MDU, route operands to it, detect cold M-op via opcode\\nencoding, assert `ex_long_busy` while MDU is active, and select MDU\\nresult into EX/MEM when done.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Accept `ex_long_busy` alongside existing `dmem_ready` / `imem_ready`\\nstall sources. Treat MDU busy like a dmem stall: freeze IF/ID/EX\\nand bubble EX/MEM until the unit completes.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Wire the new `ex_long_busy` signal from ex_stage into hazard_unit.\\nNo top-level IO changes.\\n\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": \"regression\",\n  \"fitness\": 282.82,\n  \"delta_pct\": 0.0,\n  \"vs_baseline\": 0.0,\n  \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03,\n  \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06,\n  \"cycles\": 4491485,\n  \"iterations\": 10,\n  \"lut4\": 9563,\n  \"ff\": 1866,\n  \"seeds\": [\n    128.72,\n    127.03,\n    123.02\n  ],\n  \"formal_passed\": true,\n  \"cosim_passed\": true,\n  \"error\": null,\n  \"implementation_notes\": \"\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T10:45:00.160423Z\",\n  \"slot\": 1,\n  \"round_id\": 1\n}\n{\n  \"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r2s1\",\n  \"title\": \"Early branch and jump resolution in ID stage\",\n  \"category\": \"structural\",\n  \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline resolves all control-flow instructions in EX,\\ncausing a 2-cycle bubble for every taken branch and jump. CoreMark's\\ntight loops and frequent function calls spend a significant fraction of\\ncycles recovering from these mispredicts. Moving branch condition\\nevaluation and jump target computation to the ID stage cuts the penalty\\nto 1 cycle, directly improving iterations/cycle.\\n\",\n  \"hypothesis\": {\n    \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline resolves all control-flow instructions in EX,\\ncausing a 2-cycle bubble for every taken branch and jump. CoreMark's\\ntight loops and frequent function calls spend a significant fraction of\\ncycles recovering from these mispredicts. Moving branch condition\\nevaluation and jump target computation to the ID stage cuts the penalty\\nto 1 cycle, directly improving iterations/cycle.\\n\",\n    \"hypothesis\": \"Relocate unconditional jump (JAL/JALR) target calculation and conditional\\nbranch resolution from EX to ID. Add operand forwarding paths from\\nEX/MEM and MEM/WB into the ID stage so branches dependent on recent\\nresults resolve without stalling. Introduce a load-to-branch stall in\\nthe hazard unit when a branch in ID consumes a load result still in EX.\\nPipeline an early-redirect flag so EX does not re-assert flush on an\\ninstruction already redirected in ID.\\n\",\n    \"expected_impact\": {\n      \"fitness_delta_pct\": 8,\n      \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    \"changes\": [\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add early_redirect bit to id_ex_t pipeline bundle.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Insert branch target adder, branch condition comparator, and\\nforwarding muxes for rs1/rs2. Drive id_redirect and\\nid_redirect_target to IF stage.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Accept id_redirect/id_redirect_target and prioritize them over EX redirect.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Assert flush_if (but not flush_id) on id_redirect. Add\\nload-to-branch stall detection when a branch source matches a\\nload in EX.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Suppress redirect output when the id_ex_t early_redirect flag is set.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Wire id_redirect signals between stages and update forwarding connections.\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"expected_impact\": {\n    \"fitness_delta_pct\": 8,\n    \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n  },\n  \"changes\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add early_redirect bit to id_ex_t pipeline bundle.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Insert branch target adder, branch condition comparator, and\\nforwarding muxes for rs1/rs2. Drive id_redirect and\\nid_redirect_target to IF stage.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Accept id_redirect/id_redirect_target and prioritize them over EX redirect.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Assert flush_if (but not flush_id) on id_redirect. Add\\nload-to-branch stall detection when a branch source matches a\\nload in EX.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Suppress redirect output when the id_ex_t early_redirect flag is set.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Wire id_redirect signals between stages and update forwarding connections.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": \"regression\",\n  \"fitness\": 315.22,\n  \"delta_pct\": 0.0,\n  \"vs_baseline\": 11.46,\n  \"fmax_mhz\": 141.58,\n  \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06,\n  \"cycles\": 4491485,\n  \"iterations\": 10,\n  \"lut4\": 10217,\n  \"ff\": 1864,\n  \"seeds\": [\n    146.07,\n    134.99,\n    141.58\n  ],\n  \"formal_passed\": true,\n  \"cosim_passed\": true,\n  \"error\": null,\n  \"implementation_notes\": \"\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T11:12:30.258336Z\",\n  \"slot\": 1,\n  \"round_id\": 2\n}\n{\n  \"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r3s1\",\n  \"title\": \"Eliminate load-use stall with MEM-to-EX forwarding\",\n  \"category\": \"structural\",\n  \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline stalls ID by one cycle on every load-use\\nhazard (a LOAD in EX followed by an instruction in ID that reads the\\nLOAD's rd).  CoreMark's pointer-chasing, list-walk, and matrix-access\\npatterns contain a high density of back-to-back load-dependent ALU ops,\\nso this bubble is a significant IPC limiter.  Branch-related structural\\nchanges have already been exhausted with neutral or negative results;\\nthe data-forwarding network is the remaining untouched structural knob.\\nBy forwarding the sign/zero-extended load data directly from the\\ncombinational MEM-stage output to the EX-stage operand muxes, the\\ndependent instruction can enter EX in the cycle immediately after the\\nLOAD moves to MEM, eliminating the stall entirely.\\n\",\n  \"hypothesis\": {\n    \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline stalls ID by one cycle on every load-use\\nhazard (a LOAD in EX followed by an instruction in ID that reads the\\nLOAD's rd).  CoreMark's pointer-chasing, list-walk, and matrix-access\\npatterns contain a high density of back-to-back load-dependent ALU ops,\\nso this bubble is a significant IPC limiter.  Branch-related structural\\nchanges have already been exhausted with neutral or negative results;\\nthe data-forwarding network is the remaining untouched structural knob.\\nBy forwarding the sign/zero-extended load data directly from the\\ncombinational MEM-stage output to the EX-stage operand muxes, the\\ndependent instruction can enter EX in the cycle immediately after the\\nLOAD moves to MEM, eliminating the stall entirely.\\n\",\n    \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the load_use_hazard stall from the hazard unit and add a new\\nforwarding source from the MEM-stage load_data output to the EX-stage\\noperand muxes.\\n\\n1. In mem_stage.sv, expose the combinational load_data signal as an\\n   output port (fwd_load_data).\\n2. In forward_unit.sv, add a third forwarding priority:\\n   when the instruction in EX/MEM is a load (ex_mem_ctrl.mem_read) and\\n   its rd matches id_ex_rs1/rs2 (and rd != 0), assert a new select\\n   code (e.g. 2'b11) that picks fwd_load_data.\\n3. In ex_stage.sv, add fwd_mem_load_data input and extend the rs1/rs2\\n   muxes to select it under the new forwarding code.\\n4. In hazard_unit.sv, strip load_use_hazard out of stall_if, stall_id,\\n   and flush_id.  The remaining stall/flush reasons (imem/dmem stalls\\n   and EX redirects) are unchanged.\\n5. In core.sv, wire the new mem_stage output into ex_stage and\\n   forward_unit.\\n\\nThis keeps the RVFI retirement boundary at MEM/WB and does not alter\\ntrap behaviour, ISA decoding, or the nret=1 top-level port contract.\\nThe only timing risk is a longer combinational path from dmem_rdata\\nthrough the MEM load shifter to the EX ALU, but on the Tang Nano 20K\\nthe BRAM read delay plus byte-shift logic is expected to be comparable\\nto the existing ALU+branch path, so the IPC gain should dominate.\\n\",\n    \"expected_impact\": {\n      \"fitness_delta_pct\": 7,\n      \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    \"changes\": [\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Expose combinational load_data as output port fwd_load_data.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add third forwarding priority for MEM-stage load data (ex_mem_mem_read && ex_mem_rd match).\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load_data input and extend rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Remove load_use_hazard from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Wire new fwd_load_data port and forwarding selects between mem_stage, forward_unit, and ex_stage.\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"expected_impact\": {\n    \"fitness_delta_pct\": 7,\n    \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n  },\n  \"changes\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Expose combinational load_data as output port fwd_load_data.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add third forwarding priority for MEM-stage load data (ex_mem_mem_read && ex_mem_rd match).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load_data input and extend rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Remove load_use_hazard from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Wire new fwd_load_data port and forwarding selects between mem_stage, forward_unit, and ex_stage.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": \"broken\",\n  \"formal_passed\": false,\n  \"cosim_passed\": false,\n  \"error\": \"formal_failed: reg_ch0\\n0/trace.vcd\\nSBY  9:04:25 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:11  Writing trace to Verilog testbench: engine_0/trace_tb.v\\nSBY  9:04:25 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:11  Writing trace to constraints file: engine_0/trace.smtc\\nSBY  9:04:25 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:11  Writing trace to Yosys witness file: engine_0/trace.yw\\nSBY  9:04:25 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:11  Status: failed\\nSBY  9:04:25 [reg_ch0] engine_0: finished (returncode=1)\\nSBY  9:04:25 [reg_ch0] engine_0: Status returned by engin