{"type":"text","timestamp":1778778581068,"sessionID":"ses_1d88e88c8ffeinpauws2BWqQqd","part":{"id":"prt_e27771b81001wpXzV7zgiJagxD","messageID":"msg_e27770a41001eDXiwXENcjiGar","sessionID":"ses_1d88e88c8ffeinpauws2BWqQqd","type":"text","text":"Done. The hypothesis file has been written to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r10s2.yaml`\n\n**Summary of the proposal:**\n- **Category:** predictor\n- **Core idea:** Integrate a tiny target predictor into the existing 8-entry I-cache, predicting unconditional `JAL` and backward branches. The key fix vs. the prior zero-delta attempt is **tag-matched retention**: each prediction slot stores a partial tag (`pc[31:5]`) alongside the target, so the hit check naturally suppresses stale entries after evictions. This eliminates the bug where `pred_valid` was cleared on every cache refill, rendering predictions invisible.\n- **Why it should help:** It reuses the fast, registered I-cache read path (no slow `imem_data` combinational delay), costs mainly FFs (~250), and adds only a small next-pc mux. Correctly predicted JALs and loop-back edges remove the 2-cycle flush bubble without risking the Fmax crashes that killed earlier static/BTB predictors.\n- **Expected impact:** +5 % fitness (medium confidence).","time":{"start":1778778577793,"end":1778778581066}}}
