{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778779870634,"sessionID":"ses_1d875531fffeGkoitkHgyLbHLr","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"read:0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep3/cores/bench/LESSONS.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep3/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r1s0 (improvement, +11.46%): On inference FPGA targets, unconditionally computing wide multiply products inside the ALU keeps multiplier hardware on the combinational critical path for non-M opcodes; gating the multiply evaluation by opcode removes it from the fast path and raises Fmax with no IPC penalty.\n2: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r2s0 (regression, -8.01%): Pre-computing pc+4 in IF and pc+imm in ID to remove adders from EX backfires because the adders were previously hidden in parallel with the ALU's longer delay; moving them upstream creates new critical paths in lighter stages and worsens overall Fmax.\n3: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r3s1 (broken, n/a): MEM-to-EX load forwarding to eliminate load-use stalls fails rvfi_reg_check when the forwarded value doesn't exactly match the WB write value; the combinational forward path must replicate the full mem_stage byte-alignment and sign-extension logic, not forward raw dmem_rdata.\n4: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r4s1 (broken, n/a): MEM-to-EX load forwarding can reuse the existing forward_unit select encoding by muxing the fwd_ex_mem data source in core.sv; adding unused ports to forward_unit caused an implementation compile failure from unconnected inputs.\n5: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r4s2 (broken, n/a): Mispredict-only redirect broke rvfi_pc_fwd because ex_stage.sv still tied the architectural next-PC (and thus RVFI pc_wdata) to the redirect signal; when the BTB predicted correctly, redirect stayed low and the EX stage falsely reported PC+4 for taken branches/jumps instead of the actual target.\n6: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r5s0 (regression, -5.99%): Explicit opcode gating of divide/remainder operations regressed Fmax because FPGA synthesis tools already optimize case-statement divider inference, and the added opcode-comparison and pre-compute mux logic added combinational delay that outweighed any path reduction; timing micro-optimizations that work for multiplies do not automatically transfer to dividers.\n7: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r5s1 (improvement, +6.07%): A small direct-mapped I-cache in IF can hide imem stall cycles and raise IPC without touching the synthesis critical path, because FPGA zero-wait-state builds prune the dead cache-read combinational path yet the hit-miss logic still suppresses stalls in stall-aware simulation.\n8: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r5s2 (broken, n/a): A unified `predict_taken` bit used for both branches and jumps cannot be compared against `branch_taken` in the redirect condition because jumps are always taken yet `branch_taken` is zero for JAL; this causes a false mispredict redirect on every correctly predicted jump, corrupting the RVFI trace.\n9: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (broken, n/a): Replacing `next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target : pc+4` with pure prediction-based logic in IF breaks `pc_fwd` because the redirect path is omitted; on a mispredict the fetch PC advances to the predicted target while EX reports the corrected target, violating sequential PC continuity.\n10: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r7s0 (regression, +0.00%): Replicating mem_stage byte-alignment/sign-extension in a MEM-to-EX forwarding path and clearing load_use_hazard stalls produced zero fitness gain, indicating the one-cycle load-use penalty is either hidden by other pipeline bubbles or too infrequent in CoreMark to be the true IPC bottleneck.\n11: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r7s2 (regression, +0.00%): A tiny 8-entry direct-mapped BTB thrashes continuously on CoreMark's many active branch/jump sites; the mispredicts caused by aliasing evictions consume exactly the cycles saved by rare correct predictions, neutralizing any IPC gain over the always-not-taken baseline.\n12: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r8s0 (improvement, +18.48%): Opcode gating alone does not fully remove multiplier/divider inputs from the fast-path mux tree when heavy and light ops share a large case statement; explicitly splitting the ALU into fast and M-extension paths with a final 2:1 mux is required to truly shorten the critical path for base integer ops.\n13: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r10s2 (regression, +0.00%): Tag-matched predictor retention prevents state corruption on I-cache refill, but an 8-entry direct-mapped cache is too small to retain CoreMark's active branch instructions across loop iterations; the branch PC is evicted by the loop body itself before the next fetch, so `predict_taken` never qualifies on `icache_hit` and the integration yields zero IPC gain.\n\n(End of file - total 13 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r1s0 (improvement, +11.46%): On inference FPGA targets, unconditionally computing wide multiply products inside the ALU keeps multiplier hardware on the combinational critical path for non-M opcodes; gating the multiply evaluation by opcode removes it from the fast path and raises Fmax with no IPC penalty.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r2s0 (regression, -8.01%): Pre-computing pc+4 in IF and pc+imm in ID to remove adders from EX backfires because the adders were previously hidden in parallel with the ALU's longer delay; moving them upstream creates new critical paths in lighter stages and worsens overall Fmax.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r3s1 (broken, n/a): MEM-to-EX load forwarding to eliminate load-use stalls fails rvfi_reg_check when the forwarded value doesn't exactly match the WB write value; the combinational forward path must replicate the full mem_stage byte-alignment and sign-extension logic, not forward raw dmem_rdata.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r4s1 (broken, n/a): MEM-to-EX load forwarding can reuse the existing forward_unit select encoding by muxing the fwd_ex_mem data source in core.sv; adding unused ports to forward_unit caused an implementation compile failure from unconnected inputs.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r4s2 (broken, n/a): Mispredict-only redirect broke rvfi_pc_fwd because ex_stage.sv still tied the architectural next-PC (and thus RVFI pc_wdata) to the redirect signal; when the BTB predicted correctly, redirect stayed low and the EX stage falsely reported PC+4 for taken branches/jumps instead of the actual target.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r5s0 (regression, -5.99%): Explicit opcode gating of divide/remainder operations regressed Fmax because FPGA synthesis tools already optimize case-statement divider inference, and the added opcode-comparison and pre-compute mux logic added combinational delay that outweighed any path reduction; timing micro-optimizations that work for multiplies do not automatically transfer to dividers.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r5s1 (improvement, +6.07%): A small direct-mapped I-cache in IF can hide imem stall cycles and raise IPC without touching the synthesis critical path, because FPGA zero-wait-state builds prune the dead cache-read combinational path yet the hit-miss logic still suppresses stalls in stall-aware simulation.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r5s2 (broken, n/a): A unified `predict_taken` bit used for both branches and jumps cannot be compared against `branch_taken` in the redirect condition because jumps are always taken yet `branch_taken` is zero for JAL; this causes a false mispredict redirect on every correctly predicted jump, corrupting the RVFI trace.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (broken, n/a): Replacing `next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target : pc+4` with pure prediction-based logic in IF breaks `pc_fwd` because the redirect path is omitted; on a mispredict the fetch PC advances to the predicted target while EX reports the corrected target, violating sequential PC continuity.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r7s0 (regression, +0.00%): Replicating mem_stage byte-alignment/sign-extension in a MEM-to-EX forwarding path and clearing load_use_hazard stalls produced zero fitness gain, indicating the one-cycle load-use penalty is either hidden by other pipeline bubbles or too infrequent in CoreMark to be the true IPC bottleneck.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r7s2 (regression, +0.00%): A tiny 8-entry direct-mapped BTB thrashes continuously on CoreMark's many active branch/jump sites; the mispredicts caused by aliasing evictions consume exactly the cycles saved by rare correct predictions, neutralizing any IPC gain over the always-not-taken baseline.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r8s0 (improvement, +18.48%): Opcode gating alone does not fully remove multiplier/divider inputs from the fast-path mux tree when heavy and light ops share a large case statement; explicitly splitting the ALU into fast and M-extension paths with a final 2:1 mux is required to truly shorten the critical path for base integer ops.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r10s2 (regression, +0.00%): Tag-matched predictor retention prevents state corruption on I-cache refill, but an 8-entry direct-mapped cache is too small to retain CoreMark's active branch instructions across loop iterations; the branch PC is evicted by the loop body itself before the next fetch, so `predict_taken` never qualifies on `icache_hit` and the integration yields zero IPC gain.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778779870609,"end":1778779870632}},"id":"prt_e278ad18a001X3AZqBjJN3IGAL","sessionID":"ses_1d875531fffeGkoitkHgyLbHLr","messageID":"msg_e278aaec1001gNoQ5Vbx2LZ2oz"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778779871587,"sessionID":"ses_1d875531fffeGkoitkHgyLbHLr","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"grep:1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"predictor","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep3/cores/bench/experiments","include":"*.jsonl"},"output":"Found 10 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"32-entry 2-bit dynamic branch predictor in IF stage\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline always fetches pc+4 and only redirects after a branch resolves in EX,\\ncosting a 2-cycle bubble for every taken branch. CoreMark is loop-heavy; even a\\nsimple dynamic predictor eliminates most of these bubbles, directly improving IPC.\\nA 32-entry PHT adds only 64 flops and a small combinational read port, well within\\nthe ~400 LUT4 headroom on the Tang Nano 20K.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline always fetches pc+4 and only redirects after a branch resolves in EX,\\ncosting a 2-cycle bubble for every taken branch. CoreMark is loop-heavy; even a\\nsimple dynamic predictor eliminates most of these bubbles, directly improving IPC.\\nA 32-entry PHT adds only 64 flops and a small combinational read port, well within\\nthe ~400 LUT4 headroom on the Tang Nano 20K.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry 2-bit saturating counter branch predictor (PHT) indexed by PC[6:2].\\nIn the IF stage, detect conditional branches (opcode 1100011) and JAL (opcode 1101111);\\nextract the immediate via a small imm_gen instance and compute target = pc + imm.\\nQuery the PHT for branches; always predict JAL as taken. A new predict_taken bit is\\nadded to the IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles. In EX, redirect is asserted only on\\nmispredict (predicted != actual outcome), with the redirect target selecting the\\ncorrect path (branch target or pc+4). The PHT is updated when a branch resolves in EX.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predict_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline structs.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/branch_predictor.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-entry 2-bit saturating counter PHT module with async read and synchronous update.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add branch/JAL detection, imm_gen instance, target adder, and predictor integ...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Static backward-taken predictor with early JAL resolution in IF\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline fetches sequentially and resolves all control flow in EX,\\nincurring a 2-cycle bubble for every taken branch and unconditional jump.\\nCoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward conditional branches (loop edges)\\ndominate the dynamic branch count. A purely static predictor that predicts\\nJAL as always-taken and backward branches as taken requires no stateful\\ntable, no PHT updates, and minimal combinational logic in the IF stage.\\nBecause the prediction is computed from the instruction already on the\\nimem_data bus, the target can be fetched immediately\\u2014eliminating the\\nredirect bubble entirely for correct predictions.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline fetches sequentially and resolves all control flow in EX,\\nincurring a 2-cycle bubble for every taken branch and unconditional jump.\\nCoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward conditional branches (loop edges)\\ndominate the dynamic branch count. A purely static predictor that predicts\\nJAL as always-taken and backward branches as taken requires no stateful\\ntable, no PHT updates, and minimal combinational logic in the IF stage.\\nBecause the prediction is computed from the instruction already on the\\nimem_data bus, the target can be fetched immediately\\u2014eliminating the\\nredirect bubble entirely for correct predictions.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add combinational branch/jump prediction to the IF stage and suppress\\nEX-stage redirects when the prediction is correct.\\n\\n1. Extend if_id_t and id_ex_t with a single predict_taken bit.\\n2. In if_stage, instantiate a small imm_gen (or inline equivalent) to\\n   extract the B/J immediate from imem_data. Detect opcode 1100011\\n   (BRANCH) and 1101111 (JAL). Predict taken for JAL unconditionally,\\n   and for branches when the immediate sign bit is 1 (backward branch).\\n   On a predicted-taken instruction, redirect next_pc...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"32-entry direct-mapped BTB in IF stage to eliminate taken-branch bubbles\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline always fetches sequentially, paying a 2-cycle bubble for every\\ntaken branch and JAL. A prior static predictor that computed branch targets\\ncombinationally in IF from imem_data (decode -> imm_gen -> adder) slashed\\nFmax by ~40% because that path starts from the off-chip/BRAM instruction\\nword. A Branch Target Buffer (BTB) avoids that path entirely: it is indexed\\ndirectly by the PC register output, so the predicted next PC is just a small\\ndistributed-RAM read with no instruction decode or adder in the critical\\npath. On the Tang Nano 20K a 32-entry BTB costs only ~35 LUTs and reads in\\na single LUT delay, making it a much safer timing bet while still removing\\nthe branch bubble for loop-back edges once they warm up.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline always fetches sequentially, paying a 2-cycle bubble for every\\ntaken branch and JAL. A prior static predictor that computed branch targets\\ncombinationally in IF from imem_data (decode -> imm_gen -> adder) slashed\\nFmax by ~40% because that path starts from the off-chip/BRAM instruction\\nword. A Branch Target Buffer (BTB) avoids that path entirely: it is indexed\\ndirectly by the PC register output, so the predicted next PC is just a small\\ndistributed-RAM read with no instruction decode or adder in the critical\\npath. On the Tang Nano 20K a 32-entry BTB costs only ~35 LUTs and reads in\\na single LUT delay, making it a much safer timing bet while still removing\\nthe branch bubble for loop-back edges once they warm up.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped BTB to the IF stage.\\n- Read: combinational, indexed by pc[6:2], outputs hit and target[31:0].\\n- Write: registered in EX when a conditional branch or JAL is resolved\\n  taken, storing pc[6:2] -> target.\\n- IF stage: next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target : btb_hit ? btb_target : ...\n  Line 13: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"64-entry tagged BTB inlined in IF with mispredict-only redirect\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Dynamic profiling shows CoreMark executes ~360k taken control-flow\\ninstructions (branches + JAL + JALR) out of 2.9M total instructions.\\nThe baseline always predicts not-taken, paying a 2-cycle bubble for\\nevery one of them.  Eliminating these bubbles would cut ~718k cycles\\nfrom the 4.5M-cycle run, yielding a ~16% IPC improvement.\\n\\nA prior 32-entry direct-mapped BTB attempt produced exactly zero\\nfitness delta with identical LUT/Fmax numbers, strongly suggesting the\\nBTB was synthesized away because the update path or the next-pc mux\\nwas not wired correctly.  This hypothesis inlines the BTB directly\\ninto if_stage.sv (no separate module to forget to instantiate), adds\\na partial tag to avoid aliasing, and explicitly spells out the exact\\nnext-pc expression and the pc+4 mispredict-recovery path so the\\nimplementation agent cannot leave it as a no-op.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Dynamic profiling shows CoreMark executes ~360k taken control-flow\\ninstructions (branches + JAL + JALR) out of 2.9M total instructions.\\nThe baseline always predicts not-taken, paying a 2-cycle bubble for\\nevery one of them.  Eliminating these bubbles would cut ~718k cycles\\nfrom the 4.5M-cycle run, yielding a ~16% IPC improvement.\\n\\nA prior 32-entry direct-mapped BTB attempt produced exactly zero\\nfitness delta with identical LUT/Fmax numbers, strongly suggesting the\\nBTB was synthesized away because the update path or the next-pc mux\\nwas not wired correctly.  This hypothesis inlines the BTB directly\\ninto if_stage.sv (no separate module to forget to instantiate), adds\\na partial tag to avoid aliasing, and explicitly spells out the exact\\nnext-pc expression and the pc+4 mispredict-recovery path so the\\nimplementation agent cannot leave it as a no-op.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Inline a 64-entry direct-mapped branch-target buffer into the IF ...\n  Line 16: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"16-entry inlined BTB with explicit RVFI-safe mispredict-only redirect\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline pays a 2-cycle bubble for every taken branch and JAL because\\nit always fetches PC+4 and redirects only after EX resolution. Prior\\nattempts to add a BTB either produced zero fitness delta (identical LUT/FF\\ncounts prove the structure was synthesized away because the update path was\\ndisconnected) or broke rvfi_pc_fwd (the implementation agent altered\\nEX/MEM.pc_next to depend on redirect, so a correct prediction reported\\nPC+4 instead of the actual target). A very small, explicitly inlined BTB\\navoids module-instantiation mistakes, and spelling out the exact combinational\\nchanges in ex_stage.sv with a bold \\u201cdo not touch pc_next\\u201d rule should finally\\nlet the predictor actually fire without corrupting the architectural trace.\\nCoreMark is loop-heavy; even a 16-entry table should capture the handful of\\nhot backward edges and JAL targets that dominate dynamic control flow.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline pays a 2-cycle bubble for every taken branch and JAL because\\nit always fetches PC+4 and redirects only after EX resolution. Prior\\nattempts to add a BTB either produced zero fitness delta (identical LUT/FF\\ncounts prove the structure was synthesized away because the update path was\\ndisconnected) or broke rvfi_pc_fwd (the implementation agent altered\\nEX/MEM.pc_next to depend on redirect, so a correct prediction reported\\nPC+4 instead of the actual target). A very small, explicitly inlined BTB\\navoids module-instantiation mistakes, and spelling out the exact combinational\\nchanges in ex_stage.sv with a bold \\u201cdo not touch pc_next\\u201d rule should finally\\nlet the predictor actually fire without corrupting the architectural trace.\\nCoreMark is loop-heavy; even a 16-entry table should capture the handful of\\nhot backward edges and JAL targets that dominate dynamic control fl...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Static BTFN predictor in IF with mispredict-only redirect in EX\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline always predicts not-taken, paying a 2-cycle flush penalty on every\\ntaken branch and every JAL. CoreMark is loop-heavy and makes frequent function\\ncalls, so backward branches and JALs are a large fraction of dynamic control-flow.\\nA stateless Backward-Taken / Forward-Not-taken (BTFN) predictor costs almost no\\nstate, adds only a small amount of combinational logic in the IF stage, and can\\neliminate the flush penalty on loop back-edges and unconditional jumps.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline always predicts not-taken, paying a 2-cycle flush penalty on every\\ntaken branch and every JAL. CoreMark is loop-heavy and makes frequent function\\ncalls, so backward branches and JALs are a large fraction of dynamic control-flow.\\nA stateless Backward-Taken / Forward-Not-taken (BTFN) predictor costs almost no\\nstate, adds only a small amount of combinational logic in the IF stage, and can\\neliminate the flush penalty on loop back-edges and unconditional jumps.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a BTFN predictor to the IF stage:\\n  - JAL is always predicted taken (target = PC + JAL imm, known in IF).\\n  - Conditional branches are predicted taken only when their immediate is negative\\n    (backward branch), otherwise not-taken.\\n  - JALR is not predicted (falls through) because the target depends on a register\\n    value not visible in IF.\\n  - The predicted target is validated in the same cycle it is produced; if the\\n    computed target is misaligned ([1:0] != 0) the prediction is suppressed and\\n    IF falls back to PC+4, matching the trap-and-fallthrough semantics.\\n\\nChange the EX-stage redirect semantics from \\\"taken branch/jump\\\" to \\\"mispredict\\\":\\n  - EX always computes the architecturally correct next-PC (pc_next / pc_wdata)\\n    from the actual branch/jump resolution, independent of prediction.\\n  - redirec...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"8-entry PC-indexed BTB with isolated mispredict redirect\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline pays a 2-cycle flush penalty for every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause it always fetches PC+4.  Dynamic profiling shows CoreMark executes\\n~360k taken control-flow instructions out of ~2.9M total, so removing these\\nbubbles could cut ~720k cycles (~16% IPC gain).  Prior BTB attempts either\\nproduced zero delta (update path disconnected) or broke rvfi_pc_fwd because\\nthe implementation agent altered EX/MEM.pc_next to depend on prediction.\\nA tiny 8-entry BTB indexed directly by the PC register avoids the slow\\nimem_data-decode path that killed an earlier static predictor's Fmax, and\\nkeeping the BTB inline in if_stage makes it impossible to forget to\\ninstantiate a separate module.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline pays a 2-cycle flush penalty for every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause it always fetches PC+4.  Dynamic profiling shows CoreMark executes\\n~360k taken control-flow instructions out of ~2.9M total, so removing these\\nbubbles could cut ~720k cycles (~16% IPC gain).  Prior BTB attempts either\\nproduced zero delta (update path disconnected) or broke rvfi_pc_fwd because\\nthe implementation agent altered EX/MEM.pc_next to depend on prediction.\\nA tiny 8-entry BTB indexed directly by the PC register avoids the slow\\nimem_data-decode path that killed an earlier static predictor's Fmax, and\\nkeeping the BTB inline in if_stage makes it impossible to forget to\\ninstantiate a separate module.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an 8-entry direct-mapped branch-target buffer inline in if_stage.sv,\\nindexed by pc[4:2] with a 27-bit tag (pc[31:5]).  Combinational read produces\\nbtb_hit and btb_target.  Only BRANCH (opcode 1100011) and JAL (opcode\\n1101111) are eligible for prediction; JALR is excluded.  The IF next-pc mux\\nbecomes:\\n  next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target :\\n            (btb_hit && is_branch_or_jal) ? btb_tar...\n  Line 25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"2-entry return-address stack for JALR prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline pays a 2-cycle flush bubble for every taken JALR (function return).\\nCoreMark is call-heavy, so returns are a significant fraction of dynamic control flow.\\nPrior BTB attempts either thrashed (8-entry) or were synthesized away (implementation bugs),\\nand static BTFN predictors destroyed Fmax by adding an imem_data->adder->next_pc critical path.\\nA tiny 2-entry RAS predicts returns with near-perfect accuracy, avoids an IF-stage adder entirely,\\nand targets a different instruction class (returns vs branches) than all previous predictor attempts.\\nCorrectly predicted returns eliminate the flush bubble, directly improving IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline pays a 2-cycle flush bubble for every taken JALR (function return).\\nCoreMark is call-heavy, so returns are a significant fraction of dynamic control flow.\\nP