{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778780557910,"sessionID":"ses_1d875531fffeGkoitkHgyLbHLr","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"write:12","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"id: hyp-20260514-003-r11s2\ntitle: 16-entry tagged target predictor with stored predict_taken bit\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The baseline still flushes IF/ID on every taken JAL and backward branch,\n  costing two cycles each.  All prior predictor attempts in this core failed\n  for one of three reasons: (1) decoding external imem_data in IF destroyed\n  Fmax, (2) altering EX pc_next based on prediction broke rvfi_pc_fwd, or\n  (3) integrating the predictor with the 8-entry I-cache made it depend on\n  icache_hit, but the branch instruction was evicted by the loop body before\n  the next fetch so the predictor never fired.  A standalone tagged predictor\n  that stores its own eligibility bit avoids all three pitfalls: no slow\n  instruction-decode path, no EX pc_next changes, and no dependence on the\n  I-cache.  Doubling capacity to 16 entries further reduces the thrashing\n  that neutralised the earlier 8-entry BTB.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a 16-entry direct-mapped tagged target predictor (tiny BTB) to the IF\n  stage.  Each entry stores valid, a 26-bit tag (pc[31:6]), a 32-bit target,\n  and a predict_taken bit.  The predict_taken bit is set at update time only\n  for JAL and taken backward branches, so IF never needs to decode the\n  instruction (no imem_data or icache_data in the prediction path).  This\n  eliminates both the Fmax crash caused by external-imem decode and the zero-\n  IPC failure caused by I-cache eviction of branch instructions.\n\n  Predictor read path (registered, fast):\n    pred_idx  = pc[5:2];\n    pred_tag  = pc[31:6];\n    pred_hit  = pred_valid[pred_idx] && (pred_tag_stored == pred_tag);\n    predict_taken = pred_hit && pred_taken[pred_idx] && !flush && !redirect;\n    next_pc   = redirect ? redirect_target\n              : predict_taken ? pred_target[pred_idx]\n              : pc + 32'd4;\n\n  Update path (driven combinationaly from EX, registered in IF):\n    pred_update fires for (JAL || taken backward branch) && !misalign_fault.\n    On pred_update write valid=1, tag, target, and taken=1 into the entry\n    at pc[5:2].\n\n  EX-stage mispredict-only redirect:\n    - Keep the EX/MEM pc_next register assignment completely untouched.\n    - actual_taken = in.ctrl.is_jump || branch_taken;\n    - redirect = ((!in.predict_taken && actual_taken) ||\n                  (in.predict_taken && (!actual_taken || misalign_fault)))\n                 && !misalign_fault;\n    - redirect_target recovers to pc+4 on not-taken or misalign:\n        redirect_target = misalign_fault ? (in.pc + 32'd4) :\n                          !actual_taken  ? (in.pc + 32'd4) :\n                          in.ctrl.is_jump ? jump_target : branch_target;\n\n  The 16-entry capacity (double the prior 8-entry tables) reduces conflict\n  misses on CoreMark's many active branch sites, while tag matching avoids\n  aliasing false-hits.  Because the critical path remains in the ALU fast\n  path, Fmax impact should be negligible.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 5\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: |\n      Add a single `logic predict_taken;` field to both `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t`\n      pipeline bundles so the prediction flag travels with the instruction.\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: |\n      1. Add 16-entry predictor arrays: `pred_valid[0:15]`,\n         `pred_tag[0:15][25:0]`, `pred_target[0:15][31:0]`, `pred_taken[0:15]`.\n      2. Add new inputs: `pred_update`, `pred_update_idx[3:0]`,\n         `pred_update_tag[25:0]`, `pred_update_target[31:0]`,\n         `pred_update_taken`.\n      3. On reset clear all `pred_valid`.\n      4. On `pred_update` write `pred_valid[idx] <= 1'b1`,\n         `pred_tag[idx] <= pred_update_tag`,\n         `pred_target[idx] <= pred_update_target`,\n         `pred_taken[idx] <= pred_update_taken`.\n      5. Combinational prediction:\n           `pred_idx  = pc[5:2];`\n           `pred_tag_in = pc[31:6];`\n           `pred_hit = pred_valid[pred_idx] && (pred_tag[pred_idx] == pred_tag_in);`\n           `predict_taken = pred_hit && pred_taken[pred_idx] && !flush && !redirect;`\n           `next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target\n                    : predict_taken ? pred_target[pred_idx]\n                    : pc + 32'd4;`\n      6. Drive `out.predict_taken = predict_taken`.\n      7. Keep all existing I-cache logic completely unchanged.\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: |\n      Capture `in.predict_taken` into the ID/EX register so it reaches EX stage.\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: |\n      1. Read `in.predict_taken` from the ID/EX register.\n      2. Compute `actual_taken = in.ctrl.is_jump || branch_taken;`.\n      3. Replace unconditional redirect with mispredict-only redirect:\n           `redirect = ((!in.predict_taken && actual_taken) ||\n                       (in.predict_taken && (!actual_taken || misalign_fault)))\n                      && !misalign_fault;`\n      4. Drive `redirect_target` so a predicted-taken / not-taken mispredict\n         recovers to pc+4, and a misaligned jump/branch also recovers to pc+4:\n           `redirect_target = misalign_fault          ? (in.pc + 32'd4) :\n                              !actual_taken           ? (in.pc + 32'd4) :\n                              in.ctrl.is_jump         ? jump_target :\n                                                        branch_target;`\n      5. Leave the EX/MEM `pc_next` register assignment completely untouched.\n      6. Add combinational update outputs:\n           `pred_update = !misalign_fault && in.valid &&\n                          ((in.ctrl.is_jump && !in.ctrl.is_jalr) ||\n                           (in.ctrl.is_branch && branch_taken && in.imm[31]));`\n           `pred_update_idx    = in.pc[5:2];`\n           `pred_update_tag    = in.pc[31:6];`\n           `pred_update_target = redirect_target;`\n           `pred_update_taken  = 1'b1;`\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: |\n      1. Wire the five `pred_update*` outputs from `u_ex` to the new inputs on\n         `u_if` so the predictor is updated when JALs or taken backward branches\n         resolve.\n      2. Pass `predict_taken` through the existing `if_id_t` connection to `u_id`.\n      3. No other top-level changes needed.\n","filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r11s2.yaml"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r11s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r11s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778780557897,"end":1778780557909}},"id":"prt_e2794d1080013duaVcy1FnYziK","sessionID":"ses_1d875531fffeGkoitkHgyLbHLr","messageID":"msg_e27946bd8001FSq0yztmi5eO8V"}}
