{"type":"text","timestamp":1778756329330,"sessionID":"ses_1d9e1a778ffeEgB7IWjbFuvIaA","part":{"id":"prt_e262388c50010lRi5clh0TRJt5","messageID":"msg_e262373da002vuUvHDaqukA3HE","sessionID":"ses_1d9e1a778ffeEgB7IWjbFuvIaA","type":"text","text":"Done. I wrote the hypothesis to:\n\n```\ncores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r2s2.yaml\n```\n\n**Summary:** A **static backward-taken predictor with early JAL resolution in IF**.\n\n- **Why:** The baseline incurs a 2-cycle bubble for every taken branch/jump because it always fetches `pc+4` and only redirects from EX. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward branches dominate.\n- **How:** In `if_stage`, detect `JAL` (always taken) and backward `BRANCH` (negative offset) combinationally from `imem_data`, compute `pc+imm`, and redirect the fetch immediately. Pass a `predict_taken` bit through the pipeline. In `ex_stage`, only assert `redirect` on a mispredict (actual outcome ≠ prediction) or unpredicted jumps (`JALR`).\n- **Edge over the broken attempt:** The prior `hyp-20260514-003-r1s2` used a 32-entry dynamic PHT with state updates and much more complex control; this version is purely combinational, stateless, and much lower bug risk.","time":{"start":1778756323525,"end":1778756329329}}}
