{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778758245013,"sessionID":"ses_1d9c3c403ffe4Rle1T60QoHOUK","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"read:5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r3s2.yaml"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r3s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260514-003-r3s2\n2: title: 32-entry direct-mapped BTB in IF stage to eliminate taken-branch bubbles\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The baseline always fetches sequentially, paying a 2-cycle bubble for every\n6:   taken branch and JAL. A prior static predictor that computed branch targets\n7:   combinationally in IF from imem_data (decode -> imm_gen -> adder) slashed\n8:   Fmax by ~40% because that path starts from the off-chip/BRAM instruction\n9:   word. A Branch Target Buffer (BTB) avoids that path entirely: it is indexed\n10:   directly by the PC register output, so the predicted next PC is just a small\n11:   distributed-RAM read with no instruction decode or adder in the critical\n12:   path. On the Tang Nano 20K a 32-entry BTB costs only ~35 LUTs and reads in\n13:   a single LUT delay, making it a much safer timing bet while still removing\n14:   the branch bubble for loop-back edges once they warm up.\n15: hypothesis: |\n16:   Add a 32-entry direct-mapped BTB to the IF stage.\n17:   - Read: combinational, indexed by pc[6:2], outputs hit and target[31:0].\n18:   - Write: registered in EX when a conditional branch or JAL is resolved\n19:     taken, storing pc[6:2] -> target.\n20:   - IF stage: next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target : btb_hit ? btb_target : pc+4.\n21:   - Pipeline a predict_taken bit (= btb_hit) through IF/ID and ID/EX.\n22:   - EX stage: mispredict = (predict_taken != actual_taken). Redirect only on\n23:     mispredict; correct BTB hits flow through with zero bubble. JALR is never\n24:     predicted (target depends on rs1).\n25:   CoreMark's inner loops quickly warm the BTB, after which every loop-back\n26:   branch costs zero bubbles instead of two. The BTB read path is shorter than\n27:   the previous static predictor's imem_data->decode->adder path, so Fmax\n28:   impact should be minimal.\n29: expected_impact:\n30:   fitness_delta_pct: 8\n31:   confidence: medium\n32: changes:\n33:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n34:     description: Add predict_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline structs.\n35:   - file: rtl/btb.sv\n36:     description: New 32-entry direct-mapped branch target buffer. Combinational\n37:       read indexed by pc[6:2]; registered write on taken branch/jump resolution\n38:       from EX. Each entry holds a valid bit and a 30-bit word-aligned target.\n39:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n40:     description: Query the BTB with the current PC. Drive next_pc to btb_target\n41:       on a hit, otherwise pc+4. Set out.predict_taken when the BTB hits.\n42:   - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n43:     description: Latch in.predict_taken into the ID/EX register so it reaches\n44:       EX stage.\n45:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n46:     description: Compare predicted vs actual branch/jump outcome and assert\n47:       redirect only on mispredict. Drive BTB update signals (update_en,\n48:       update_pc, update_target) for taken branches and JAL.\n49:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n50:     description: Instantiate the BTB module, wire its read ports to the IF\n51:       stage, and wire its update ports from the EX stage. Pass predict_taken\n52:       through the pipeline bundles.\n\n(End of file - total 52 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260514-003-r3s2\ntitle: 32-entry direct-mapped BTB in IF stage to eliminate taken-branch bubbles\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The baseline always fetches sequentially, paying a 2-cycle bubble for every\n  taken branch and JAL. A prior static predictor that computed branch targets\n  combinationally in IF from imem_data (decode -> imm_gen -> adder) slashed\n  Fmax by ~40% because that path starts from the off-chip/BRAM instruction\n  word. A Branch Target Buffer (BTB) avoids that path entirely: it is indexed\n  directly by the PC register output, so the predicted next PC is just a small\n  distributed-RAM read with no instruction decode or adder in the critical\n  path. On the Tang Nano 20K a 32-entry BTB costs only ~35 LUTs and reads in\n  a single LUT delay, making it a much safer timing bet while still removing\n  the branch bubble for loop-back edges once they warm up.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a 32-entry direct-mapped BTB to the IF stage.\n  - Read: combinational, indexed by pc[6:2], outputs hit and target[31:0].\n  - Write: registered in EX when a conditional branch or JAL is resolved\n    taken, storing pc[6:2] -> target.\n  - IF stage: next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target : btb_hit ? btb_target : pc+4.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r3s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778758245005,"end":1778758245013}},"id":"prt_e2640d311002To5Q9wrgJUgbC1","sessionID":"ses_1d9c3c403ffe4Rle1T60QoHOUK","messageID":"msg_e2640b5b8001Ipupx1yZ5yN3o9"}}
