{"type":"text","timestamp":1778758269773,"sessionID":"ses_1d9c3c403ffe4Rle1T60QoHOUK","part":{"id":"prt_e26411193001fPIQfrMN3zeQjc","messageID":"msg_e2640e448001jQeuveq2sLqI59","sessionID":"ses_1d9c3c403ffe4Rle1T60QoHOUK","type":"text","text":"Done. I wrote the hypothesis YAML to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r3s2.yaml`\n\n**Summary of the hypothesis:**\n\n- **Category:** predictor\n- **Idea:** Add a **32-entry direct-mapped Branch Target Buffer (BTB)** indexed by `pc[6:2]` in the IF stage.\n- **Why it should work:** The previous static predictor failed because it computed branch targets from `imem_data` in IF (`imem_data → decode → imm_gen → adder`), creating a path from the instruction memory output back to the PC register that slashed Fmax by ~40%. A BTB avoids that entirely: it stores previously-seen targets in a tiny distributed RAM and is indexed directly by the PC register, so the predicted next PC is just a fast RAM read (`pc → LUT-RAM → mux`) with no instruction decode or adder on the critical path.\n- **Expected impact:** CoreMark's tight loops warm the BTB quickly; after that, every loop-back branch costs **zero bubbles** instead of two. At ~20% branch/jump density, this should improve IPC by 5–10% while adding minimal timing delay (~35 LUTs, single LUT read delay). Net fitness gain target: **+8%**.","time":{"start":1778758259091,"end":1778758269771}}}
