{"type":"text","timestamp":1778773154308,"sessionID":"ses_1d8e75fe8ffeCsElbBK3KfZMTR","part":{"id":"prt_e27243d7e001yc6oCOBdEWJEdJ","messageID":"msg_e2724070f001Okn4iyUXyyvcVO","sessionID":"ses_1d8e75fe8ffeCsElbBK3KfZMTR","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r8s2.yaml`\n\n**Summary of the proposal:** a **2-entry Return Address Stack (RAS)** that predicts `jalr ra` (function returns) in the IF stage. Key design choices that avoid the failure modes of previous predictor attempts:\n\n- **No adder in IF** — the RAS stores return addresses directly, avoiding the `imem_data → imm_gen → adder → next_pc` path that killed Fmax in the static-BTFN attempts.\n- **No BTB thrashing** — returns are a tiny, highly predictable subset of control flow; a 2-entry stack captures most CoreMark call/return patterns without aliasing.\n- **pc_fwd-safe** — `if_stage.next_pc` keeps its original `redirect ? redirect_target : pc+4` shape; the combined redirect is muxed at the top level in `core.sv`, so EX-stage `pc_next` remains architecturally correct and untouched.\n- **Mispredict-only redirect in EX** — a 32-bit target comparator in `ex_stage` verifies RAS predictions; on a correct prediction `redirect` stays low and no flush bubble is inserted.","time":{"start":1778773147006,"end":1778773154306}}}
