{"type":"text","timestamp":1778776942439,"sessionID":"ses_1d8b3b5a5ffeXLTooDKsTP5DiN","part":{"id":"prt_e275e03ac001iOrsl0Det7vSR5","messageID":"msg_e275def77001qMWFMRdpQJ1uvE","sessionID":"ses_1d8b3b5a5ffeXLTooDKsTP5DiN","type":"text","text":"Done. Wrote `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r9s2.yaml`.\n\n**Summary of the hypothesis:**\n\n- **Category:** predictor\n- **Core idea:** Integrate a tiny branch-target predictor into the existing 8-entry I-cache. Each cache line gets a `pred_valid` bit and 32-bit `pred_target`. Only unconditional `JAL` and backward branches are predicted, avoiding the thrashing that killed the prior standalone BTB.\n- **Why it should avoid prior pitfalls:**\n  1. **Fmax-safe:** All prediction logic reads the *cached* instruction inside `if_stage`—it never creates the long `io_imemData → core.sv → IF` combinational path that slashed Fmax to 70 MHz in the RAS attempt.\n  2. **rvfi_pc_fwd-safe:** Redirect becomes *mispredict-only*; EX/MEM `pc_next` is left completely untouched, so architectural next-PC is always independent of prediction state.\n  3. **Thrashing-safe:** By predicting only `JAL` (always taken, stable target) and backward branches (loop back-edges), the 8-entry table concentrates on highly repetitive patterns instead of aliasing across all control-flow sites.\n- **Expected impact:** +8 % fitness (medium confidence), driven by 5–10 % IPC improvement from eliminating flush bubbles on loops and function calls, with minimal Fmax impact because the critical path should remain in the ALU fast path.","time":{"start":1778776933292,"end":1778776942437}}}
